1
00:00:24,300 --> 00:00:32,425
The film "DOGVILLE" as told
in nine chapters and a prologue.

2
00:00:33,467 --> 00:00:40,425
PROLOGUE (which introduces us
to the town and its residents)

3
00:00:43,074 --> 00:00:46,111
<i>This is the sad tale
of the township of Dogville.</i>

4
00:00:47,741 --> 00:00:51,197
<i>Dogville was in the Rocky
Mountains in the US of A,</i>

5
00:00:51,741 --> 00:00:54,368
<i>up here where the road
came to its definitive end</i>

6
00:00:54,807 --> 00:00:58,024
<i>near the entrance to the old
abandoned silver mine.</i>

7
00:00:58,541 --> 00:01:01,558
<i>The residents of Dogville
were good honest folks,</i>

8
00:01:02,041 --> 00:01:04,179
<i>and they liked their township.</i>

9
00:01:04,541 --> 00:01:06,619
<i>And while a sentimental soul
from the East Coast</i>

10
00:01:06,974 --> 00:01:09,432
<i>had once dubbed
their main street Elm Street,</i>

11
00:01:09,840 --> 00:01:12,618
<i>though no elm had ever
cast its shadow in Dogville,</i>

12
00:01:13,074 --> 00:01:15,382
<i>they saw no reason
to change anything.</i>

13
00:01:16,907 --> 00:01:19,395
<i>Most of the buildings
were pretty wretched,</i>

14
00:01:19,807 --> 00:01:22,145
<i>more like shacks, frankly.</i>

15
00:01:22,541 --> 00:01:25,408
<i>The house in which Tom lived
was the best, though,</i>

16
00:01:25,874 --> 00:01:29,351
<i>and in good times, might almost
have passed for presentable.</i>

17
00:01:30,907 --> 00:01:34,594
<i>That afternoon,
the radio was playing softly</i>

18
00:01:35,174 --> 00:01:38,161
<i>for in his dotage,
Thomas Edison, Sr.</i>

19
00:01:38,641 --> 00:01:42,267
<i>had developed a weakness
for music of the lighter kind.</i>

20
00:01:44,041 --> 00:01:46,039
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>

21
00:01:46,174 --> 00:01:49,271
<i>- the President of the United States.
- My friends...</i>

22
00:01:49,774 --> 00:01:51,852
<i>Tom, do me a favor, will you?</i>

23
00:01:52,208 --> 00:01:54,106
<i>The radio?</i>

24
00:01:54,107 --> 00:01:56,105
Just because the music's over

25
00:01:56,374 --> 00:01:58,372
and you might risk hearing
something useful?

26
00:01:58,608 --> 00:02:00,715
I thought that's
why we had the radio.

27
00:02:01,074 --> 00:02:03,681
Well, I need to rest, as you know.

28
00:02:05,374 --> 00:02:07,801
Mock me if you like.

29
00:02:08,208 --> 00:02:10,206
<i>Tom's father had been a doctor</i>

30
00:02:10,341 --> 00:02:12,339
<i>and now received a modest pension.</i>

31
00:02:12,674 --> 00:02:15,542
<i>So it was no great disaster
for Tom to drift about</i>

32
00:02:16,007 --> 00:02:18,405
<i>not doing anything in particular.</i>

33
00:02:18,807 --> 00:02:20,805
<i>Tom was a writer...</i>

34
00:02:21,107 --> 00:02:23,295
<i>at any rate, by his own rights.</i>

35
00:02:23,674 --> 00:02:27,621
<i>His output as committed to paper
was so far limited to the words</i>

36
00:02:28,241 --> 00:02:30,239
<i>"great" and "small,"</i>

37
00:02:30,341 --> 00:02:32,339
<i>followed by a question mark,</i>

38
00:02:32,474 --> 00:02:34,472
<i>but nevertheless
meticulously archived</i>

39
00:02:34,807 --> 00:02:37,525
<i>in one of his many bureau drawers.</i>

40
00:02:39,041 --> 00:02:40,940
Bye, Dad.

41
00:02:45,241 --> 00:02:47,239
Evenin', Master Tom!

42
00:02:47,441 --> 00:02:49,439
Evening, Master Olivia.

43
00:02:49,508 --> 00:02:51,506
You don't forget
about the meeting tomorrow.

44
00:02:51,707 --> 00:02:53,705
No.

45
00:02:58,141 --> 00:03:00,139
<i>In order to postpone the time</i>

46
00:03:00,374 --> 00:03:02,681
<i>at which he would have
to put pen to paper in earnest,</i>

47
00:03:03,074 --> 00:03:06,111
<i>Tom had now come up
with a series of meetings</i>

48
00:03:06,608 --> 00:03:08,606
<i>on moral rearmament,</i>

49
00:03:08,640 --> 00:03:11,478
<i>with which he felt
obliged to benefit the town.</i>

50
00:03:11,941 --> 00:03:13,939
- Hi, kids.
- Hi, Tom.

51
00:03:14,941 --> 00:03:16,939
Evening, Chuck.

52
00:03:17,007 --> 00:03:19,005
Will we see you
at the meeting tomorrow?

53
00:03:19,341 --> 00:03:21,339
I could do without your lectures.

54
00:03:21,674 --> 00:03:23,672
You know Vera...

55
00:03:24,007 --> 00:03:26,465
wouldn't give me a moment's
peace till I said yes.

56
00:03:28,707 --> 00:03:30,705
<i>Who gave Moses that bone?</i>

57
00:03:30,974 --> 00:03:32,906
It's still got meat on it.

58
00:03:32,907 --> 00:03:34,507
Jason did.

59
00:03:34,508 --> 00:03:37,435
Jason gave that mutt
a bone with meat on it?!

60
00:03:37,907 --> 00:03:39,985
When did we last see meat?

61
00:03:40,341 --> 00:03:43,298
Next time you waste good food,
I'll take your knife away.

62
00:03:43,774 --> 00:03:45,962
<i>Ought have known it was you
who was given meat to eat.</i>

63
00:03:46,341 --> 00:03:48,618
<i>Moses is meant to be hungry!
To keep watch.</i>

64
00:03:49,007 --> 00:03:51,005
Keep watch in Dogville?

65
00:03:51,074 --> 00:03:53,006
What's there to steal?

66
00:03:53,007 --> 00:03:55,754
These are wicked times,
Tom Edison.

67
00:03:56,208 --> 00:03:59,335
Soon there'll be folks by
with even less than us.

68
00:04:06,607 --> 00:04:09,265
<i>Indeed, Tom was busy enough,</i>

69
00:04:09,707 --> 00:04:11,705
<i>even though, formally speaking,</i>

70
00:04:11,807 --> 00:04:14,295
<i>not yet busy with writing per Se.</i>

71
00:04:14,707 --> 00:04:17,015
<i>And if a body
found it hard to grasp</i>

72
00:04:17,408 --> 00:04:19,456
<i>what profession he was busy at,</i>

73
00:04:19,807 --> 00:04:22,175
<i>he'd merely reply, "mining."</i>

74
00:04:22,574 --> 00:04:25,352
<i>For although he did not blast
his way through rock,</i>

75
00:04:25,807 --> 00:04:28,554
<i>he'd blasted
through what was even harder...</i>

76
00:04:29,007 --> 00:04:31,005
<i>namely, the human soul,</i>

77
00:04:31,308 --> 00:04:33,915
<i>right into where it blistered.</i>

78
00:04:34,341 --> 00:04:36,339
- Hey, Martha.
- Hello, Tom.

79
00:04:36,441 --> 00:04:38,808
They're all coming, so you just
have those benches ready.

80
00:04:39,208 --> 00:04:40,873
Yes, they're ready.

81
00:04:40,874 --> 00:04:43,681
But Tom, I repeat,
if you need to use my organ,

82
00:04:44,141 --> 00:04:47,178
I got to get special permission
from the regional director.

83
00:04:47,674 --> 00:04:50,392
And I repeat,
we don't need the organ.

84
00:04:50,840 --> 00:04:54,057
We can be spiritual without singing
or reading from the Bible.

85
00:04:54,574 --> 00:04:57,032
It's almost 7:00,
don't forget your bell now.

86
00:04:58,907 --> 00:05:00,873
<i>I imagine that'll do, Ma Ginger.</i>

87
00:05:00,874 --> 00:05:03,771
I don't think it's good for the soil
with all that raking and hoeing.

88
00:05:05,740 --> 00:05:07,818
<i>It's the soil
that gave life to us all.</i>

89
00:05:09,174 --> 00:05:12,271
Don't give me any of your lip,
Thomas Edison, Jr.

90
00:05:12,774 --> 00:05:14,792
I'll hoe as I darn well please.

91
00:05:15,141 --> 00:05:17,918
Yeah, and spoil the whole thing.

92
00:05:18,374 --> 00:05:20,240
I agree with Tom.

93
00:05:20,241 --> 00:05:22,239
Yeah, but he likes eating
my pies, don't you?

94
00:05:22,474 --> 00:05:24,641
They're tasty, no doubt about it.

95
00:05:25,007 --> 00:05:27,664
So when it comes to hoeing,
who's right, Tom, you or me?

96
00:05:28,107 --> 00:05:30,105
I'm not so sure it's that simple.

97
00:05:30,408 --> 00:05:31,906
He's got you there, Ginger.

98
00:05:31,907 --> 00:05:34,894
You cannot resist, can you, Gloria?

99
00:05:35,374 --> 00:05:37,372
Hey, Ben, I'll get the doors.

100
00:05:37,607 --> 00:05:40,854
- That'll be fine, Tom.
<i>- Any news from the freight industry?</i>

101
00:05:41,374 --> 00:05:43,372
Is everything going
to hell there too?

102
00:05:43,574 --> 00:05:46,002
Don't poke fun
at the freight industry.

103
00:05:51,074 --> 00:05:53,072
<i>It was 7:00 precisely</i>

104
00:05:53,308 --> 00:05:55,555
<i>as Martha chimed the hour.</i>

105
00:05:55,941 --> 00:05:59,837
<i>And Tom was due to play checkers
with his childhood friend Bill Henson.</i>

106
00:06:01,408 --> 00:06:03,406
<i>Bill was dumb and knew it.</i>

107
00:06:04,374 --> 00:06:06,771
<i>Far too dumb to qualify
as an engineer,</i>

108
00:06:07,174 --> 00:06:09,172
<i>he was certainly sure of that.</i>

109
00:06:10,674 --> 00:06:13,451
<i>After listening for a while
to the pile driver down the valley</i>

110
00:06:13,907 --> 00:06:16,075
<i>that Ben insisted was working
on the foundation</i>

111
00:06:16,440 --> 00:06:18,438
<i>of a new penitentiary,</i>

112
00:06:18,740 --> 00:06:22,017
<i>Tom headed for the Henson home
in order to inflict upon Bill</i>

113
00:06:22,540 --> 00:06:25,907
<i>yet another humiliating
defeat at checkers.</i>

114
00:06:26,440 --> 00:06:28,928
<i>Some folks might say
the opportunity</i>

115
00:06:29,341 --> 00:06:31,339
<i>to meet Bill's older sister Liz</i>

116
00:06:31,540 --> 00:06:33,818
<i>was more of a draw
than the checkerboard.</i>

117
00:06:34,208 --> 00:06:36,226
<i>And they might be right.</i>

118
00:06:36,574 --> 00:06:39,262
<i>It was a fact that
in the Henson home</i>

119
00:06:39,707 --> 00:06:41,925
<i>lay another horizon,</i>

120
00:06:42,308 --> 00:06:45,325
<i>a horizon just as alluring
as the one beyond the valley...</i>

121
00:06:47,174 --> 00:06:50,450
<i>a horizon bound by Liz Henson's
luscious curves...</i>

122
00:06:50,974 --> 00:06:55,479
- Nobody's getting it?
<i>- ...a sweet, painful, seductive abyss.</i>

123
00:06:56,174 --> 00:06:57,839
<i>- Hey, Liz.</i>
- Hey, Tom.

124
00:06:57,840 --> 00:06:59,918
<i>Must you come by every single day?</i>

125
00:07:02,107 --> 00:07:05,383
It'd be a lot more fun if somebody
interesting appeared for a change.

126
00:07:05,907 --> 00:07:08,305
You know, I really am
so lonesome in this town.

127
00:07:10,274 --> 00:07:13,930
<i>The moment my fiancé writes that he's
gotten that job in Boulder, I'm off</i>

128
00:07:14,507 --> 00:07:17,544
then the lot of you will have to find
some other girl's skirts to peek up.

129
00:07:18,041 --> 00:07:19,673
Is Bill in?

130
00:07:19,674 --> 00:07:21,672
Well, isn't he always?

131
00:07:22,874 --> 00:07:25,012
He studies and I help out
with the glasses,

132
00:07:25,373 --> 00:07:27,541
even though everybody knows
that I'm the clever one.

133
00:07:28,941 --> 00:07:31,518
<i>- Hey, Mrs. Henson.
- Good evening, Tom.</i>

134
00:07:31,941 --> 00:07:33,939
Checkers time, Bill ol' buddy!

135
00:07:36,373 --> 00:07:38,371
What is that...?

136
00:07:38,640 --> 00:07:40,638
You didn't hear the bell?

137
00:07:41,907 --> 00:07:45,943
<i>As usual, Bill tried
to fake his way around actually playing.</i>

138
00:07:46,574 --> 00:07:48,652
<i>He had not yet fully comprehended</i>

139
00:07:49,007 --> 00:07:51,724
<i>this meeting business, he claimed.</i>

140
00:07:52,174 --> 00:07:54,172
Maybe you should just let them be.

141
00:07:54,274 --> 00:07:57,930
- I don't think so. I...
- What if they're just fine as they are?

142
00:07:58,507 --> 00:08:00,905
You think they're fine?
I don't think so.

143
00:08:01,308 --> 00:08:03,415
I think there is a lot
this country's forgotten.

144
00:08:03,774 --> 00:08:06,841
I just try to refresh folks' memories
by way of illustration.

145
00:08:07,340 --> 00:08:09,338
<i>So the illustration for tomorrow...</i>

146
00:08:10,407 --> 00:08:12,405
I don't know.

147
00:08:14,274 --> 00:08:17,171
See, if the people of Dogville
have a problem with acceptance,

148
00:08:17,640 --> 00:08:20,158
what I really need is
something for them to accept.

149
00:08:21,640 --> 00:08:24,008
Something tangible, like a gift.

150
00:08:26,041 --> 00:08:28,968
Why in the heck would someone
up and give us a gift?

151
00:08:29,440 --> 00:08:31,173
I don't know.

152
00:08:31,174 --> 00:08:33,311
I'm gonna have
to do some thinking.

153
00:08:33,674 --> 00:08:35,672
Wait, wait, wait-<i>...</i>

154
00:08:38,774 --> 00:08:40,772
We're missing a piece.

155
00:08:41,041 --> 00:08:43,039
We won't be able to play.

156
00:08:51,740 --> 00:08:54,138
My mind is sharp tonight.

157
00:09:06,273 --> 00:09:08,271
Night, Bill.

158
00:09:14,342 --> 00:09:21,425
CHAPTER ONE in which Tom
hears gunfire and meets Grace.

159
00:09:23,007 --> 00:09:26,134
<i>Despite considerable effort
on his part to prolong things,</i>

160
00:09:26,640 --> 00:09:30,446
<i>Tom had achieved the triumph
of the checkerboard pretty quickly.</i>

161
00:09:31,041 --> 00:09:34,198
<i>It had started to rain, and the wind
had become a regular gale</i>

162
00:09:34,707 --> 00:09:37,774
<i>when Tom strolled home
through Elm Street.</i>

163
00:09:38,273 --> 00:09:40,271
<i>If Tom were to prove</i>

164
00:09:40,440 --> 00:09:42,928
<i>that the citizens of Dogville
had a problem receiving</i>

165
00:09:43,340 --> 00:09:45,338
<i>in his lecture the next day,</i>

166
00:09:45,373 --> 00:09:47,561
<i>he sorely lacked an illustration...</i>

167
00:09:47,941 --> 00:09:49,539
<i>a gift.</i>

168
00:09:49,540 --> 00:09:51,678
<i>Bill might have been right.</i>

169
00:09:52,041 --> 00:09:55,637
<i>It hadn't exactly rained gifts
on this particular township.</i>

170
00:10:34,074 --> 00:10:36,731
<i>There was no doubt in his mind.</i>

171
00:10:37,173 --> 00:10:39,221
<i>They were gunshots.</i>

172
00:10:39,574 --> 00:10:42,731
<i>The pile driver in the marshes
didn't sound like that at all.</i>

173
00:10:43,240 --> 00:10:45,238
<i>The shots had come
from down in the valley,</i>

174
00:10:45,574 --> 00:10:47,406
<i>or perhaps from Canyon Road,</i>

175
00:10:47,407 --> 00:10:49,515
<i>some place in the direction
of Georgetown.</i>

176
00:10:52,141 --> 00:10:55,357
<i>He listened for more shots for ages,</i>

177
00:10:55,874 --> 00:10:57,892
<i>but they were not repeated.</i>

178
00:11:00,540 --> 00:11:02,538
<i>A tad disappointed,</i>

179
00:11:02,640 --> 00:11:05,507
<i>Tom sat down
on the old ladies' bench to think,</i>

180
00:11:05,974 --> 00:11:08,991
<i>to hang on to the feeling
of danger for a moment.</i>

181
00:11:10,440 --> 00:11:12,748
<i>But it wasn't long
before his thoughts</i>

182
00:11:13,140 --> 00:11:15,478
<i>were back on his favorite
subjects again.</i>

183
00:11:15,874 --> 00:11:17,892
<i>And in the midst of the storm,
they metamorphosed</i>

184
00:11:18,240 --> 00:11:20,238
<i>into articles and novels,</i>

185
00:11:20,407 --> 00:11:23,214
<i>and great gatherings
that'd listen in silence to Tom</i>

186
00:11:23,674 --> 00:11:26,161
<i>after the publication
of yet another volume</i>

187
00:11:26,574 --> 00:11:29,381
<i>that scourged and purged
the human soul.</i>

188
00:11:30,874 --> 00:11:34,061
<i>And he saw men... and among them
even other writers...</i>

189
00:11:34,574 --> 00:11:36,682
<i>throw their arms
around one another</i>

190
00:11:37,041 --> 00:11:40,547
<i>as, through his words,
life had opened up for them anew.</i>

191
00:11:42,173 --> 00:11:44,171
<i>It hadn't been easy.</i>

192
00:11:44,173 --> 00:11:47,300
<i>But by his diligence and application
to narrative and drama,</i>

193
00:11:47,807 --> 00:11:50,734
<i>his message had gotten through.</i>

194
00:11:51,207 --> 00:11:53,315
<i>And asked about his technique,</i>

195
00:11:53,674 --> 00:11:56,131
<i>he would have to say but one word:</i>

196
00:11:57,941 --> 00:11:59,939
<i>"illustration."</i>

197
00:12:18,707 --> 00:12:21,924
<i>Tom could have spent another
half hour or more on the bench,</i>

198
00:12:22,440 --> 00:12:24,988
<i>but another unusual noise
roused him.</i>

199
00:12:25,407 --> 00:12:28,214
<i>It was Moses barking.</i>

200
00:12:28,674 --> 00:12:31,042
<i>That wasn't unusual in itself,</i>

201
00:12:31,440 --> 00:12:33,928
<i>but it was the way
he barked that was new.</i>

202
00:12:34,340 --> 00:12:36,338
<i>His barking was not loud,</i>

203
00:12:36,507 --> 00:12:39,964
<i>but more of a snarl, as if the danger
was quite close at hand</i>

204
00:12:40,507 --> 00:12:43,784
<i>and not merely
a passing raccoon or fox,</i>

205
00:12:44,307 --> 00:12:47,294
<i>as if the dog was
standing face to face</i>

206
00:12:47,774 --> 00:12:51,430
<i>with a force
to be taken seriously.</i>

207
00:12:52,007 --> 00:12:54,005
<i>Hey, lady!</i>

208
00:12:55,407 --> 00:12:57,405
<i>I wouldn't go up there
if I were you.</i>

209
00:12:59,907 --> 00:13:01,985
<i>I know the mountain well.</i>

210
00:13:02,340 --> 00:13:04,828
<i>I doubt if I'd get away
with my life.</i>

211
00:13:05,240 --> 00:13:07,238
It's a very nasty drop.

212
00:13:12,941 --> 00:13:15,188
Is there another way?

213
00:13:15,574 --> 00:13:17,572
<i>Yeah.</i>

214
00:13:20,740 --> 00:13:22,738
Where?

215
00:13:22,840 --> 00:13:24,918
Back down the way you came from,

216
00:13:25,273 --> 00:13:27,271
back down to Georgetown.

217
00:13:28,273 --> 00:13:30,139
Why do you need
to get up the mountain?

218
00:13:30,140 --> 00:13:32,158
Did it have anything to do
with those gunshots?

219
00:13:39,373 --> 00:13:41,591
Help me! Help me, please.

220
00:13:41,974 --> 00:13:44,491
Hide in the mine. In there.

221
00:13:53,574 --> 00:13:55,572
Where is this road headed to?

222
00:13:55,607 --> 00:13:57,506
Nowhere. It's a dead end.

223
00:13:57,507 --> 00:13:59,875
If you want the pass,
you'll have to turn around,

224
00:14:00,273 --> 00:14:04,079
go back by way of Georgetown.
This place, it's called Dogville.

225
00:14:04,674 --> 00:14:06,072
- Dogville?
<i>- Yeah.</i>

226
00:14:06,073 --> 00:14:08,071
It figures. A stupid name
if I ever heard one.

227
00:14:09,473 --> 00:14:12,430
- Hey, we're looking for somebody.
- Really? Who might that be?

228
00:14:15,540 --> 00:14:18,087
My boss wants to talk to you.

229
00:14:18,507 --> 00:14:20,525
- Young man?
- Yes, sir?

230
00:14:20,874 --> 00:14:22,872
I'm looking for a girl.

231
00:14:23,040 --> 00:14:26,057
<i>She may have made her way
to your town in her confusion.</i>

232
00:14:26,540 --> 00:14:28,538
<i>I don't want any harm
to come to her.</i>

233
00:14:28,674 --> 00:14:30,842
<i>She's very precious to me.</i>

234
00:14:31,207 --> 00:14:33,139
Well, sir...

235
00:14:33,140 --> 00:14:36,537
nobody's been through Dogville.
Moses would have barked.

236
00:14:37,073 --> 00:14:40,140
He's very suspicious of strangers.

237
00:14:40,640 --> 00:14:43,127
<i>That's very wise of Moses.</i>

238
00:14:43,540 --> 00:14:45,306
Please take my card...

239
00:14:45,307 --> 00:14:48,404
and if perhaps you see a stranger,

240
00:14:48,907 --> 00:14:52,093
then give me a call.

241
00:14:52,607 --> 00:14:55,704
<i>I am in a position
to offer a considerable reward.</i>

242
00:14:56,207 --> 00:14:58,225
Yes, sir. Thank you.

243
00:15:01,273 --> 00:15:03,271
Was it you that fired those shots?

244
00:15:15,840 --> 00:15:17,838
Well, they're gone.

245
00:15:20,273 --> 00:15:22,441
<i>You want to come out now?</i>

246
00:15:31,940 --> 00:15:34,748
You want a cup of coffee
before you go mountain climbing?

247
00:15:38,273 --> 00:15:40,701
<i>- Yeah?
- That'd be nice.</i>

248
00:15:44,640 --> 00:15:47,886
<i>The beautiful
fugitive's name was Grace.</i>

249
00:15:48,407 --> 00:15:50,835
<i>She hadn't chosen Dogville
from a map</i>

250
00:15:51,240 --> 00:15:53,288
<i>or sought out
the township for a visit.</i>

251
00:15:53,640 --> 00:15:56,916
<i>Yet Tom felt right away
that she belonged.</i>

252
00:15:58,407 --> 00:16:00,405
Shall I take the bone?

253
00:16:06,006 --> 00:16:08,993
<i>She could have kept
her vulnerability to herself,</i>

254
00:16:09,473 --> 00:16:13,309
<i>but she had elected to give
herself up to him at random...</i>

255
00:16:15,106 --> 00:16:18,443
<i>as... yes... a gift.</i>

256
00:16:18,973 --> 00:16:20,905
<i>"Generous,</i>

257
00:16:20,906 --> 00:16:23,014
<i>very generous," thought Tom.</i>

258
00:16:23,373 --> 00:16:25,371
Do you want to eat?

259
00:16:28,839 --> 00:16:31,357
- You must be hungry...
- I can't.

260
00:16:32,740 --> 00:16:34,738
I don't deserve that bread.

261
00:16:36,240 --> 00:16:38,238
<i>I stole that bone.</i>

262
00:16:38,340 --> 00:16:40,857
I'd never stolen anything before.

263
00:16:42,240 --> 00:16:44,897
So now...
now I have to punish myself.

264
00:16:45,340 --> 00:16:48,816
<i>I was raised to be arrogant.</i>

265
00:16:49,373 --> 00:16:52,530
So, I... I had to teach myself
these things.

266
00:16:54,440 --> 00:16:56,548
Well...

267
00:16:56,906 --> 00:16:59,214
it may be best
for your education...

268
00:17:01,073 --> 00:17:03,071
but, Grace, in this town,

269
00:17:04,073 --> 00:17:06,071
in these times...

270
00:17:07,707 --> 00:17:10,134
it's very impolite not to eat
what's set before you.

271
00:17:13,839 --> 00:17:16,207
<i>I'm so sorry.</i>

272
00:17:27,040 --> 00:17:29,118
<i>Who were the men in the car?</i>

273
00:17:29,473 --> 00:17:31,471
Why would they want to hurt you?

274
00:17:33,440 --> 00:17:35,897
The man in the back of the car,
he's the boss.

275
00:17:36,307 --> 00:17:38,305
I saw his face.

276
00:17:39,307 --> 00:17:41,615
He gave me his telephone number,

277
00:17:42,006 --> 00:17:44,024
told me to call if I saw you.

278
00:17:44,373 --> 00:17:46,371
I'm sure he'd offer you
a big reward

279
00:17:46,574 --> 00:17:48,572
if you told him where I was.

280
00:17:48,674 --> 00:17:50,672
Yeah.

281
00:17:54,906 --> 00:17:57,514
- Where is your family?
<i>- I don't have a family.</i>

282
00:17:57,940 --> 00:18:00,128
All I had was a father.

283
00:18:03,240 --> 00:18:06,367
Those gangsters
took him away from me.

284
00:18:08,340 --> 00:18:10,737
What if I said you could stay here?

285
00:18:11,140 --> 00:18:14,677
Here? Even if you meant it,
it's impossible.

286
00:18:17,839 --> 00:18:20,117
It's a very small town.

287
00:18:20,507 --> 00:18:23,753
I have to hide.
People will ask questions.

288
00:18:24,273 --> 00:18:27,729
That might not matter,
not if they all wanted to help you too.

289
00:18:29,540 --> 00:18:32,147
Are you saying that everybody
in this town is like you?

290
00:18:32,574 --> 00:18:34,572
They're good people.

291
00:18:34,739 --> 00:18:36,737
They're honest people.

292
00:18:36,906 --> 00:18:39,514
<i>They've all been
in need themselves.</i>

293
00:18:39,940 --> 00:18:42,218
They might well
turn you down, but...

294
00:18:43,873 --> 00:18:46,241
I think it'd be worth
the trouble to ask.

295
00:18:46,640 --> 00:18:48,717
<i>But I've got nothing
to offer them in return.</i>

296
00:18:49,073 --> 00:18:51,730
<i>No, I think you have plenty
to offer Dogville.</i>

297
00:19:01,273 --> 00:19:03,960
<i>To call the mood
of the audience at Tom's moral lecture</i>

298
00:19:04,407 --> 00:19:06,714
<i>in the mission house
the next day "enthusiastic"</i>

299
00:19:07,106 --> 00:19:09,384
<i>would have been going too far.</i>

300
00:19:09,773 --> 00:19:11,639
<i>But they had come,</i>

301
00:19:11,640 --> 00:19:13,887
<i>and Tom had launched
himself fearlessly</i>

302
00:19:14,273 --> 00:19:18,399
<i>into his endeavor to illustrate
the human problem... to receive.</i>

303
00:19:23,440 --> 00:19:25,438
<i>The subject was obvious...</i>

304
00:19:25,639 --> 00:19:28,766
<i>but quite dreadfully ill-considered
by this young man.</i>

305
00:19:29,273 --> 00:19:31,441
<i>To compensate
for his lack of preparation,</i>

306
00:19:31,806 --> 00:19:34,464
<i>Tom made diligent use
of his technique of lashing out</i>

307
00:19:34,906 --> 00:19:38,413
<i>somewhat haphazardly
in all directions.</i>

308
00:19:38,973 --> 00:19:42,340
<i>His father peered around covertly
to gauge the mood,</i>

309
00:19:42,873 --> 00:19:45,241
<i>and sensing that the assembly
was not entirely happy</i>

310
00:19:45,639 --> 00:19:47,747
<i>with his rather direct criticism,</i>

311
00:19:48,106 --> 00:19:50,594
<i>he decided to forestall any protests.</i>

312
00:19:51,006 --> 00:19:53,693
I'm sure that
you wish us well, Tom.

313
00:19:54,140 --> 00:19:56,188
But, of any town,

314
00:19:56,540 --> 00:19:59,666
I believe this one has
a very fine sense of community.

315
00:20:00,173 --> 00:20:02,341
Living side by side,
we all know one another.

316
00:20:02,706 --> 00:20:04,844
I'm a pretty fair judge
of character myself.

317
00:20:05,207 --> 00:20:07,345
Honestly, Tom,
you've done it again!

318
00:20:07,706 --> 00:20:10,284
Made us come here to listen
to a lot of nonsense.

319
00:20:10,706 --> 00:20:13,104
What do you think you are,
some kind of philosopher?

320
00:20:13,507 --> 00:20:16,903
- Observant, that's what I am.
- Lazy, I would say.

321
00:20:17,440 --> 00:20:19,438
We shovel snow together.

322
00:20:19,440 --> 00:20:21,717
- You shovel snow together?
<i>- Yeah.</i>

323
00:20:22,106 --> 00:20:24,244
Every household clears
their own front walk!

324
00:20:24,606 --> 00:20:27,154
I got to allow
that Tom's right on that.

325
00:20:27,573 --> 00:20:29,821
<i>The roads don't get cleared proper...</i>

326
00:20:31,873 --> 00:20:34,770
I'm sorry, Tom, you'll have to come up
with something better than that.

327
00:20:35,240 --> 00:20:37,488
The whole country
would be better served

328
00:20:37,873 --> 00:20:40,560
with a greater attitude
of openness and acceptance.

329
00:20:41,006 --> 00:20:43,024
You're not suggesting
we all wouldn't help out

330
00:20:43,373 --> 00:20:45,541
- if somebody needed help?
<i>- No, that's not the point.</i>

331
00:20:45,906 --> 00:20:49,533
- We care for human beings up here!
- We'll probably never find out.

332
00:20:55,006 --> 00:20:58,073
Since nobody seems to want
to admit that there is a problem...

333
00:21:00,673 --> 00:21:02,671
let me illustrate.

334
00:21:04,307 --> 00:21:07,783
I'm not going to use something
that's already happened.

335
00:21:09,440 --> 00:21:12,507
<i>I'm going to use something
that's just about to happen.</i>

336
00:21:16,673 --> 00:21:19,221
<i>And after providing
a quick summary of the events</i>

337
00:21:19,639 --> 00:21:22,327
<i>of the previous evening
to the astonished people of Dogville,</i>

338
00:21:22,773 --> 00:21:25,051
<i>Tom went down to the mine</i>

339
00:21:25,440 --> 00:21:28,596
<i>to retrieve the fugitive
from her hideaway.</i>

340
00:21:36,673 --> 00:21:38,671
Allow me to introduce Grace.

341
00:21:39,006 --> 00:21:40,905
Grace, these are the...

342
00:21:40,906 --> 00:21:42,904
citizens of Dogville.

343
00:21:43,173 --> 00:21:45,171
- Hello.
<i>- Hello.</i>

344
00:21:48,673 --> 00:21:51,131
Tom has told us
about your predicament, miss.

345
00:21:51,539 --> 00:21:53,877
I really don't want to put
any of you in jeopardy.

346
00:21:54,273 --> 00:21:57,929
Why don't you just go to the police?
They can take care of gangsters.

347
00:21:58,506 --> 00:22:02,862
- It's their job.
- I don't know that that's a good idea.

348
00:22:03,539 --> 00:22:05,877
- In the transportation business-<i>-
- Ben!</i>

349
00:22:06,273 --> 00:22:09,989
These men, they have
powerful connections...

350
00:22:12,573 --> 00:22:14,571
even with the police.

351
00:22:14,606 --> 00:22:17,064
You think we should give
sanctuary to a fugitive?

352
00:22:17,472 --> 00:22:19,840
A fugitive that gangsters
want to get a hold of?

353
00:22:20,240 --> 00:22:22,238
Well, that would put us
in a pretty pickle...

354
00:22:22,573 --> 00:22:24,538
Easy, Claire,
think of your asthma.

355
00:22:24,539 --> 00:22:27,087
<i>Dogville's a good place
to hide, that's for certain.</i>

356
00:22:27,506 --> 00:22:30,523
Exactly. The only way up here
is Canyon Road.

357
00:22:31,006 --> 00:22:34,902
<i>That could easily be watched by
Ma Ginger's... excuse me... nosey cousin</i>

358
00:22:35,506 --> 00:22:37,504
<i>who lives only yards
from the turnoff.</i>

359
00:22:37,673 --> 00:22:40,391
<i>She has a telephone.
Martha, you could ring the bell,</i>

360
00:22:40,839 --> 00:22:42,837
<i>tell the town
if people were coming.</i>

361
00:22:44,573 --> 00:22:46,571
But, Tom, I chime the hours.

362
00:22:46,639 --> 00:22:49,067
What if people get confused
with all the ringing?

363
00:22:49,472 --> 00:22:52,050
Come now, Martha.
Surely we can use our old bell

364
00:22:52,472 --> 00:22:54,900
to save a life if need be.

365
00:22:55,307 --> 00:22:57,934
<i>- Why should we?</i>
- Because we care, Chuck.

366
00:22:58,373 --> 00:23:00,860
- We care for human beings.
- That ain't what I mean.

367
00:23:02,240 --> 00:23:04,607
How do we know this woman
is telling us the truth?

368
00:23:05,006 --> 00:23:07,004
Maybe these gangsters
did shoot at her.

369
00:23:07,207 --> 00:23:09,205
That don't make her
somebody to be trusted.

370
00:23:09,373 --> 00:23:11,371
He's right.

371
00:23:13,207 --> 00:23:15,454
Why would you trust me?

372
00:23:15,839 --> 00:23:19,346
- I trust you.
- Tom, we're not gangsters.

373
00:23:19,906 --> 00:23:21,984
We mind our own business.

374
00:23:23,340 --> 00:23:25,917
We don't ask nothing from nobody.

375
00:23:27,307 --> 00:23:30,234
- So at last you admit it?
- If only there was some way

376
00:23:30,706 --> 00:23:33,104
that we wouldn't doubt
the young lady's word,

377
00:23:33,506 --> 00:23:36,843
<i>some way to know her,
then I think we'd all ignore the risk.</i>

378
00:23:38,906 --> 00:23:41,393
<i>There is a way.
You said it yourself...</i>

379
00:23:41,806 --> 00:23:44,793
by living side by side with her.

380
00:23:45,273 --> 00:23:47,460
<i>Dad, you're such a fine
judge of character.</i>

381
00:23:47,839 --> 00:23:50,876
How long would it take a man
like you to unmask her?

382
00:23:51,372 --> 00:23:53,370
A week?

383
00:23:53,472 --> 00:23:55,405
Maybe two?

384
00:23:55,406 --> 00:23:57,624
Surely we can offer her two weeks!

385
00:23:59,173 --> 00:24:02,300
And if after that time, so much
as one man cries out, <i>"</i>Be gone!<i>"</i>

386
00:24:02,806 --> 00:24:05,823
I promise I'll happily
send her packing myself.

387
00:24:14,240 --> 00:24:17,077
Well, if Master Tom think
this is right for us,

388
00:24:17,539 --> 00:24:19,617
and for the community, then,

389
00:24:19,973 --> 00:24:21,971
that'll do for me.

390
00:24:22,173 --> 00:24:24,780
He might be young,
but his heart is right.

391
00:24:25,207 --> 00:24:28,543
And I've known his heart
for as long as it's been beating.

392
00:24:38,506 --> 00:24:41,933
<i>No more words were spoken at
the town meeting in the mission house.</i>

393
00:24:42,472 --> 00:24:45,250
<i>But it had been decided,
they all felt,</i>

394
00:24:45,706 --> 00:24:48,313
<i>that the fugitive would be
given two weeks.</i>

395
00:24:48,739 --> 00:24:51,456
<i>And they would all be able
to look at themselves in the mirror</i>

396
00:24:51,906 --> 00:24:54,513
<i>and know that they had done
what they could indeed,</i>

397
00:24:54,940 --> 00:24:58,217
<i>and perhaps more
than most people would have done.</i>

398
00:25:00,906 --> 00:25:02,984
<i>So, that very afternoon,</i>

399
00:25:03,339 --> 00:25:05,647
<i>Tom took Grace on a stroll
down Elm Street</i>

400
00:25:06,040 --> 00:25:09,137
<i>to introduce her
to the town he loved.</i>

401
00:25:09,639 --> 00:25:12,296
Well, this is where...

402
00:25:12,739 --> 00:25:15,516
Olivia and June live.
June's a cripple.

403
00:25:15,973 --> 00:25:20,009
<i>They live here as a token
of my dad's broad-mindedness.</i>

404
00:25:20,639 --> 00:25:23,766
<i>Chuck and Vera, they have seven children
and they hate each other.</i>

405
00:25:24,273 --> 00:25:26,350
<i>Next door, we have the Hensons.</i>

406
00:25:26,706 --> 00:25:29,953
They make a living from grinding
the edges off cheap glasses

407
00:25:30,472 --> 00:25:32,640
to try and make
them look expensive.

408
00:25:33,006 --> 00:25:35,663
Moving on we have Jack McKay.

409
00:25:36,106 --> 00:25:38,413
Jack McKay, he's blind
and the whole town knows it,

410
00:25:38,806 --> 00:25:42,752
but he thinks he can hide it
by never leaving his house.

411
00:25:43,372 --> 00:25:45,390
In the old stable,
Ben keeps his truck.

412
00:25:45,739 --> 00:25:49,335
He drinks, and he visits
the whorehouse...

413
00:25:49,906 --> 00:25:52,303
once a month,
and he's ashamed of it.

414
00:25:52,706 --> 00:25:54,784
Martha, she runs the mission house

415
00:25:55,140 --> 00:25:57,138
<i>until the new preacher comes,</i>

416
00:25:57,240 --> 00:25:59,238
which will just never happen.

417
00:26:00,639 --> 00:26:03,766
And that leaves
Ma Ginger and Gloria.

418
00:26:04,272 --> 00:26:06,790
<i>They run this really
expensive store</i>

419
00:26:07,207 --> 00:26:11,103
where they exploit the fact
that nobody leaves town.

420
00:26:11,706 --> 00:26:13,704
We used to leave to go vote,

421
00:26:14,006 --> 00:26:16,613
but since they put in
the registration fee...

422
00:26:17,040 --> 00:26:19,058
it's about a day's
wages for these people...

423
00:26:19,406 --> 00:26:21,864
Dogville didn't feel
the democratic need anymore.

424
00:26:26,372 --> 00:26:29,499
<i>Those awful figurines say more
about the people in this town</i>

425
00:26:30,006 --> 00:26:32,313
<i>- than many words.</i>
- If this is the town that you love,

426
00:26:32,706 --> 00:26:34,704
then you really have
a strange way of showing it.

427
00:26:37,073 --> 00:26:39,790
All I see is...

428
00:26:40,239 --> 00:26:43,516
a beautiful little town
in the midst of...

429
00:26:44,040 --> 00:26:46,317
magnificent mountains.

430
00:26:47,673 --> 00:26:50,950
A place where people
have hopes and dreams...

431
00:26:53,239 --> 00:26:55,757
even under the hardest conditions.

432
00:26:57,839 --> 00:27:01,705
<i>And seven figurines
that are not awful at all.</i>

433
00:27:04,573 --> 00:27:07,700
<i>Calling Dogville beautiful
was original at least.</i>

434
00:27:09,239 --> 00:27:11,987
<i>Grace was just casting
one more look at the figurines</i>

435
00:27:12,439 --> 00:27:15,976
<i>she herself would have dismissed
as tasteless a few days earlier,</i>

436
00:27:16,539 --> 00:27:18,537
<i>when she suddenly sensed</i>

437
00:27:18,806 --> 00:27:20,854
<i>what would best
have been described</i>

438
00:27:21,206 --> 00:27:24,104
<i>as a tiny change of light
over Dogville.</i>

439
00:27:47,306 --> 00:27:49,674
<i>They're keeping an eye on you.</i>

440
00:27:50,073 --> 00:27:52,071
<i>If you love them already,</i>

441
00:27:52,306 --> 00:27:54,554
<i>they might need a little persuading.</i>

442
00:27:56,506 --> 00:27:59,373
We've got two weeks
to get them to accept you.

443
00:27:59,839 --> 00:28:03,295
You make it sound
like we're playing a game.

444
00:28:03,839 --> 00:28:05,837
Well, yes...

445
00:28:06,073 --> 00:28:08,071
we are.

446
00:28:08,573 --> 00:28:11,290
Isn't saving your life
worth a little game?

447
00:28:11,739 --> 00:28:14,756
- What do you want me to do?
- Do you mind physical labor?

448
00:28:17,372 --> 00:28:19,370
No.

449
00:28:19,539 --> 00:28:21,677
Dogville offered you two weeks.

450
00:28:23,806 --> 00:28:25,804
Now you offer them.

451
00:28:32,717 --> 00:28:39,425
CHAPTER TWO in which Grace follows Tom's
plan and embarks upon physical labour.

452
00:28:40,973 --> 00:28:44,309
<i>The next day was
a beautiful day in Dogville.</i>

453
00:28:44,839 --> 00:28:47,356
<i>The tender leaves on Ma Ginger's
gooseberry bushes</i>

454
00:28:47,773 --> 00:28:50,580
<i>were unfurling despite
wise Tom's misgivings</i>

455
00:28:51,040 --> 00:28:53,177
<i>as regards her gardening methods.</i>

456
00:28:53,539 --> 00:28:55,537
<i>But more than that,</i>

457
00:28:55,706 --> 00:28:57,704
<i>this first day of spring</i>

458
00:28:57,839 --> 00:29:01,965
<i>had also been picked to be
Grace's first-ever day of work,</i>

459
00:29:02,606 --> 00:29:05,623
<i>the day in which she was
to set off around Dogville</i>

460
00:29:06,105 --> 00:29:09,472
<i>and offer herself
one hour per household per day.</i>

461
00:29:10,006 --> 00:29:12,004
Excuse me.

462
00:29:14,573 --> 00:29:16,711
I'd like to offer you my help.

463
00:29:17,072 --> 00:29:19,070
If there's anything
that you need...

464
00:29:20,706 --> 00:29:22,438
Yeah...

465
00:29:22,439 --> 00:29:24,517
a carburetor that don't leak.

466
00:29:27,573 --> 00:29:30,090
All right, here. Let me take that.

467
00:29:30,506 --> 00:29:33,573
Maybe I could help
around your home.

468
00:29:34,072 --> 00:29:36,850
I don't really have a home, miss.

469
00:29:39,573 --> 00:29:42,590
Just the garage.

470
00:29:43,072 --> 00:29:45,940
I'm in the freight business.
The road's my home.

471
00:29:46,406 --> 00:29:48,338
I'm ready. Good morning.

472
00:29:48,339 --> 00:29:50,557
Miss Olivia's got a home.

473
00:29:50,940 --> 00:29:54,186
She's looking to help out
in somebody's home.

474
00:29:54,706 --> 00:29:57,923
A cleaning lady for a cleaning lady?!

475
00:29:58,439 --> 00:30:00,437
You be talking nonsense, Mr. Ben.

476
00:30:01,673 --> 00:30:03,841
- Have a good day.
<i>- All right.</i>

477
00:30:04,206 --> 00:30:06,204
<i>See you later on.</i>

478
00:30:06,906 --> 00:30:09,943
<i>And off Ben went
to Georgetown with the weekly shipment</i>

479
00:30:10,439 --> 00:30:13,246
<i>of glasses that Mr. Henson had
so laboriously cleansed</i>

480
00:30:13,706 --> 00:30:17,212
<i>with his polisher of any trace
of their cheap manufacture.</i>

481
00:30:21,606 --> 00:30:23,604
<i>So Grace turned into the alley,</i>

482
00:30:23,906 --> 00:30:27,622
<i>which went by the exotic name
"Glunen Street"...</i>

483
00:30:29,539 --> 00:30:33,635
<i>to knock on the door of the blind,
but only too vain, man.</i>

484
00:30:35,940 --> 00:30:37,938
Yes?

485
00:30:38,272 --> 00:30:41,139
Good morning, Mr. McKay.
My name is Grace.

486
00:30:41,606 --> 00:30:45,202
I was wondering if there's
anything I can do for you.

487
00:30:46,873 --> 00:30:49,360
That's very kind
of you, Grace, but...

488
00:30:49,773 --> 00:30:51,771
<i>I was thinking that perhaps
because of...</i>

489
00:30:52,072 --> 00:30:54,530
the situation that you're in...

490
00:30:54,940 --> 00:30:57,597
What situation am I in?

491
00:30:58,039 --> 00:31:00,037
<i>Ummm...</i>

492
00:31:00,972 --> 00:31:02,505
you're...

493
00:31:02,506 --> 00:31:05,433
you're on... your own.

494
00:31:09,773 --> 00:31:12,380
I've been on my own for so long.

495
00:31:12,806 --> 00:31:15,203
Anything that you might need?

496
00:31:16,839 --> 00:31:18,338
I'm sorry.

497
00:31:18,339 --> 00:31:21,496
Have you ever noticed
the wooden spire

498
00:31:22,005 --> 00:31:24,633
on the roof of the mission house?

499
00:31:25,072 --> 00:31:27,760
At 5:00 in the afternoon,

500
00:31:28,206 --> 00:31:31,773
it points a shadow
at Ginger's grocery store,

501
00:31:32,339 --> 00:31:35,056
right at the "O"

502
00:31:35,506 --> 00:31:38,813
in "Open" on the sign
in the window.

503
00:31:40,706 --> 00:31:44,012
Maybe it's telling people that
it's time to go shopping for supper.

504
00:31:45,706 --> 00:31:48,073
Goodbye, Mr. McKay.

505
00:31:49,639 --> 00:31:51,572
Goodbye, Grace.

506
00:31:51,573 --> 00:31:53,681
<i>Grace's interview with Jack McKay</i>

507
00:31:54,039 --> 00:31:57,406
<i>proved sadly symptomatic
of the attitude in Dogville...</i>

508
00:31:57,939 --> 00:32:00,157
<i>reserved but friendly,</i>

509
00:32:00,539 --> 00:32:02,817
<i>not without curiosity.</i>

510
00:32:04,639 --> 00:32:08,944
<i>Only Jack had expressed his "no"
concisely and precisely.</i>

511
00:32:09,606 --> 00:32:12,353
<i>Martha needed a monologue
almost an hour long</i>

512
00:32:12,806 --> 00:32:14,804
<i>to arrive at the same conclusion.</i>

513
00:32:15,072 --> 00:32:17,290
Oh my goodness.
I... I... I'd have to think

514
00:32:17,673 --> 00:32:20,300
of work for you to do, because
I barely have enough work myself.

515
00:32:21,905 --> 00:32:24,393
<i>So, not very much later,
Grace had ended up</i>

516
00:32:24,806 --> 00:32:26,853
<i>next to Ma Ginger's
gooseberry bushes</i>

517
00:32:27,206 --> 00:32:30,223
<i>in a mood that was not
particularly good.</i>

518
00:32:31,806 --> 00:32:34,703
<i>She could not tell
a gooseberry bush from a cactus,</i>

519
00:32:35,172 --> 00:32:37,889
<i>but the meticulous order
in the yard appealed to her,</i>

520
00:32:38,339 --> 00:32:40,677
<i>such as the metal chains
placed there</i>

521
00:32:41,072 --> 00:32:43,090
<i>in order to shield
the second and third bushes</i>

522
00:32:43,439 --> 00:32:45,437
<i>lest anybody decided to make use</i>

523
00:32:45,539 --> 00:32:49,545
<i>of the deplorably time-honored
shortcut to the old lady's bench.</i>

524
00:32:50,172 --> 00:32:52,540
<i>Grace pulled herself together</i>

525
00:32:52,939 --> 00:32:54,987
<i>and headed towards the store.</i>

526
00:32:58,506 --> 00:33:00,694
- Hello.
<i>- Hi.</i>

527
00:33:01,072 --> 00:33:03,790
Hello. We don't need
any help here either.

528
00:33:04,239 --> 00:33:06,237
<i>I told that to Tom.</i>

529
00:33:06,472 --> 00:33:08,470
Well, it doesn't matter anyway

530
00:33:08,639 --> 00:33:10,637
because there's nothing I can do.

531
00:33:10,838 --> 00:33:12,836
I've never worked
a day in my life, so...

532
00:33:17,139 --> 00:33:20,096
You know, if you put some aloe
on those hands of yours,

533
00:33:20,573 --> 00:33:22,505
<i>they'll be better by the morning.</i>

534
00:33:22,506 --> 00:33:24,504
It's the wood shavings.

535
00:33:24,706 --> 00:33:26,704
I really do hate them.

536
00:33:27,805 --> 00:33:29,883
But I do believe
I'll take your advice.

537
00:33:30,239 --> 00:33:33,196
Your hands are surely the most
alabaster hands I've ever seen.

538
00:33:33,673 --> 00:33:35,860
Here comes Tom. How lucky we are!

539
00:33:37,739 --> 00:33:39,786
- Hi, all. Liz.
<i>- Hello, Tom.</i>

540
00:33:40,139 --> 00:33:41,772
Grace.

541
00:33:41,773 --> 00:33:44,580
- How is all going?
- Not very well, I'm afraid.

542
00:33:45,039 --> 00:33:47,497
<i>- Really?
- No. Nobody needs any help.</i>

543
00:33:47,905 --> 00:33:49,903
Well, I thought
that might be the case.

544
00:33:50,206 --> 00:33:52,574
His plan to make everybody like me

545
00:33:52,972 --> 00:33:54,970
has run into a few problems

546
00:33:55,239 --> 00:33:57,237
because nobody wants me
to work for them.

547
00:33:57,539 --> 00:34:00,166
I would really like to offer
something in return.

548
00:34:02,139 --> 00:34:04,327
<i>You're all running a terrible risk
having me here...</i>

549
00:34:06,673 --> 00:34:08,605
I mean, I'm willing to learn.

550
00:34:08,606 --> 00:34:11,063
There must be somebody
who needs help.

551
00:34:11,472 --> 00:34:14,309
- Mr. McKay's sight is not so good...
- Yes, I went to Mr. McKay.

552
00:34:14,772 --> 00:34:17,460
I went to Martha
and to Chuck and Vera's,

553
00:34:17,905 --> 00:34:19,903
and nobody seems to need any help.

554
00:34:20,172 --> 00:34:23,099
<i>They all think everyone else needs
something, and not themselves.</i>

555
00:34:23,573 --> 00:34:25,571
Funny, that's exactly
what Tom said!

556
00:34:25,872 --> 00:34:28,270
- I suppose he's pleased.
- Well...

557
00:34:28,673 --> 00:34:31,540
Just to prove him wrong...

558
00:34:32,005 --> 00:34:34,633
maybe you can lend a hand here.

559
00:34:35,072 --> 00:34:38,229
But, Ginger, there really isn't
anything we need done.

560
00:34:38,738 --> 00:34:41,286
<i>Perhaps there's something
you don't need doing.</i>

561
00:34:41,706 --> 00:34:43,983
- Anything we don't need done?
<i>- Something...</i>

562
00:34:44,372 --> 00:34:46,370
something that
you would like done,

563
00:34:46,506 --> 00:34:49,023
but that you don't think
is necessary.

564
00:34:49,439 --> 00:34:51,437
What on earth would that be?

565
00:34:51,673 --> 00:34:53,671
<i>Maybe the gooseberry bushes?</i>

566
00:34:53,872 --> 00:34:56,420
The gooseberries are
just fine. Thank you very much.

567
00:34:56,838 --> 00:35:00,055
Not yours. The one that planted
themselves in the tall grass?

568
00:35:00,573 --> 00:35:02,681
<i>We don't grow anything there.</i>

569
00:35:03,039 --> 00:35:04,737
Exactly.

570
00:35:04,738 --> 00:35:06,736
A bit of tidying up.

571
00:35:06,872 --> 00:35:08,572
Who knows,

572
00:35:08,573 --> 00:35:10,571
those bushes might
one day bear fruit.

573
00:35:10,872 --> 00:35:14,089
<i>Yeah, that's true.
That's true. Who knows?</i>

574
00:35:14,606 --> 00:35:16,604
All right, girl.

575
00:35:16,838 --> 00:35:19,006
Those alabaster hands of yours

576
00:35:19,372 --> 00:35:22,968
are hereby engaged to weed
the wild gooseberry bushes.

577
00:35:23,539 --> 00:35:25,471
<i>There you go.</i>

578
00:35:25,472 --> 00:35:27,470
Thank you.

579
00:35:27,738 --> 00:35:29,305
Around...

580
00:35:29,306 --> 00:35:31,304
like this, you see?

581
00:35:31,606 --> 00:35:34,233
<i>Anything too close to them,
just be careful.</i>

582
00:35:34,672 --> 00:35:36,505
There you...!

583
00:35:36,506 --> 00:35:39,193
<i>After a few of the wild
little gooseberry bushes</i>

584
00:35:39,639 --> 00:35:41,657
<i>had given up the ghost in the care</i>

585
00:35:42,005 --> 00:35:44,902
<i>of Grace's as yet unpracticed
alabaster hands,</i>

586
00:35:45,372 --> 00:35:47,560
<i>things began looking up
with the weeding...</i>

587
00:35:47,939 --> 00:35:49,937
- Quick study.
<i>- ...and the town.</i>

588
00:35:51,905 --> 00:35:55,002
<i>In fact, it turned out,
there were not so few things</i>

589
00:35:55,506 --> 00:35:59,282
<i>that the other townsfolk of Dogville
didn't need doing either.</i>

590
00:36:00,838 --> 00:36:02,836
<i>As Ben had no home,</i>

591
00:36:02,905 --> 00:36:06,771
<i>Grace's domestic experiments were
absolutely things he didn't need,</i>

592
00:36:07,372 --> 00:36:10,998
<i>but he put up with them anyhow,
appearing with astonishing punctuality</i>

593
00:36:11,573 --> 00:36:13,820
<i>when the act of domesticity
had been completed,</i>

594
00:36:14,206 --> 00:36:16,204
<i>no matter how unpredictable
business hours</i>

595
00:36:16,339 --> 00:36:19,675
<i>in the freight industry
might otherwise have been.</i>

596
00:36:23,206 --> 00:36:27,452
<i>Olivia didn't need anyone to help June
to the toilet while she was at work,</i>

597
00:36:28,105 --> 00:36:30,533
<i>as hitherto
they had coped splendidly</i>

598
00:36:30,939 --> 00:36:33,487
<i>with Olivia's excellent
diaper arrangement.</i>

599
00:36:36,105 --> 00:36:38,882
<i>If Jack McKay had needed
a partner for conversation,</i>

600
00:36:39,339 --> 00:36:42,815
<i>he would surely have gone out
and gotten one for himself in the town.</i>

601
00:36:43,372 --> 00:36:46,828
<i>So, it was not out of need
that he allowed Grace to sit with him</i>

602
00:36:47,372 --> 00:36:50,529
<i>in his dark parlor with the dramatic
drapes on one wall</i>

603
00:36:51,039 --> 00:36:53,966
<i>for lengthy discussions regarding
the underestimated qualities</i>

604
00:36:54,439 --> 00:36:56,686
<i>of the light on the East Coast.</i>

605
00:36:58,905 --> 00:37:01,592
<i>As Martha wouldn't dream
of burdening the parish</i>

606
00:37:02,039 --> 00:37:04,527
<i>with wear and tear
of the pedals and bellows</i>

607
00:37:04,939 --> 00:37:07,247
<i>while waiting for a new
priest to be appointed,</i>

608
00:37:07,638 --> 00:37:10,266
<i>she practiced without a note
ever leaving the organ.</i>

609
00:37:10,705 --> 00:37:12,703
<i>And was therefore
not really in need</i>

610
00:37:13,039 --> 00:37:15,467
<i>of anyone to turn her pages.</i>

611
00:37:15,872 --> 00:37:17,870
<i>And God knows</i>

612
00:37:18,039 --> 00:37:22,045
<i>that Mr. and Mrs. Henson's son
did not need any help with his books,</i>

613
00:37:22,672 --> 00:37:26,539
<i>and that the family had taken Grace in
for her own sake.</i>

614
00:37:27,139 --> 00:37:29,217
My hands are getting much better.

615
00:37:29,572 --> 00:37:31,570
Yes!

616
00:37:32,139 --> 00:37:34,247
<i>And although
Liz's hands had improved</i>

617
00:37:34,605 --> 00:37:36,538
<i>through Grace's good counsel,</i>

618
00:37:36,539 --> 00:37:40,135
<i>Thomas Edison was a doctor,
and of indisputable health.</i>

619
00:37:40,705 --> 00:37:42,703
<i>And he did not need care or help</i>

620
00:37:43,005 --> 00:37:45,872
<i>with the pills from the medicine
closet with its many secrets.</i>

621
00:37:50,538 --> 00:37:54,405
<i>Actually, Chuck was the only one
"not yet hooked," as Tom put it.</i>

622
00:37:55,005 --> 00:37:57,003
<i>- Hooked?</i>
- Hooked.

623
00:37:57,005 --> 00:37:59,143
You sound so arrogant.

624
00:37:59,506 --> 00:38:01,504
<i>Arrogance is the worst thing!</i>

625
00:38:01,838 --> 00:38:03,836
He doesn't like me.

626
00:38:05,605 --> 00:38:07,603
And he has every right
to feel that way.

627
00:38:07,738 --> 00:38:09,876
<i>Yeah. Listen...</i>

628
00:38:10,239 --> 00:38:13,835
luckily, I've prepared
a Trojan horse.

629
00:38:14,406 --> 00:38:16,404
- A what?
<i>- A Trojan horse.</i>

630
00:38:16,472 --> 00:38:18,470
<i>We can get in by way of Vera.</i>

631
00:38:18,505 --> 00:38:22,571
There's this lecture tomorrow
in Georgetown...

632
00:38:23,206 --> 00:38:25,983
given by some professor.

633
00:38:26,439 --> 00:38:30,445
It's some intellectual thing...

634
00:38:32,039 --> 00:38:34,666
but not so intellectual
he can't tour the provinces with it.

635
00:38:35,105 --> 00:38:38,501
Anyway, the point is,
Vera, she'd do anything to go.

636
00:38:39,039 --> 00:38:41,696
<i>But she's got no one to mind
Achilles while she's gone.</i>

637
00:38:42,139 --> 00:38:45,066
<i>She trusts the girls mastering
their iambic pentameters,</i>

638
00:38:45,538 --> 00:38:47,726
but not with the little one.

639
00:38:48,105 --> 00:38:50,502
So this is where you come in...
I said that you

640
00:38:50,905 --> 00:38:52,903
would watch him
tomorrow afternoon.

641
00:38:52,939 --> 00:38:57,215
Now, I'll try and stall her
on her way home.

642
00:38:57,872 --> 00:39:00,180
With a bit of luck, Chuck
will get back before she does

643
00:39:00,572 --> 00:39:02,880
and you can use the time
and all of your charm

644
00:39:03,272 --> 00:39:05,270
<i>to try and win him over.</i>

645
00:39:05,272 --> 00:39:08,139
I will happily mind Achilles
if Vera will let me.

646
00:39:08,605 --> 00:39:11,443
But if he doesn't like me,
he doesn't like me.

647
00:39:13,306 --> 00:39:17,991
<i>Tom really was enchanted
by this unusual, mysterious creature.</i>

648
00:39:18,705 --> 00:39:21,333
<i>And even though she did not
satisfy his curiosity</i>

649
00:39:21,772 --> 00:39:24,020
<i>by saying anything about her past,</i>

650
00:39:24,406 --> 00:39:26,483
<i>so as not to put anyone in danger,</i>

651
00:39:26,838 --> 00:39:28,836
<i>she still fitted Tom's mission</i>

652
00:39:28,872 --> 00:39:33,028
<i>to educate Dogville on the subject
of acceptance like a glove.</i>

653
00:39:33,672 --> 00:39:35,670
<i>Tom felt content.</i>

654
00:39:35,939 --> 00:39:38,516
<i>Grace had been dangling
over the edge,</i>

655
00:39:38,939 --> 00:39:41,716
<i>and he had been the one
to pull her back onto the path.</i>

656
00:39:42,172 --> 00:39:44,979
<i>It gave him a fine
sensation of mastery,</i>

657
00:39:45,438 --> 00:39:48,276
<i>new for him in terms
of the opposite sex.</i>

658
00:39:48,738 --> 00:39:52,604
<i>And his feelings unleashed
the best in his burgeoning love.</i>

659
00:40:03,872 --> 00:40:05,238
<i>Hello.</i>

660
00:40:05,239 --> 00:40:07,846
This is Dahlia...

661
00:40:08,272 --> 00:40:10,439
Olympia, Diana,

662
00:40:10,805 --> 00:40:12,853
Athena, Pandora,

663
00:40:13,206 --> 00:40:15,204
<i>Jason, Achilles.</i>

664
00:40:15,505 --> 00:40:17,503
Go play.

665
00:40:20,206 --> 00:40:22,171
Your children are lovely.

666
00:40:22,172 --> 00:40:24,389
They are good kids.

667
00:40:26,939 --> 00:40:28,937
And I love them.

668
00:40:34,072 --> 00:40:36,529
<i>Please don't say such
nice things about the kids.</i>

669
00:40:36,939 --> 00:40:39,127
I cry too easily...

670
00:40:41,306 --> 00:40:44,642
both in sorrow and in joy.

671
00:40:45,172 --> 00:40:47,340
<i>- Okay, Vera.
- Hi.</i>

672
00:40:47,705 --> 00:40:49,703
- Ready to go?
<i>- I'm ready.</i>

673
00:40:49,838 --> 00:40:51,976
<i>Thanks for leaving the map out.</i>

674
00:40:52,339 --> 00:40:54,337
I'd have probably
forgot it, I'm sure.

675
00:40:54,405 --> 00:40:56,271
How did you know
I was going that far?

676
00:40:56,272 --> 00:40:58,609
Last time I saw the thermos,

677
00:40:59,005 --> 00:41:01,193
it was on the doorstep
and the map was beside it,

678
00:41:01,572 --> 00:41:03,570
so I just thought...

679
00:41:03,605 --> 00:41:06,382
when I saw the thermos this time
and no map that...

680
00:41:08,805 --> 00:41:10,803
You're a sweet girl, Grace.

681
00:41:12,105 --> 00:41:14,822
- Sweet as Miss Laura.
- Who's Miss Laura?

682
00:41:15,272 --> 00:41:17,270
You gave yourself away again, Bill.

683
00:41:17,405 --> 00:41:21,761
I think Miss Laura is
what Ovid might call a Maenad.

684
00:41:27,206 --> 00:41:29,204
<i>Don't be ashamed, Ben.</i>

685
00:41:30,338 --> 00:41:33,146
We all have the right
to make the most of our lives.

686
00:41:33,605 --> 00:41:35,713
I'm sure that those ladies
in those houses,

687
00:41:36,072 --> 00:41:38,679
they bring a lot of joy
to a lot of men.

688
00:41:40,438 --> 00:41:42,436
Ain't nothing I'm proud of.

689
00:41:44,805 --> 00:41:46,803
It really ain't.

690
00:41:48,538 --> 00:41:50,536
<i>It's all right.</i>

691
00:42:04,105 --> 00:42:06,183
I know what you're doing here.

692
00:42:07,572 --> 00:42:09,570
You do?

693
00:42:10,305 --> 00:42:12,303
You want people to like you...

694
00:42:12,638 --> 00:42:14,636
so you don't have to go away.

695
00:42:16,572 --> 00:42:18,570
You're very smart.

696
00:42:20,772 --> 00:42:22,770
Yes, I like it here in Dogville.

697
00:42:23,105 --> 00:42:26,411
So you want me to read to you

698
00:42:26,939 --> 00:42:28,937
<i>about the Cyclops?</i>

699
00:42:29,206 --> 00:42:31,813
I don't like the Cyclops.

700
00:42:33,471 --> 00:42:35,469
Two eyes are prettier.

701
00:42:37,872 --> 00:42:39,870
Like yours.

702
00:42:44,105 --> 00:42:47,261
If you want my ma to like you
and let you stay,

703
00:42:47,772 --> 00:42:50,110
you just have to be nice to me.

704
00:42:52,838 --> 00:42:55,146
Maybe you should help me
clean up instead.

705
00:42:55,538 --> 00:42:58,166
<i>- Come on.</i>
- My ma says I don't have to work.

706
00:42:58,605 --> 00:43:02,961
- Except in my head.
- But what about if I ask you?

707
00:43:03,638 --> 00:43:05,404
Please?

708
00:43:05,405 --> 00:43:07,403
Okay.

709
00:43:19,738 --> 00:43:21,704
What are you doing here?

710
00:43:21,705 --> 00:43:24,193
<i>Didn't I tell you
we don't need no help from you?</i>

711
00:43:24,605 --> 00:43:27,262
- Ma asked her to mind me and Achilles... <i>
- Quiet! Get out,</i>

712
00:43:27,705 --> 00:43:29,703
the lot of you.

713
00:43:32,505 --> 00:43:34,673
<i>Same nonsense.</i>

714
00:43:35,039 --> 00:43:37,616
<i>They'd have done just great
in antiquity, no doubt.</i>

715
00:43:39,005 --> 00:43:42,481
How's it going otherwise,
with the fooling act?

716
00:43:46,271 --> 00:43:48,269
I wasn't trying to fool anyone.

717
00:43:49,805 --> 00:43:52,732
I mean Dogville.
Has it got you fooled yet?

718
00:43:56,205 --> 00:43:59,682
I thought you were implying
that I was trying to exploit the town.

719
00:44:00,238 --> 00:44:02,606
Wishful thinking.

720
00:44:04,805 --> 00:44:06,771
This town is rotten...

721
00:44:06,772 --> 00:44:08,770
<i>from the inside out.</i>

722
00:44:08,805 --> 00:44:11,352
<i>Wouldn't miss it
if it fell into the gorge tomorrow.</i>

723
00:44:12,738 --> 00:44:14,736
<i>I see no charm here.</i>

724
00:44:18,139 --> 00:44:20,137
You seem to.

725
00:44:21,072 --> 00:44:23,239
<i>Admit it,
you've fallen for Dogville.</i>

726
00:44:25,405 --> 00:44:27,423
The trees, the mountains...

727
00:44:27,772 --> 00:44:29,671
<i>the simple folk,</i>

728
00:44:29,672 --> 00:44:33,128
if all that ain't got you fooled yet,
I bet the cinnamon has.

729
00:44:33,672 --> 00:44:36,709
<i>That damn cinnamon
in those gooseberry pies.</i>

730
00:44:38,305 --> 00:44:40,963
Dogville's got everything
you ever dreamed of in the big city.

731
00:44:41,405 --> 00:44:43,403
You're worse than Tom.

732
00:44:45,105 --> 00:44:47,103
How do you know
what I've dreamed of?

733
00:44:51,672 --> 00:44:54,189
You're from the city yourself,
aren't you?

734
00:44:54,605 --> 00:44:56,237
<i>That was a long time ago.</i>

735
00:44:56,238 --> 00:44:59,635
I'm not that stupid anymore. I found out
that people are the same all over...

736
00:45:00,171 --> 00:45:02,169
<i>greedy as animals.</i>

737
00:45:03,072 --> 00:45:05,209
In a small town they're just
a bit less successful.

738
00:45:05,572 --> 00:45:08,229
Feed them enough,
they'll eat till their bellies burst.

739
00:45:08,672 --> 00:45:10,670
<i>That's why you want
to be rid of me,</i>

740
00:45:10,838 --> 00:45:13,615
because you can't stand
that I remind you

741
00:45:14,072 --> 00:45:16,070
of what it was
you came here to find.

742
00:45:24,438 --> 00:45:26,516
I'm telling you for the last time
to get out of my home.

743
00:45:26,872 --> 00:45:28,980
<i>Moses don't like you,
and I don't like you.</i>

744
00:45:29,338 --> 00:45:31,446
Kids are going crazy enough
from their ma's teaching.

745
00:45:31,805 --> 00:45:33,803
Thank you, Grace.

746
00:45:42,633 --> 00:45:49,258
CHAPTER THREE in which Grace
indulges in a shady piece of provocation.

747
00:45:51,738 --> 00:45:54,365
<i>The two weeks
had passed far too quickly.</i>

748
00:45:54,805 --> 00:45:57,202
<i>Grace had enjoyed herself.</i>

749
00:45:57,605 --> 00:46:00,442
<i>All she could say was
that she was fond of them all,</i>

750
00:46:00,905 --> 00:46:04,801
<i>including the folk who had greeted her
with reluctance and hostility.</i>

751
00:46:06,405 --> 00:46:09,422
<i>Even though she might not have won
everybody over completely,</i>

752
00:46:09,905 --> 00:46:12,302
<i>or even half way, as Tom put it,</i>

753
00:46:12,705 --> 00:46:14,703
<i>she cared for Dogville.</i>

754
00:46:14,805 --> 00:46:16,913
<i>And she had shown the town her face.</i>

755
00:46:17,271 --> 00:46:19,269
<i>Her true face.</i>

756
00:46:19,572 --> 00:46:21,570
<i>But was that enough?</i>

757
00:46:21,572 --> 00:46:24,639
<i>During Jack McKay's
long lecture that evening,</i>

758
00:46:25,138 --> 00:46:28,006
<i>she had found herself
in a heart-searching mood.</i>

759
00:46:28,471 --> 00:46:32,367
<i>Whether heart searching or concern
for her future was the cause,</i>

760
00:46:32,972 --> 00:46:36,688
<i>the result was that
the otherwise so-lovable Grace</i>

761
00:46:37,271 --> 00:46:40,868
<i>indulged in a pretty shady
piece of provocation.</i>

762
00:46:41,438 --> 00:46:43,436
<i>So, you agree...</i>

763
00:46:43,471 --> 00:46:45,779
<i>that the windows in St. Bridget's...</i>

764
00:46:46,171 --> 00:46:48,169
the first time you saw them...

765
00:46:48,205 --> 00:46:50,283
didn't live up
to their reputation?

766
00:46:50,638 --> 00:46:53,505
<i>I don't think it's the position...</i>

767
00:46:53,972 --> 00:46:56,869
of the church itself.

768
00:46:57,338 --> 00:46:59,766
No, no, maybe it's...

769
00:47:00,171 --> 00:47:02,169
the light in Los Angeles,

770
00:47:02,271 --> 00:47:05,428
and the mosaic glass
in those windows.

771
00:47:05,939 --> 00:47:08,046
They kind of collide.

772
00:47:10,305 --> 00:47:12,523
I remember thinking that.

773
00:47:13,971 --> 00:47:15,989
I think we've talked long enough

774
00:47:16,338 --> 00:47:18,556
about the way we remember
seeing things.

775
00:47:18,939 --> 00:47:21,156
<i>- Don't you?
- Well...</i>

776
00:47:21,538 --> 00:47:24,285
Why don't we talk
about something...

777
00:47:25,705 --> 00:47:27,703
that we can see right now?

778
00:47:28,772 --> 00:47:30,910
There's not much
to see around here.

779
00:47:32,605 --> 00:47:34,603
Wretched town.

780
00:47:35,471 --> 00:47:37,469
Why don't we talk about the view?

781
00:47:39,305 --> 00:47:41,303
Well...

782
00:47:41,905 --> 00:47:43,952
I don't go out much.

783
00:47:46,004 --> 00:47:48,342
<i>You know, the... the... the sun...</i>

784
00:47:48,738 --> 00:47:50,437
<i>my skin.</i>

785
00:47:50,438 --> 00:47:53,535
Yesterday, I was walking
in Chuck's apple trees.

786
00:47:55,605 --> 00:47:58,382
If you go right up
to the edge of the cliff...

787
00:47:59,938 --> 00:48:02,276
you just manage to peer
around Ben's garage,

788
00:48:02,672 --> 00:48:05,389
and you get a view of your house
from the side facing the gorge.

789
00:48:05,838 --> 00:48:09,204
- Well.
- I didn't realize there was...

790
00:48:10,738 --> 00:48:13,075
windows behind there.

791
00:48:13,471 --> 00:48:15,469
Huge windows.

792
00:48:17,305 --> 00:48:19,733
It must be a wonderful view.

793
00:48:21,405 --> 00:48:23,683
<i>Would you mind if I opened them?</i>

794
00:49:05,271 --> 00:49:07,489
<i>You're no fool, Miss Grace.</i>

795
00:49:10,305 --> 00:49:12,303
You're no fool.

796
00:49:13,605 --> 00:49:16,971
<i>You probably see that
those curtains are hard to open.</i>

797
00:49:17,505 --> 00:49:19,503
I'm sorry.

798
00:49:21,505 --> 00:49:24,492
<i>And obviously concluded
it's because...</i>

799
00:49:24,971 --> 00:49:27,779
- I'm sorry.
<i>- ...they're not used very often.</i>

800
00:49:30,338 --> 00:49:32,336
But the view is good.

801
00:49:34,104 --> 00:49:36,102
Entrancing, even.

802
00:49:40,171 --> 00:49:42,169
<i>So...</i>

803
00:49:44,205 --> 00:49:47,422
ask me why a man
who loves the light...

804
00:49:50,038 --> 00:49:52,206
hanged these heavy curtains.

805
00:49:59,505 --> 00:50:02,961
Yes, I'm blind.

806
00:50:04,638 --> 00:50:07,005
Not weak-sighted,

807
00:50:07,405 --> 00:50:09,423
not myopic,

808
00:50:09,772 --> 00:50:11,770
blind.

809
00:50:13,738 --> 00:50:16,255
So...

810
00:50:16,672 --> 00:50:18,779
please go...

811
00:50:22,938 --> 00:50:25,106
<i>and let me be that on my own.</i>

812
00:50:31,871 --> 00:50:34,009
<i>In Switzerland,</i>

813
00:50:34,371 --> 00:50:36,337
<i>they call it</i>

814
00:50:36,338 --> 00:50:40,054
the <i>Alpenglünen.</i>

815
00:50:42,505 --> 00:50:44,437
That's the light

816
00:50:44,438 --> 00:50:47,155
that reflects
from the highest peaks,

817
00:50:47,605 --> 00:50:49,852
after the sun

818
00:50:50,238 --> 00:50:52,666
<i>goes down behind the mountains.</i>

819
00:50:54,938 --> 00:50:57,276
And now it's gone.

820
00:51:21,305 --> 00:51:23,303
<i>It was in complete silence</i>

821
00:51:23,405 --> 00:51:26,392
<i>that the people of Dogville turned up
for the meeting at the mission house</i>

822
00:51:26,871 --> 00:51:30,378
<i>two weeks to the day since
the beautiful fugitive had come to town.</i>

823
00:51:32,904 --> 00:51:36,800
<i>Grace was standing beside Tom,
watching them convene</i>

824
00:51:37,405 --> 00:51:40,741
<i>and knew inside herself
that this might well be the last time</i>

825
00:51:41,271 --> 00:51:44,458
<i>she would see
these now-so-familiar faces.</i>

826
00:51:44,971 --> 00:51:47,049
<i>She had at least
two of them against her,</i>

827
00:51:47,405 --> 00:51:50,502
<i>and even one
would have been too many.</i>

828
00:51:51,004 --> 00:51:53,002
Welcome,

829
00:51:53,071 --> 00:51:54,437
good people of Dogville,

830
00:51:54,438 --> 00:51:56,436
two weeks...

831
00:51:56,572 --> 00:51:58,570
two weeks have passed

832
00:51:58,672 --> 00:52:01,708
and it's time for your verdict.

833
00:52:02,205 --> 00:52:05,861
Is it right that she should be here
while we talk?

834
00:52:06,438 --> 00:52:08,486
<i>Well, Mrs. Henson,
when Grace first came,</i>

835
00:52:08,837 --> 00:52:10,885
she made no attempt
to hide her weakness from us,

836
00:52:11,238 --> 00:52:13,606
I think it's only right
that we'd be as open with her.

837
00:52:14,004 --> 00:52:16,612
Tell her to her face if we...

838
00:52:17,038 --> 00:52:19,036
want her to leave.

839
00:52:19,371 --> 00:52:21,369
No, Mrs. Henson's right.

840
00:52:21,704 --> 00:52:24,771
Nobody should be prevented
from speaking their mind

841
00:52:25,271 --> 00:52:27,349
<i>out of politeness.</i>

842
00:52:27,704 --> 00:52:29,922
I'll wait at the mine

843
00:52:30,305 --> 00:52:32,852
and if the vote says
that I should leave,

844
00:52:33,271 --> 00:52:35,269
then I'll take the path
across the...

845
00:52:35,438 --> 00:52:37,655
across the mountains
while it's still light.

846
00:52:38,038 --> 00:52:40,036
<i>All of the things
that I've borrowed,</i>

847
00:52:40,338 --> 00:52:42,336
if you could return them
to everybody.

848
00:52:42,605 --> 00:52:45,851
- Of course.
- Nobody has to see me before I go.

849
00:52:46,371 --> 00:52:49,528
Martha, if you'll just ring the bell,
then I'll understand.

850
00:52:50,038 --> 00:52:51,703
Well, I don't...

851
00:52:51,704 --> 00:52:53,702
how do you want me
to ring the bell?

852
00:52:54,038 --> 00:52:57,195
Just ring it for every vote
that lets me stay.

853
00:52:57,704 --> 00:52:59,752
<i>I'll count.</i>

854
00:53:00,104 --> 00:53:02,791
<i>And if it doesn't reach 15, then...</i>

855
00:53:03,238 --> 00:53:05,635
then I'll leave.

856
00:53:13,538 --> 00:53:16,964
Tom is anxious
to speak in her behalf,

857
00:53:17,505 --> 00:53:19,553
but I think he's had
his allotted time.

858
00:53:19,904 --> 00:53:22,332
We know his view. We respect it.

859
00:53:22,737 --> 00:53:24,735
And now he must respect ours.

860
00:53:26,071 --> 00:53:28,069
<i>Grace pulled her bundle out</i>

861
00:53:28,171 --> 00:53:30,539
<i>from under the bureau
to change into her own clothes</i>

862
00:53:30,938 --> 00:53:33,366
<i>only to discover
that somebody had been in it</i>

863
00:53:33,771 --> 00:53:35,769
<i>and left a loaf of bread.</i>

864
00:53:37,305 --> 00:53:40,112
<i>Next to it
was a folded sheet of paper.</i>

865
00:53:40,572 --> 00:53:43,229
<i>It was a map Tom had drawn.</i>

866
00:53:43,671 --> 00:53:46,688
<i>He had known where the bundle was
and had put it there.</i>

867
00:53:47,171 --> 00:53:49,419
<i>It showed the path
across the mountain,</i>

868
00:53:49,804 --> 00:53:51,882
<i>and all the dangerous spots
were furnished</i>

869
00:53:52,238 --> 00:53:54,635
<i>with witty horrific little sketches.</i>

870
00:53:56,637 --> 00:53:58,635
<i>But there was more...</i>

871
00:53:58,704 --> 00:54:01,162
<i>several people
had had the same idea.</i>

872
00:54:01,571 --> 00:54:04,319
<i>They had eased gifts
into the bundle for her.</i>

873
00:54:04,771 --> 00:54:09,017
<i>Jason's beloved little penknife
lay there, all polished and shiny.</i>

874
00:54:09,671 --> 00:54:12,568
<i>And a pie
from Ma Ginger and Gloria.</i>

875
00:54:13,038 --> 00:54:15,785
<i>And some clothing
and matches and a hymnal.</i>

876
00:54:16,238 --> 00:54:18,516
<i>Grace opened it at number 18</i>

877
00:54:18,904 --> 00:54:21,561
<i>where Martha always had trouble
with the fingering,</i>

878
00:54:23,305 --> 00:54:26,492
<i>and between the pages,
lay a dollar bill.</i>

879
00:54:27,004 --> 00:54:29,581
<i>Martha alone
could not have afforded it.</i>

880
00:54:31,071 --> 00:54:33,499
<i>Grace had friends in Dogville.</i>

881
00:54:33,904 --> 00:54:35,437
<i>That was for sure.</i>

882
00:54:35,438 --> 00:54:38,834
<i>Whether they were few or many
did not matter a jot.</i>

883
00:54:39,371 --> 00:54:41,588
<i>Grace had bared her throat
to the town</i>

884
00:54:41,971 --> 00:54:44,868
<i>and it had responded
with a great gift...</i>

885
00:54:45,338 --> 00:54:47,336
<i>with friends.</i>

886
00:54:52,138 --> 00:54:55,295
<i>No gangster could deprive her
of this meeting with the township,</i>

887
00:54:55,804 --> 00:54:58,521
<i>no matter how many guns
in the world.</i>

888
00:54:58,971 --> 00:55:01,598
<i>And should the strokes of the bell
not reach 15,</i>

889
00:55:02,038 --> 00:55:04,875
<i>she knew now that she meant
something to the town</i>

890
00:55:05,338 --> 00:55:07,555
<i>and that her stay
had been of significance.</i>

891
00:55:07,938 --> 00:55:09,936
<i>Not much perhaps,</i>

892
00:55:09,971 --> 00:55:13,368
<i>but nevertheless
a trace she had left.</i>

893
00:55:13,904 --> 00:55:15,902
<i>And the first in her young life</i>

894
00:55:16,171 --> 00:55:18,249
<i>in which she took pride.</i>

895
00:55:32,104 --> 00:55:35,381
<i>Grace stiffened
as the bell began its toll.</i>

896
00:56:12,004 --> 00:56:14,661
Twelve.

897
00:56:18,671 --> 00:56:20,370
14...

898
00:56:20,371 --> 00:56:23,238
<i>14, Grace counted.</i>

899
00:56:23,704 --> 00:56:27,071
<i>So McKay must have
voted for her after all.</i>

900
00:56:27,604 --> 00:56:29,602
<i>And if so,</i>

901
00:56:29,904 --> 00:56:32,332
<i>why not Chuck too?</i>

902
00:57:13,837 --> 00:57:15,835
Everyone?

903
00:57:16,704 --> 00:57:18,702
- And Chuck.
<i>- Chuck?!</i>

904
00:57:18,737 --> 00:57:20,735
<i>Everyone.</i>

905
00:57:21,737 --> 00:57:23,735
I think they like you here.

906
00:57:38,133 --> 00:57:42,467
CHAPTER FOUR
"Happy times in Dogville"

907
00:57:42,537 --> 00:57:45,464
<i>The period of spring and early summer</i>

908
00:57:45,938 --> 00:57:47,836
<i>proved a happy one for Grace.</i>

909
00:57:47,837 --> 00:57:51,373
<i>Martha rang the hours,
conducting her through the day,</i>

910
00:57:51,938 --> 00:57:54,455
<i>so she could serve
as eyes for McKay,</i>

911
00:57:54,871 --> 00:57:57,448
<i>- a mother for Ben, -</i> Right.

912
00:57:57,871 --> 00:58:00,089
<i>A friend for Vera,</i>

913
00:58:00,470 --> 00:58:02,898
<i>and brains for Bill.</i>

914
00:58:12,737 --> 00:58:14,735
<i>And one day it had
occurred to Grace</i>

915
00:58:15,071 --> 00:58:17,069
<i>to tread the pedals herself</i>

916
00:58:17,404 --> 00:58:19,270
<i>so as to get Martha to agree</i>

917
00:58:19,271 --> 00:58:21,103
<i>to play a couple of proper notes</i>

918
00:58:21,104 --> 00:58:23,851
<i>just to empty the bellows naturally
so that they wouldn't be</i>

919
00:58:24,304 --> 00:58:27,142
<i>left under pressure
and thus be spoiled.</i>

920
00:58:27,604 --> 00:58:29,602
<i>And now they had tacitly agreed</i>

921
00:58:29,904 --> 00:58:32,801
<i>that as long as it was Grace
who trod the pedals</i>

922
00:58:33,271 --> 00:58:35,788
<i>Martha could play
without feeling any guilt.</i>

923
00:58:40,938 --> 00:58:44,334
<i>To Tom's pop, the old doctor
who imagined he had a new ailment</i>

924
00:58:44,871 --> 00:58:47,328
<i>every single day and was thus
increasingly addicted</i>

925
00:58:47,737 --> 00:58:50,754
<i>to the simpler coordination tests
from his medical school days,</i>

926
00:58:51,238 --> 00:58:53,070
<i>she had to be severe,</i>

927
00:58:53,071 --> 00:58:56,407
<i>telling him that there was
nothing wrong with him.</i>

928
00:58:58,304 --> 00:59:00,912
<i>And now since the town had agreed</i>

929
00:59:01,337 --> 00:59:03,505
<i>that everyone was to give
according to his abilities,</i>

930
00:59:03,871 --> 00:59:05,979
<i>she received wages... not much,</i>

931
00:59:06,337 --> 00:59:07,736
<i>but enough to save up</i>

932
00:59:07,737 --> 00:59:09,735
<i>for the first of the tiny
china figurines</i>

933
00:59:09,871 --> 00:59:12,119
<i>from the row of seven
that had stood for so long</i>

934
00:59:12,504 --> 00:59:14,932
<i>gathering dust in the window
of the store.</i>

935
00:59:16,871 --> 00:59:18,869
<i>And she dreamed that in time,</i>

936
00:59:18,971 --> 00:59:21,189
<i>she would be able
to acquire them all.</i>

937
00:59:22,637 --> 00:59:24,570
- Don't make sense.
- I wanted to be...

938
00:59:24,571 --> 00:59:27,818
<i>Slowly those alabaster hands
turned into a pair of hands</i>

939
00:59:28,337 --> 00:59:32,283
<i>that could have belonged to anyone
