940
00:59:32,904 --> 00:59:36,820
<i>And three weeks later,
she triumphantly moved into a place</i>

941
00:59:37,437 --> 00:59:39,625
<i>Tom and Ben had secretly restored...</i>

942
00:59:40,004 --> 00:59:42,002
<i>namely the old mill,</i>

943
00:59:42,171 --> 00:59:44,858
<i>which had once held
the town's ore crusher,</i>

944
00:59:45,304 --> 00:59:48,991
<i>but of which only the heavy
flywheel now remained.</i>

945
00:59:55,904 --> 00:59:57,336
Thanks.

946
00:59:57,337 --> 00:59:59,335
See, that's what I'm talking about

947
00:59:59,470 --> 01:00:01,468
with the freight industry.

948
01:00:01,637 --> 01:00:04,974
Miss Laura had thrown that out.
It was no use to anybody

949
01:00:05,504 --> 01:00:07,582
just a good thing
in the wrong place, but...

950
01:00:07,938 --> 01:00:09,936
From a truck, you know?

951
01:00:10,204 --> 01:00:12,662
You shouldn't poke fun
at the freight industry, that's all.

952
01:00:14,470 --> 01:00:16,838
No, you're right, Ben,
they shouldn't.

953
01:00:24,071 --> 01:00:26,069
Grace?

954
01:00:27,138 --> 01:00:28,703
<i>What?</i>

955
01:00:28,704 --> 01:00:30,982
I just had to tell you I had
a really selfish reason

956
01:00:31,370 --> 01:00:33,618
for voting to keep you
in Dogville.

957
01:00:37,837 --> 01:00:39,835
What was it?

958
01:00:41,170 --> 01:00:43,338
It was such a relief
when you turned up,

959
01:00:43,704 --> 01:00:45,702
and you were the one
all the men had eyes for.

960
01:00:46,004 --> 01:00:48,052
<i>-</i> You know, Tom and them?

961
01:00:50,170 --> 01:00:52,168
I had to put up with it for long.

962
01:00:53,470 --> 01:00:55,868
Frankly, I just didn't have
the energy for it anymore.

963
01:00:57,237 --> 01:00:59,235
They'll always have eyes
for you, Liz.

964
01:01:01,337 --> 01:01:03,335
You know that.

965
01:01:03,871 --> 01:01:06,119
- They will.
- Okay.

966
01:01:06,504 --> 01:01:08,502
<i>- You're beautiful.</i>
- Thank you, Grace.

967
01:01:10,137 --> 01:01:11,770
<i>The very latest development</i>

968
01:01:11,771 --> 01:01:13,939
<i>now that summer was at its peak</i>

969
01:01:14,304 --> 01:01:15,937
<i>was that Grace had been given leave</i>

970
01:01:15,938 --> 01:01:18,625
<i>to help Chuck in the orchard.</i>

971
01:01:19,071 --> 01:01:21,618
<i>And every day at 5:00,
once their work was done,</i>

972
01:01:22,038 --> 01:01:25,344
<i>she could appreciate
that actually McKay was right.</i>

973
01:01:25,871 --> 01:01:27,803
<i>The shadow of the spire</i>

974
01:01:27,804 --> 01:01:30,641
<i>did indeed point at Ma Ginger's store.</i>

975
01:01:33,404 --> 01:01:36,062
<i>But today</i>

976
01:01:36,504 --> 01:01:39,251
<i>the tower did not only announce
that it was time to go shopping,</i>

977
01:01:39,704 --> 01:01:43,890
<i>but also... by a signal which nobody,
despite Martha's initial concerns,</i>

978
01:01:44,537 --> 01:01:47,055
<i>could have confused
with the ringing of the hours...</i>

979
01:01:47,470 --> 01:01:49,658
<i>a warning that somebody
was approaching</i>

980
01:01:50,038 --> 01:01:52,435
<i>by a canyon road from Georgetown.</i>

981
01:01:52,837 --> 01:01:54,835
<i>For the first time in living memory</i>

982
01:01:55,004 --> 01:01:57,691
<i>law enforcers had come to Dogville.</i>

983
01:02:07,938 --> 01:02:09,936
Good evening, sir.

984
01:02:11,304 --> 01:02:13,522
<i>This the whole place?</i>

985
01:02:13,904 --> 01:02:16,651
<i>- Is there a town hall?
- No.</i>

986
01:02:17,103 --> 01:02:19,241
I got me a notice to paste up.

987
01:02:19,604 --> 01:02:21,403
We've got the mission house.

988
01:02:21,404 --> 01:02:23,622
<i>- That do you?</i>
- Sure.

989
01:02:25,237 --> 01:02:26,836
<i>What'd she do?</i>

990
01:02:26,837 --> 01:02:28,835
Missing, that's all it says.

991
01:02:28,837 --> 01:02:31,464
I guess somebody's
been missing her.

992
01:02:31,904 --> 01:02:34,421
Heard tell she was
last seen around here.

993
01:02:34,837 --> 01:02:37,324
We're putting these things up
all over the county.

994
01:02:38,938 --> 01:02:41,425
<i>If somebody sees her,
they ought to go to the police?</i>

995
01:02:41,837 --> 01:02:43,835
I guess that's the idea.

996
01:03:15,804 --> 01:03:18,461
These men were never
gonna give in easily.

997
01:03:18,904 --> 01:03:22,800
<i>Now these posters,
they hang all over the county...</i>

998
01:03:25,404 --> 01:03:27,712
which means nobody suspects
she's right here with us.

999
01:03:28,103 --> 01:03:30,036
No, but it was a policeman, Tom.

1000
01:03:30,037 --> 01:03:32,035
Isn't it a duty to respond
to the police?

1001
01:03:32,304 --> 01:03:35,141
I mean legally speaking.

1002
01:03:35,604 --> 01:03:38,231
I... I'm sorry.

1003
01:03:38,671 --> 01:03:41,038
I just...
when I get upset, I cough.

1004
01:03:41,437 --> 01:03:43,575
She's a missing person,
she hasn't done anything.

1005
01:03:43,938 --> 01:03:46,365
<i>- He even said so.</i>
- I think you should vote again.

1006
01:03:46,771 --> 01:03:49,198
<i>Why?
We can't resort to plebiscites</i>

1007
01:03:49,604 --> 01:03:51,792
time and time again.

1008
01:03:53,404 --> 01:03:55,402
<i>Come on,</i>

1009
01:03:55,537 --> 01:03:58,524
who's really got cold feet
because of a picture and piece of paper?

1010
01:04:15,175 --> 01:04:20,133
CHAPTER FIVE
"Fourth of July after all"

1011
01:04:23,103 --> 01:04:25,101
<i>The fourth of July came</i>

1012
01:04:25,337 --> 01:04:28,464
<i>with huge clouds of seeds
from some remote meadow</i>

1013
01:04:28,970 --> 01:04:32,157
<i>gracefully floating down Elm Street
in the early evening.</i>

1014
01:04:32,671 --> 01:04:35,248
<i>Today was a day for celebration.</i>

1015
01:04:35,671 --> 01:04:37,948
<i>Nobody was to worry
about the hard times.</i>

1016
01:04:38,337 --> 01:04:41,404
<i>And Grace could stop
at Ma Ginger's window quite content</i>

1017
01:04:41,904 --> 01:04:45,650
<i>to ascertain that only two
of the little china figurines remained.</i>

1018
01:04:46,237 --> 01:04:48,169
<i>And were thus the only two</i>

1019
01:04:48,170 --> 01:04:51,157
<i>she had not yet been able
to save up enough to purchase.</i>

1020
01:04:56,270 --> 01:04:58,268
It looks great, girls.

1021
01:05:00,003 --> 01:05:02,491
Grace, will you put in
a couple of hours with me?

1022
01:05:02,903 --> 01:05:04,901
In the orchard again today?

1023
01:05:05,070 --> 01:05:07,937
It's real nice down there
with the sunshine.

1024
01:05:08,404 --> 01:05:10,402
Chuck, it's the Fourth of July.

1025
01:05:11,671 --> 01:05:14,158
What are you talking
about sunshine for?

1026
01:05:14,571 --> 01:05:16,998
<i>Have you turned
into a romantic like me?</i>

1027
01:05:21,637 --> 01:05:23,635
- No.
<i>- We're gonna have fun.</i>

1028
01:05:24,871 --> 01:05:26,978
During the winter,
we'll all starve.

1029
01:05:27,337 --> 01:05:29,795
Even Ben's taking the day off.

1030
01:05:31,870 --> 01:05:33,948
- Hi.
- Hey, Tom.

1031
01:05:34,304 --> 01:05:36,302
Gracie, you got a moment?

1032
01:05:38,671 --> 01:05:41,598
- Now?
<i>- Yeah.</i>

1033
01:05:42,070 --> 01:05:44,088
I've got something
interesting to tell you.

1034
01:05:46,304 --> 01:05:48,302
Well, it has to be quick.

1035
01:05:55,437 --> 01:05:58,714
I got so much going on in my head.

1036
01:05:59,237 --> 01:06:01,255
That must be very tiring for you.

1037
01:06:03,470 --> 01:06:06,597
I think I've done a pretty good analysis
of the folks in this town and...

1038
01:06:09,737 --> 01:06:12,104
I think I understand them...

1039
01:06:14,003 --> 01:06:16,001
in a meaningful way.

1040
01:06:18,070 --> 01:06:20,408
<i>But when I come to decipher you,</i>

1041
01:06:20,804 --> 01:06:22,802
<i>I get absolutely nowhere.</i>

1042
01:06:24,237 --> 01:06:26,235
You know, Liz...

1043
01:06:27,137 --> 01:06:29,135
Liz is easy to read.

1044
01:06:31,671 --> 01:06:34,128
And there was some
attraction between us.

1045
01:06:37,903 --> 01:06:40,531
But as I can see right through her,

1046
01:06:40,970 --> 01:06:43,867
intellectually, I mean,
I can see right through her.

1047
01:06:44,337 --> 01:06:48,143
My desire was purely of a physical...

1048
01:06:50,204 --> 01:06:52,202
<i>physical nature.</i>

1049
01:06:54,671 --> 01:06:56,669
But with you

1050
01:06:57,003 --> 01:06:59,001
it's...

1051
01:06:59,337 --> 01:07:01,944
<i>- What?
- It's more... it's more complicated.</i>

1052
01:07:02,370 --> 01:07:04,368
What are you trying to say?

1053
01:07:07,270 --> 01:07:09,458
No, I should get it clearer
in my head first.

1054
01:07:12,637 --> 01:07:14,745
Are you trying to say that...

1055
01:07:17,404 --> 01:07:19,402
you're in love with me?

1056
01:07:21,470 --> 01:07:23,468
No, I wouldn't...

1057
01:07:26,604 --> 01:07:28,602
Love is what... it's not...

1058
01:07:32,037 --> 01:07:34,035
It's a big word... yeah.

1059
01:07:38,370 --> 01:07:40,368
Yeah.

1060
01:07:41,470 --> 01:07:43,488
Well, that's good.

1061
01:07:46,937 --> 01:07:48,935
Because...

1062
01:07:52,337 --> 01:07:54,675
I think that I'm in love with you too.

1063
01:07:57,537 --> 01:07:59,535
Very interesting, isn't it?

1064
01:08:01,836 --> 01:08:04,324
I mean it's interesting
in a psychological...

1065
01:08:11,637 --> 01:08:13,635
Did they call you?
I think they're...

1066
01:08:14,770 --> 01:08:16,768
calling you.

1067
01:08:19,370 --> 01:08:21,368
I didn't hear them.

1068
01:08:24,037 --> 01:08:26,035
No.

1069
01:08:28,470 --> 01:08:30,169
You should...

1070
01:08:30,170 --> 01:08:32,218
probably get back anyway.

1071
01:08:35,637 --> 01:08:38,733
I'll see you at the wedding...
celebration. Sorry.

1072
01:08:43,337 --> 01:08:45,335
<i>America</i>

1073
01:08:46,370 --> 01:08:48,368
<i>America</i>

1074
01:08:48,670 --> 01:08:53,296
<i>God shed his grace on thee</i>

1075
01:08:54,003 --> 01:08:58,069
<i>And crown thy good
with brotherhood</i>

1076
01:08:58,703 --> 01:09:03,209
<i>From sea to shining sea.</i>

1077
01:09:04,870 --> 01:09:06,868
- Bravo.
- Yay.

1078
01:09:08,170 --> 01:09:09,702
<i>Well done!</i>

1079
01:09:14,370 --> 01:09:17,117
This year I didn't bring
any notes with me

1080
01:09:17,571 --> 01:09:20,378
because I'm not gonna pretend
I can read them.

1081
01:09:23,437 --> 01:09:25,575
Which brings me to a point,

1082
01:09:25,937 --> 01:09:28,015
a point I want to make.

1083
01:09:28,370 --> 01:09:30,647
And that point is,

1084
01:09:31,037 --> 01:09:33,035
<i>you, Grace.</i>

1085
01:09:33,204 --> 01:09:35,602
<i>Yes, you've made Dogville</i>

1086
01:09:36,003 --> 01:09:38,431
<i>a wonderful place to live in.</i>

1087
01:09:40,470 --> 01:09:41,969
Yeah, as a matter of fact,

1088
01:09:41,970 --> 01:09:46,186
somebody tells me they ran
into grumpy old Chuck on the street

1089
01:09:46,836 --> 01:09:49,703
<i>and he was actually smiling.</i>

1090
01:09:51,537 --> 01:09:53,754
<i>Well, I've never
seen your smile, Grace,</i>

1091
01:09:54,137 --> 01:09:58,053
<i>but I will bet you
I could describe it.</i>

1092
01:10:00,370 --> 01:10:02,857
Because it obviously has every color

1093
01:10:03,270 --> 01:10:06,137
that's refracted from the shiniest

1094
01:10:06,603 --> 01:10:08,681
<i>prism in the world.</i>

1095
01:10:09,037 --> 01:10:11,205
<i>And you probably have a face
to match that?</i>

1096
01:10:11,571 --> 01:10:13,503
<i>Does she have a face
to match that, Tom?</i>

1097
01:10:13,504 --> 01:10:14,869
<i>Yes, sir.</i>

1098
01:10:14,870 --> 01:10:16,888
<i>- Yes, sir.
- I'll bet she does.</i>

1099
01:10:17,237 --> 01:10:19,844
We are proud to have you among us.

1100
01:10:21,470 --> 01:10:24,746
And we thank you

1101
01:10:25,270 --> 01:10:27,488
<i>for showing us who you are.</i>

1102
01:10:28,870 --> 01:10:30,978
Here's to you, Grace.

1103
01:10:31,337 --> 01:10:33,475
<i>Stay with us as long
as you damn please.</i>

1104
01:10:33,836 --> 01:10:36,054
To Grace.

1105
01:10:50,937 --> 01:10:52,935
Stop!

1106
01:10:57,370 --> 01:10:59,368
A police car
has just been seen in town

1107
01:10:59,470 --> 01:11:01,987
and it's just made the turn
up Canyon Road.

1108
01:11:02,404 --> 01:11:04,921
- So he'll be here any minute.
- Should I ring the bell?

1109
01:11:06,903 --> 01:11:08,901
No, Martha, Grace probably heard.

1110
01:11:10,670 --> 01:11:13,218
- We'll get rid of him quickly-<i>-
-</i> Better go, honey, go.

1111
01:11:13,636 --> 01:11:15,634
Don't worry.

1112
01:11:28,204 --> 01:11:31,361
Should have been celebrating myself
if this hadn't have come up.

1113
01:11:31,870 --> 01:11:34,857
I got to change this
missing persons notice.

1114
01:11:36,304 --> 01:11:38,412
It's that lady again.

1115
01:11:39,736 --> 01:11:41,734
It's why she disappeared.

1116
01:11:43,503 --> 01:11:47,280
She's wanted in connection with some
bank robberies on the West Coast.

1117
01:11:47,870 --> 01:11:50,418
<i>When did these robberies take place?</i>

1118
01:11:50,836 --> 01:11:52,769
Last couple of weeks.

1119
01:11:52,770 --> 01:11:55,927
- All right.
- <i>You don't get much news up here?</i>

1120
01:11:56,437 --> 01:11:59,044
My dad's radio only plays music.

1121
01:12:01,204 --> 01:12:03,861
All I know is they say
she's dangerous...

1122
01:12:04,304 --> 01:12:08,310
and that anyone with any information
about her better call us pronto.

1123
01:12:08,937 --> 01:12:10,935
<i>That's the law.</i>

1124
01:12:24,870 --> 01:12:26,868
<i>Two weeks.</i>

1125
01:12:29,237 --> 01:12:31,235
Can't be our girl, Tom.

1126
01:12:31,503 --> 01:12:33,781
- No, she's been here all the time.
- <i>Right.</i>

1127
01:12:34,170 --> 01:12:36,338
She couldn't have done
what they're accusing her of.

1128
01:12:37,937 --> 01:12:39,935
<i>No, that's true, Tom, you're right.</i>

1129
01:12:40,204 --> 01:12:42,511
Still it's an unpleasant business
just the same.

1130
01:12:50,503 --> 01:12:53,191
<i>Grace was the same and so was the town.</i>

1131
01:12:54,636 --> 01:12:56,634
<i>That the gangsters had fixed
to have charges</i>

1132
01:12:56,870 --> 01:12:59,238
<i>made against Grace
and their efforts to neutralize her</i>

1133
01:12:59,636 --> 01:13:01,744
<i>came as no surprise.</i>

1134
01:13:03,204 --> 01:13:06,071
<i>But everything had changed a little
yet again.</i>

1135
01:13:06,536 --> 01:13:09,873
I'm telling you, you have exactly
the same kind of little lump

1136
01:13:10,404 --> 01:13:13,061
in exactly the same spot
on the other side of your back.

1137
01:13:13,503 --> 01:13:15,581
- Really?
- I can only assume...

1138
01:13:18,037 --> 01:13:20,375
that it belongs on your body.

1139
01:13:20,770 --> 01:13:22,938
But you are the doctor,

1140
01:13:23,304 --> 01:13:25,382
so...

1141
01:13:25,736 --> 01:13:27,734
It's very unlikely, don't you think,

1142
01:13:28,070 --> 01:13:31,027
that a cancer would develop
in such precise symmetry?

1143
01:13:31,503 --> 01:13:33,781
- Mr. Edison, please-<i>-
-</i> No, don't you... I mean...

1144
01:13:34,170 --> 01:13:36,747
- we have been over this so many times.
- Anything's possible.

1145
01:13:37,170 --> 01:13:39,168
I think you have to accept the fact

1146
01:13:39,503 --> 01:13:42,111
that you are an exceptionally healthy

1147
01:13:42,536 --> 01:13:44,534
elderly gentleman.

1148
01:13:44,703 --> 01:13:47,131
I'm gonna rest just the same.

1149
01:13:47,536 --> 01:13:49,534
<i>I'll see you in the morning.</i>

1150
01:13:49,603 --> 01:13:51,601
I hope so.

1151
01:13:51,703 --> 01:13:54,041
What? What did they say?

1152
01:13:54,436 --> 01:13:56,434
<i>Well...</i>

1153
01:13:58,670 --> 01:14:01,537
I couldn't really argue
that anything had changed, but...

1154
01:14:02,003 --> 01:14:06,189
by not telling the police they felt that
they were committing a crime themselves.

1155
01:14:10,503 --> 01:14:12,468
- I think I should leave.
<i>- No.</i>

1156
01:14:12,469 --> 01:14:14,717
- Enough is enough.
<i>- I have suggested the opposite.</i>

1157
01:14:16,536 --> 01:14:20,432
<i>- You did?
- From a business perspective...</i>

1158
01:14:23,369 --> 01:14:25,887
from a business prospective your...

1159
01:14:26,304 --> 01:14:28,821
your presence in Dogville
has become more costly...

1160
01:14:30,369 --> 01:14:33,526
<i>because it's more dangerous
for them to have you here...</i>

1161
01:14:34,037 --> 01:14:36,035
<i>not that they don't want you.</i>

1162
01:14:37,037 --> 01:14:39,844
It's just they feel
there should be some

1163
01:14:40,304 --> 01:14:42,302
counterbalance.

1164
01:14:43,304 --> 01:14:45,302
Some quid pro quo.

1165
01:14:45,304 --> 01:14:47,821
That sounds like words
the gangsters would use.

1166
01:14:48,237 --> 01:14:51,953
But there is also more of an incentive
for you to want to stay.

1167
01:14:55,469 --> 01:14:58,536
<i>See, with all of those wanted posters
hanging around the place,</i>

1168
01:14:59,037 --> 01:15:01,964
I can hardly think of anywhere else
you could hide.

1169
01:15:04,369 --> 01:15:07,356
So what's the counterbalance
that you suggest?

1170
01:15:07,836 --> 01:15:09,834
Right, well...

1171
01:15:11,003 --> 01:15:13,281
they wanted you
to work longer hours.

1172
01:15:15,170 --> 01:15:17,036
But instead, what I proposed

1173
01:15:17,037 --> 01:15:19,255
is that

1174
01:15:19,636 --> 01:15:22,264
you just pay a visit to folks
twice a day now.

1175
01:15:22,703 --> 01:15:25,770
That way it would seem
that you're willing to contribute more

1176
01:15:26,270 --> 01:15:28,607
without actually lengthening
your day too much.

1177
01:15:29,003 --> 01:15:31,660
<i>It's just a way of heading off
any unpleasantness.</i>

1178
01:15:38,237 --> 01:15:40,255
But it sounds...

1179
01:15:40,603 --> 01:15:43,970
it sounds a little peculiar,
difficult to put into practice.

1180
01:15:44,503 --> 01:15:46,501
That's what I thought.

1181
01:15:47,636 --> 01:15:50,563
Martha, she said she'd ring her bell
every half hour

1182
01:15:51,037 --> 01:15:53,225
so you could keep track
of your new schedule.

1183
01:15:56,836 --> 01:15:58,834
Then they're all willing
to let me stay?

1184
01:15:59,037 --> 01:16:01,035
<i>No.</i>

1185
01:16:01,037 --> 01:16:03,964
Mrs. Henson, she also

1186
01:16:04,436 --> 01:16:06,484
thought we should cut your pay.

1187
01:16:06,836 --> 01:16:09,413
- So...
- Merely a symbolic gesture.

1188
01:16:09,836 --> 01:16:11,834
It was...

1189
01:16:12,603 --> 01:16:15,620
You see the word dangerous
on the poster worried her.

1190
01:16:18,103 --> 01:16:20,101
I'm willing to do whatever it takes.

1191
01:16:20,137 --> 01:16:22,135
If I have to work

1192
01:16:22,269 --> 01:16:24,577
harder, longer hours for less pay,

1193
01:16:24,970 --> 01:16:27,627
then I'm wiling to do that,
of course I am.

1194
01:16:29,770 --> 01:16:31,768
I just want to be sure

1195
01:16:31,803 --> 01:16:34,430
that they wouldn't prefer
that I left town.

1196
01:16:34,870 --> 01:16:36,868
<i>Of course not.</i>

1197
01:16:39,170 --> 01:16:41,168
<i>You think this is for the best?</i>

1198
01:16:42,203 --> 01:16:44,201
I know it is.

1199
01:16:47,536 --> 01:16:49,534
I have to get some sleep.

1200
01:16:52,536 --> 01:16:55,114
My days are gonna be
much busier now.

1201
01:16:55,536 --> 01:16:57,534
I'm sorry.

1202
01:17:21,369 --> 01:17:23,367
<i>Tom.</i>

1203
01:17:25,970 --> 01:17:27,968
I just need to know something.

1204
01:17:30,836 --> 01:17:34,172
You know the card
that the man in the car gave you?

1205
01:17:34,703 --> 01:17:36,701
<i>Yeah.</i>

1206
01:17:40,970 --> 01:17:42,968
Did you show it to anyone?

1207
01:17:43,003 --> 01:17:45,220
Come on, Grace.

1208
01:17:47,236 --> 01:17:49,202
I burned it first thing.

1209
01:17:49,203 --> 01:17:51,201
I am being so silly,

1210
01:17:51,303 --> 01:17:53,301
of course you did.

1211
01:17:53,436 --> 01:17:55,434
<i>It's all right, it's all right.</i>

1212
01:17:55,436 --> 01:17:57,434
No, it's not all right.

1213
01:17:57,570 --> 01:17:59,968
I... I hate it for you
to see me like this.

1214
01:18:00,369 --> 01:18:02,235
I can't bear that I'm doubting you.

1215
01:18:02,236 --> 01:18:05,223
I'm sorry. Good night.

1216
01:18:25,102 --> 01:18:27,320
<i>Everybody was really against</i>

1217
01:18:27,703 --> 01:18:30,310
<i>any changes to Grace's
working conditions at all</i>

1218
01:18:30,736 --> 01:18:33,074
<i>when the subject occasionally
came up in conversation.</i>

1219
01:18:41,603 --> 01:18:44,320
<i>Ben had declared in sympathy
that he wouldn't accept</i>

1220
01:18:44,770 --> 01:18:47,487
<i>any more work than before...
and Grace was grateful for that.</i>

1221
01:18:47,937 --> 01:18:51,413
<i>Even if he was a bit drunk
when he said so.</i>

1222
01:18:55,670 --> 01:18:58,127
<i>Busy minutes became busy hours,</i>

1223
01:18:58,536 --> 01:19:01,553
<i>and busy hours became busy days.</i>

1224
01:19:02,037 --> 01:19:05,873
<i>And irrespective of whether they thought
the idea of increasing Grace's services</i>

1225
01:19:06,469 --> 01:19:09,306
<i>had any fairness
and justification to it or not,</i>

1226
01:19:09,770 --> 01:19:12,077
<i>it didn't seem to make anyone
any happier,</i>

1227
01:19:12,469 --> 01:19:14,467
<i>more to the contrary.</i>

1228
01:19:16,937 --> 01:19:19,924
Grace,
you have to be more careful.

1229
01:19:20,403 --> 01:19:22,401
Liz wasn't very careful either,

1230
01:19:22,636 --> 01:19:24,468
<i>but she didn't break our glasses.</i>

1231
01:19:24,469 --> 01:19:27,156
I think you need to understand
that Mr. Henson

1232
01:19:27,603 --> 01:19:30,410
<i>works very hard
to grind off any traces of the molds.</i>

1233
01:19:31,836 --> 01:19:33,834
It makes the glass weak.

1234
01:19:34,636 --> 01:19:37,593
<i>- I thought you knew that.</i>
- It won't happen again.

1235
01:19:38,069 --> 01:19:40,067
Of course I'll pay for it.

1236
01:19:40,136 --> 01:19:42,304
No, of course not,
you don't have to pay us for it.

1237
01:19:42,670 --> 01:19:44,748
We'll get over it.

1238
01:19:46,570 --> 01:19:49,557
<i>And off she went again
to keep her appointment with Chuck,</i>

1239
01:19:50,036 --> 01:19:52,114
<i>to free the last tree trunks
from the grass,</i>

1240
01:19:52,469 --> 01:19:54,957
<i>in order to keep
the ever busy mice away.</i>

1241
01:19:56,436 --> 01:19:58,434
<i>She was in a hurry
and took the shortcut</i>

1242
01:19:58,603 --> 01:20:00,468
<i>between the gooseberry bushes,</i>

1243
01:20:00,469 --> 01:20:02,467
<i>only to brought up by a shout.</i>

1244
01:20:02,636 --> 01:20:04,634
- Grace!
<i>- Yes.</i>

1245
01:20:10,469 --> 01:20:12,986
I didn't see that you just
raked the path. I'm sorry.

1246
01:20:13,403 --> 01:20:16,500
It isn't that I just raked it,
the idea is

1247
01:20:17,002 --> 01:20:20,159
for people to pass
around the bushes completely.

1248
01:20:20,670 --> 01:20:23,157
<i>I prefer it that way,
as you should know.</i>

1249
01:20:23,570 --> 01:20:26,557
<i>I thought that these chains
were put up to...</i>

1250
01:20:27,036 --> 01:20:29,084
to make a path between the bushes.

1251
01:20:29,436 --> 01:20:32,713
They were put up to protect the bushes.
It's not supposed to be a pathway.

1252
01:20:33,236 --> 01:20:35,514
But everyone goes this way.

1253
01:20:35,903 --> 01:20:37,901
<i>Yeah, that's right,</i>

1254
01:20:38,102 --> 01:20:40,001
but they've been living here for years,

1255
01:20:40,002 --> 01:20:42,000
you haven't been here that long.

1256
01:20:43,369 --> 01:20:45,367
<i>Are you saying that I'm less entitled</i>

1257
01:20:45,603 --> 01:20:47,851
to use the shortcut because

1258
01:20:48,236 --> 01:20:49,936
I haven't always lived here?

1259
01:20:49,937 --> 01:20:51,602
Of course not.

1260
01:20:51,603 --> 01:20:54,320
No, I just thought it pleased you
to be here, that's all.

1261
01:20:56,102 --> 01:20:58,100
Go on, go on, it's all right.

1262
01:20:58,236 --> 01:21:00,234
- I'll see you this afternoon.
<i>- Okay.</i>

1263
01:21:00,570 --> 01:21:03,587
And I'll rake those bushes
like they've never been raked before.

1264
01:21:04,069 --> 01:21:06,067
I promise.

1265
01:21:12,770 --> 01:21:14,669
I'm sorry about that branch,

1266
01:21:14,670 --> 01:21:16,668
there were so many apples on it.

1267
01:21:19,069 --> 01:21:22,026
I should have cut that branch,
but I got greedy.

1268
01:21:23,903 --> 01:21:25,901
<i>Is it greedy to want
to feed your family?</i>

1269
01:21:32,570 --> 01:21:34,568
So how come you don't like me?

1270
01:21:38,536 --> 01:21:40,534
Why do you ask me that?

1271
01:21:40,536 --> 01:21:42,534
<i>When I get close to you,
you edge away.</i>

1272
01:21:45,703 --> 01:21:47,268
No, I don't.

1273
01:21:47,269 --> 01:21:49,235
<i>You did so</i>

1274
01:21:49,236 --> 01:21:51,844
when we were thinning
the seedlings in the bottom row.

1275
01:21:53,236 --> 01:21:55,983
<i>How am I supposed to show you what I do
if I ain't allowed to touch you?</i>

1276
01:21:58,269 --> 01:22:00,267
You tried to kiss me.

1277
01:22:09,303 --> 01:22:12,200
Vera never took any interest
in the apples.

1278
01:22:12,670 --> 01:22:14,668
<i>She hates the orchard.</i>

1279
01:22:16,036 --> 01:22:19,193
<i>This is the first time I ever met
anyone who understood about the apples.</i>

1280
01:22:22,369 --> 01:22:24,367
Sorry it made me so happy.

1281
01:22:29,036 --> 01:22:31,314
- It's all right.
- No, it ain't all right.

1282
01:22:31,703 --> 01:22:34,390
I reckon the stuff about the apples
is just words in your mouth.

1283
01:22:36,136 --> 01:22:38,134
You can't really share my pleasure.

1284
01:22:39,036 --> 01:22:40,402
I do.

1285
01:22:40,403 --> 01:22:44,529
Vera wants me picking apples from trees
that are barely in the ground.

1286
01:22:46,369 --> 01:22:48,367
Things take time, that's love!

1287
01:22:49,803 --> 01:22:53,169
Seeing what they need
and respecting those needs,

1288
01:22:53,703 --> 01:22:56,480
if anyone understands that it's you.
At least I thought so.

1289
01:22:56,936 --> 01:22:59,394
- I do understand that.
- But you edge away when I get close.

1290
01:22:59,803 --> 01:23:01,202
N...

1291
01:23:01,203 --> 01:23:03,068
Why do you find me so repugnant?

1292
01:23:03,069 --> 01:23:05,067
I don't find you repugnant, I...

1293
01:23:06,503 --> 01:23:08,501
Don't be upset.

1294
01:23:09,736 --> 01:23:12,133
I'm sorry if I doubted you.

1295
01:23:12,536 --> 01:23:14,534
It won't happen again...

1296
01:23:16,469 --> 01:23:18,467
I promise you.

1297
01:23:20,670 --> 01:23:22,977
I wouldn't make that promise
if I was you.

1298
01:23:29,436 --> 01:23:31,714
When you fended me <i>off,
</i>a thought came into my mind.

1299
01:23:32,102 --> 01:23:34,380
<i>It made me ashamed.</i>

1300
01:23:34,770 --> 01:23:36,768
A thought that you'd hate me for.

1301
01:23:38,236 --> 01:23:40,234
I would never hate you...

1302
01:23:41,036 --> 01:23:43,034
never.

1303
01:23:47,036 --> 01:23:49,034
<i>What?</i>

1304
01:23:50,236 --> 01:23:52,234
Chuck, I treated you unfairly,

1305
01:23:52,469 --> 01:23:54,637
it's all right
to have angry thoughts.

1306
01:23:58,403 --> 01:24:00,401
I thought of turning you in.

1307
01:24:03,002 --> 01:24:05,490
I thought of blackmailing you
into respecting me.

1308
01:24:15,336 --> 01:24:17,334
It means that much to you?

1309
01:24:19,203 --> 01:24:21,201
It does, doesn't it?

1310
01:24:23,002 --> 01:24:25,170
You've really been alone up here,
haven't you?

1311
01:24:26,936 --> 01:24:28,934
<i>You haven't had anyone
to comfort you.</i>

1312
01:24:30,203 --> 01:24:32,721
And I should ask you
for forgiveness.

1313
01:24:41,169 --> 01:24:43,167
<i>Still friends?</i>

1314
01:25:12,169 --> 01:25:13,734
Sorry. Are you asleep?

1315
01:25:13,735 --> 01:25:15,733
No.

1316
01:25:15,969 --> 01:25:17,967
<i>Want me to leave?</i>

1317
01:25:18,102 --> 01:25:20,100
No, I was just resting.

1318
01:25:20,369 --> 01:25:23,406
Awful lot to do
here in Dogville considering...

1319
01:25:25,203 --> 01:25:27,750
nobody needs anything done.

1320
01:25:29,969 --> 01:25:32,367
Jason wants to sit
on my lap all the time.

1321
01:25:37,203 --> 01:25:39,391
I think you're doing a wonderful job.

1322
01:25:41,969 --> 01:25:44,137
<i>You give us all so much.</i>

1323
01:25:44,503 --> 01:25:47,190
What Mr. McKay said,
right on the button.

1324
01:25:47,636 --> 01:25:49,634
Right on the button.

1325
01:25:50,536 --> 01:25:52,703
He tried to put his hand
on my knee today.

1326
01:25:53,069 --> 01:25:55,117
Well, he's blind, after all.

1327
01:25:55,469 --> 01:25:57,487
It was probably an accident.

1328
01:26:01,102 --> 01:26:03,035
Ma Ginger

1329
01:26:03,036 --> 01:26:07,042
got angry at me
for running across the gravel path.

1330
01:26:09,869 --> 01:26:13,206
Well, good. She gets angry at me.

1331
01:26:15,503 --> 01:26:17,501
It just means you're one of us now.

1332
01:26:17,769 --> 01:26:19,817
You can see through it all,
can't you?

1333
01:26:36,936 --> 01:26:39,364
I tell you, I'm gonna be asleep
in two minutes.

1334
01:26:39,769 --> 01:26:42,577
What if I don't want you
to go to sleep?

1335
01:26:43,036 --> 01:26:45,314
I don't think you have
a choice tonight.

1336
01:26:56,802 --> 01:26:58,850
I do love you, Grace.

1337
01:27:00,669 --> 01:27:04,146
I'm glad you love me,
I love you too.

1338
01:27:04,702 --> 01:27:06,700
<i>I really do.</i>

1339
01:27:10,835 --> 01:27:13,083
I mean I yearn for you when...

1340
01:27:13,469 --> 01:27:15,467
when I'm not with you.

1341
01:27:20,602 --> 01:27:24,109
I yearn for you even when we're...
alone like this.

1342
01:27:27,403 --> 01:27:30,649
I yearn to be even closer to you,

1343
01:27:31,169 --> 01:27:33,447
to touch you the way that people...

1344
01:27:33,835 --> 01:27:36,702
We have our whole lives
ahead of us.

1345
01:27:39,735 --> 01:27:43,861
The thing that I love about you is
that you don't demand anything of me,

1346
01:27:44,503 --> 01:27:48,369
that we can just... just be together.

1347
01:27:48,969 --> 01:27:51,017
Yeah.

1348
01:27:51,369 --> 01:27:54,675
Yearning will only make it better.

1349
01:28:02,902 --> 01:28:04,900
<i>Thank you for your...</i>

1350
01:28:04,936 --> 01:28:07,893
<i>your words, your wise, wise words.</i>

1351
01:28:10,702 --> 01:28:12,700
You're welcome.

1352
01:28:15,735 --> 01:28:17,733
You want your shoes off?

1353
01:28:33,425 --> 01:28:39,758
CHAPTER SIX
in which Dogville bares its teeth.

1354
01:28:43,569 --> 01:28:45,647
Jason, what are you doing here?

1355
01:28:46,969 --> 01:28:49,017
That's wrong.

1356
01:28:49,369 --> 01:28:51,367
The words have to be
divided differently.

1357
01:28:54,203 --> 01:28:56,001
Stop it!

1358
01:28:56,002 --> 01:28:58,220
How's that for dividing the words?

1359
01:29:00,369 --> 01:29:03,236
This is not a good day.
Everybody should leave.

1360
01:29:03,702 --> 01:29:06,629
Everybody except Jason.
Jason, I want to talk to you alone.

1361
01:29:07,102 --> 01:29:10,029
<i>What is it? What's going on?</i>

1362
01:29:11,835 --> 01:29:14,003
- I can be very bad.
- What...?

1363
01:29:14,369 --> 01:29:16,068
Bet my Pa told you.

1364
01:29:16,069 --> 01:29:18,067
I don't think that.

1365
01:29:18,102 --> 01:29:20,100
I think there is
another reason for this.

1366
01:29:21,769 --> 01:29:24,017
I would love to have you
on my lap all the time

1367
01:29:24,403 --> 01:29:26,401
but I can't,
not with the others here.

1368
01:29:28,602 --> 01:29:32,259
When somebody can't do all the things
they'd like to do for others,

1369
01:29:32,835 --> 01:29:35,582
sometimes the people
they promised get mad.

1370
01:29:37,203 --> 01:29:39,371
That's what Mrs. Henson says.

1371
01:29:41,669 --> 01:29:43,568
Yes, that's true.

1372
01:29:43,569 --> 01:29:46,117
I suppose I know why you won't let me
sit in your lap anymore.

1373
01:29:47,535 --> 01:29:49,533
- Why?
<i>- Because I've been mean lately.</i>

1374
01:29:49,602 --> 01:29:53,878
Come on, I'm sure you have
your reasons for that.

1375
01:29:54,535 --> 01:29:56,533
I've been mean to the others too.

1376
01:29:56,735 --> 01:29:59,073
Even baby Achilles.

1377
01:29:59,468 --> 01:30:02,096
And he's so tiny,
he can't put up a fight.

1378
01:30:04,303 --> 01:30:06,610
- It's not right.
- No, it's not.

1379
01:30:07,002 --> 01:30:09,000
I got it coming to me.

1380
01:30:09,936 --> 01:30:12,863
- I know, I deserve a spanking.
- What?

1381
01:30:13,336 --> 01:30:16,762
I should hit you?
I'm not gonna do that.

1382
01:30:17,303 --> 01:30:20,429
Your mother doesn't believe in physical
discipline, I'm not gonna hit you.

1383
01:30:20,936 --> 01:30:24,412
I know. She'd be awful mad
if she found out you whipped me.

1384
01:30:24,969 --> 01:30:27,956
I just said I won't do that, so...

1385
01:30:28,435 --> 01:30:31,183
It's good
having Ma on your side, right?

1386
01:30:32,669 --> 01:30:35,037
<i>It would be pretty serious
if she turned against you.</i>

1387
01:30:35,435 --> 01:30:38,652
I am the way I am. If people
in this town don't like me, then...

1388
01:30:39,169 --> 01:30:41,826
there's nothing I can do about that.

1389
01:30:42,269 --> 01:30:44,267
I feel bad, I need to be punished.

1390
01:30:44,569 --> 01:30:47,876
In fact, I wouldn't have any respect for
you if you didn't give me a spanking.

1391
01:30:48,402 --> 01:30:50,800
I don't care how much fun
you think it would be

1392
01:30:51,203 --> 01:30:53,341
I'm not gonna spank you, Jason.

1393
01:30:55,136 --> 01:30:57,304
In that case...

1394
01:30:57,669 --> 01:31:01,146
when Ma gets home... maybe I'll just
have to tell her you hit me.

1395
01:31:01,702 --> 01:31:03,235
But I just said that I wouldn't.

1396
01:31:03,236 --> 01:31:06,572
<i>I reckon Ma'll take my word for it.</i>

1397
01:31:07,102 --> 01:31:10,119
If you give me that spanking,
nobody's ever have to know.

1398
01:31:16,635 --> 01:31:18,633
Stop it. Get away from Achilles.
Stop it!

1399
01:31:20,269 --> 01:31:22,576
I gave his crib a shove.

1400
01:31:22,969 --> 01:31:25,896
- Not my fault it didn't tip over.
- Don't you touch him.

1401
01:31:26,368 --> 01:31:28,366
Move away from the crib.
Stop it, Jason!

1402
01:31:28,502 --> 01:31:30,670
Stop it!
All right, you want a spanking?

1403
01:31:31,036 --> 01:31:33,433
I'll give you a spanking.
Come here. Come here.

1404
01:31:36,602 --> 01:31:38,600
There... there we go.

1405
01:31:38,669 --> 01:31:42,236
That wasn't hard. It's got to be hard
or it isn't punishment.

1406
01:31:42,802 --> 01:31:45,699
- All right.
- Harder.

1407
01:31:48,102 --> 01:31:49,668
This is... Come on!

1408
01:31:49,669 --> 01:31:51,687
That's enough.
That's enough punishment now.

1409
01:31:52,036 --> 01:31:54,753
Maybe I should go stand in the corner
and be ashamed?

1410
01:31:55,203 --> 01:31:58,329
I don't care! Stand in the corner,
do whatever you're gonna do.

1411
01:31:58,835 --> 01:32:00,833
<i>Hey, there's Pa!</i>

1412
01:32:05,535 --> 01:32:07,501
He's early...
I hope nothing's wrong.

1413
01:32:07,502 --> 01:32:09,960
<i>Just as Dogville
had done from its open,</i>

1414
01:32:10,368 --> 01:32:14,115
<i>frail shelf on the mountainside, quite
unprotected from any capricious storms,</i>

1415
01:32:14,702 --> 01:32:18,069
<i>- Grace too had laid herself open.</i>
- Ma Ginger says...

1416
01:32:18,602 --> 01:32:21,379
<i>And there she dangled
from her frail stalk</i>

1417
01:32:21,835 --> 01:32:24,292
<i>like the apple in the Garden of Eden,</i>

1418
01:32:24,702 --> 01:32:27,799
<i>an apple so swollen
that the juices almost ran.</i>

1419
01:32:30,435 --> 01:32:33,622
<i>And once again,
the police had come to Dogville.</i>

1420
01:32:35,869 --> 01:32:37,867
<i>I said I'd tell you...</i>

1421
01:32:38,102 --> 01:32:40,439
to save Martha
the confusion about the ringing.

1422
01:32:40,835 --> 01:32:43,262
But I forgot.
They're already down by Canyon Road.

1423
01:32:43,669 --> 01:32:46,856
The fellow in the other car is from
the Federal Bureau of investigation.

1424
01:32:47,368 --> 01:32:49,646
- You forgot?
- Yeah.

1425
01:32:50,036 --> 01:32:52,034
It's the busy time for the apples.

1426
01:32:52,136 --> 01:32:54,001
The FBI.

1427
01:32:54,002 --> 01:32:57,568
They were most interested in hearing
what I'd seen in the past six months.

1428
01:32:58,136 --> 01:33:00,883
<i>Anything related to that
wanted poster.</i>

1429
01:33:01,335 --> 01:33:03,413
They asked me if I'd seen
any signs in the woods

1430
01:33:03,769 --> 01:33:06,107
of anyone camping out there.

1431
01:33:06,502 --> 01:33:08,690
God only knows
what that woman is capable of.

1432
01:33:09,069 --> 01:33:11,376
You know
she is not capable of anything.

1433
01:33:11,769 --> 01:33:14,167
Well, that's what <i>you</i> say.

1434
01:33:14,569 --> 01:33:18,285
It sure didn't sound that way
coming from the laws.

1435
01:33:18,869 --> 01:33:21,087
<i>That's why I felt
I had to tell them what I knew.</i>

1436
01:33:24,302 --> 01:33:26,300
<i>What did you tell them?</i>

1437
01:33:26,569 --> 01:33:29,756
<i>I thought I'd seen something
in the woods recently.</i>

1438
01:33:30,268 --> 01:33:32,266
<i>An item of clothing, to be exact.</i>

1439
01:33:32,402 --> 01:33:35,769
Turned out it was just an old hat
Tom had lost.

1440
01:33:36,302 --> 01:33:38,730
- But could have been this.
<i>- Chuck, give me that.</i>

1441
01:33:39,136 --> 01:33:41,134
Expensive by the feel of it.

1442
01:33:41,402 --> 01:33:43,400
Your initials on it.

1443
01:33:46,468 --> 01:33:49,455
I imagine they'd draw the same
conclusions from this as anybody would.

1444
01:33:49,936 --> 01:33:54,561
I told the laws it will take me no time
at all to find this piece of clothing.

1445
01:33:56,235 --> 01:33:58,513
<i>I reckon we got us 10 minutes,
maybe 15,</i>

1446
01:33:58,902 --> 01:34:01,209
before they start knocking on doors.

1447
01:34:01,602 --> 01:34:04,259
<i>I wouldn't try to run away.</i>

1448
01:34:04,702 --> 01:34:06,700
<i>They're sure to see you.</i>

1449
01:34:06,802 --> 01:34:09,959
- Why would I want to run away, Chuck?
<i>- I wouldn't try to holler either.</i>

1450
01:34:10,468 --> 01:34:13,595
- Why would I want to do that?
<i>- It wasn't me who wanted you here.</i>

1451
01:34:14,102 --> 01:34:16,789
You're far too beautiful
and frail for this place.

1452
01:34:18,402 --> 01:34:20,830
You tricked me into feeling
that I meant something to you.

1453
01:34:21,235 --> 01:34:23,693
It's your own damned fault
I need your respect, Grace.

1454
01:34:24,102 --> 01:34:27,029
- You have my respect, Chuck.
- I want your respect.

1455
01:34:27,502 --> 01:34:29,500
Don't...

1456
01:34:42,502 --> 01:34:44,500
This is wrong.

1457
01:34:46,069 --> 01:34:48,556
If I can force the flowers
to bloom early in spring...

1458
01:34:50,268 --> 01:34:52,576
I can force you.

1459
01:34:52,969 --> 01:34:54,967
Please...

1460
01:35:02,936 --> 01:35:05,713
No! Stop it!

1461
01:35:06,168 --> 01:35:08,166
Please stop, please.

1462
01:35:08,502 --> 01:35:10,500
Please don't, please.

1463
01:35:12,135 --> 01:35:14,183
Please, please, look at me.

1464
01:35:14,535 --> 01:35:16,553
Look at me and talk to me, please.

1465
01:35:16,902 --> 01:35:19,209
We're friends. You're my friend.

1466
01:35:21,702 --> 01:35:25,358
- No, no, Grace, we're not.
- Stop it.

1467
01:36:24,735 --> 01:36:26,534
Have you seen Grace?

1468
01:36:26,535 --> 01:36:28,903
She's at my place.

1469
01:36:29,302 --> 01:36:32,339
- She busy?
- Not anymore. Go right in.

1470
01:36:57,468 --> 01:36:59,466
<i>Yet again Grace had made</i>

1471
01:36:59,602 --> 01:37:03,228
<i>a miraculous escape from her pursuers
with the aid of the people of Dogville.</i>

1472
01:37:03,802 --> 01:37:07,398
<i>Everyone had covered up for her,
including Chuck,</i>

1473
01:37:07,968 --> 01:37:10,866
<i>who had to admit
that it was probably Tom's hat</i>

1474
01:37:11,335 --> 01:37:14,402
<i>he'd mistakenly considered
so suspicious.</i>

1475
01:37:21,550 --> 01:37:26,467
CHAPTER SEVEN in which Grace
finally gets enough of Dogville,

1476
01:37:26,633 --> 01:37:30,300
leaves the town,
and again sees the light of day.

1477
01:37:30,702 --> 01:37:33,719
<i>That evening, Tom had sensed at once</i>

1478
01:37:34,202 --> 01:37:38,267
<i>that something had taken place,
but had to plead with Grace for ages</i>

1479
01:37:38,902 --> 01:37:40,920
<i>before she finally broke down</i>

1480
01:37:41,268 --> 01:37:43,266
<i>and unburdened herself.</i>

1481
01:37:43,435 --> 01:37:45,401
I have to confront him, I mean...

1482
01:37:45,402 --> 01:37:47,450
- No, no.
<i>- I have no choice.</i>

1483
01:37:47,802 --> 01:37:50,200
- No one will accept what he did to you.
<i>- I don't want you to.</i>

1484
01:37:50,602 --> 01:37:53,289
I came here with all these ideas

1485
01:37:53,735 --> 01:37:56,752
and these stupid prejudices...

1486
01:37:59,635 --> 01:38:02,762
He's not strong, Tom.

1487
01:38:03,268 --> 01:38:06,076
<i>He looks strong, but he's not.</i>

1488
01:38:07,835 --> 01:38:10,792
I'm gonna start looking for a way
to get you out of here.

1489
01:38:23,969 --> 01:38:25,967
<i>The end of the summer had come</i>

1490
01:38:26,069 --> 01:38:29,965
<i>and in Elm Street, the second clutch
of Dogville's scatty squirrels</i>

1491
01:38:30,569 --> 01:38:33,376
<i>scooted in and out of the legs
of children and grown-ups alike,</i>

1492
01:38:33,835 --> 01:38:37,781
<i>searching in vain
for Elm Street's nonexistent elms.</i>

1493
01:38:39,535 --> 01:38:43,571
<i>The heat had turned the soil
among the gooseberry bushes to stone.</i>

1494
01:38:44,201 --> 01:38:47,538
<i>But Grace did not complain.
She threw herself into her work,</i>

1495
01:38:48,069 --> 01:38:52,514
<i>happy that it was something you could
actually grasp between your fingers.</i>

1496
01:38:53,201 --> 01:38:55,889
- Hey, Liz, hey, Vera.
<i>- Better watch out, Grace.</i>

1497
01:38:56,335 --> 01:38:58,853
<i>Vera's got it in for you today.</i>

1498
01:38:59,268 --> 01:39:01,696
What are you talking about?

1499
01:39:02,102 --> 01:39:04,499
<i>Maybe you thought
he wouldn't tell me.</i>

1500
01:39:07,869 --> 01:39:10,057
Who?

1501
01:39:10,435 --> 01:39:12,433
You hit Jason.

1502
01:39:15,136 --> 01:39:18,003
- I did.
<i>- How could you do such a thing?</i>

1503
01:39:20,036 --> 01:39:24,221
I know it sounds implausible,
but he was asking for it.

1504
01:39:24,869 --> 01:39:28,175
It's true, Vera,
he's always asking for it.

1505
01:39:29,802 --> 01:39:32,110
I should have done it myself
a long time ago.

1506
01:39:32,502 --> 01:39:33,935
Liz!

1507
01:39:33,936 --> 01:39:35,934
It's your fault,
the way you've spoiled him.

1508
01:39:36,201 --> 01:39:38,199
I know how much
you love him, Vera.

1509
01:39:40,502 --> 01:39:42,434
So do I.

1510
01:39:42,435 --> 01:39:44,513
It won't happen again.

1511
01:39:44,869 --> 01:39:46,867
It really won't...

1512
01:39:47,069 --> 01:39:51,164
I know it won't, because I'll never
leave them with you again.

1513
01:39:51,802 --> 01:39:54,489
<i>That'd be far too dangerous
for any child of mine.</i>

1514
01:39:54,936 --> 01:39:58,272
- I've been tired.
- Well, maybe you should see

1515
01:39:58,802 --> 01:40:01,229
about sleeping at night
like most folks do.

1516
01:40:01,635 --> 01:40:04,242
Sleeping at night?

1517
01:40:04,669 --> 01:40:08,795
Martha saw
a certain Tom Edison Jr.

1518
01:40:09,435 --> 01:40:11,433
Sneak out of her shed

1519
01:40:11,769 --> 01:40:13,957
early this morning.

1520
01:40:19,002 --> 01:40:22,308
Grace, you won't hear anything from me
about whipping that idiot kid.

1521
01:40:22,835 --> 01:40:26,052
<i>I'm also grateful for you for turning
Tom's wandering eye away from my skirts,</i>

1522
01:40:26,569 --> 01:40:29,966
but on the other hand, I expected
more from you than that.

1523
01:40:32,435 --> 01:40:35,152
But if that's the kind of thing
you're after, then I'm sure

1524
01:40:35,602 --> 01:40:38,529
with your innocent looks you'll do
just fine in a place like Dogville.

1525
01:40:39,002 --> 01:40:41,000
It's not what I am after, Liz.

1526
01:40:41,036 --> 01:40:43,753
No? We all saw you
take his hand at the picnic.

1527
01:40:44,201 --> 01:40:46,389
Maybe that wasn't flirting.

1528
01:40:48,302 --> 01:40:51,729
Yes, maybe I was flirting.

1529
01:41:00,869 --> 01:41:03,676
<i>Next day, the weather changed.</i>

1530
01:41:04,135 --> 01:41:07,322
<i>The fog came rolling down
from the mountains.</i>

1531
01:41:07,835 --> 01:41:10,322
<i>And although there were
no sunsets to be seen,</i>

1532
01:41:10,735 --> 01:41:13,922
<i>McKay thought it best
that she sat by him anyway.</i>

1533
01:41:14,435 --> 01:41:17,362
<i>She had sat by Jack McKay
so many times now.</i>

1534
01:41:17,835 --> 01:41:21,521
<i>But Jack had not got better
at judging the distance between them.</i>

1535
01:41:22,101 --> 01:41:26,457
<i>On the contrary, where fingers alone
had previously brushed her young flesh,</i>

1536
01:41:27,135 --> 01:41:29,593
<i>now it was a hand
that remained in place</i>

1537
01:41:30,002 --> 01:41:32,000
<i>throughout the allotted span.</i>

1538
01:41:35,068 --> 01:41:39,224
<i>The hours in the orchard were long now,
for the harvest was underway.</i>

1539
01:41:39,869 --> 01:41:43,295
<i>And Grace had long since given up
arguing with Chuck's perception</i>

1540
01:41:43,835 --> 01:41:47,311
<i>that respect for cultivation,
harvest and fruit</i>

1541
01:41:47,869 --> 01:41:51,205
<i>could be directly measured
in provision of carnality.</i>

1542
01:41:51,735 --> 01:41:54,602
<i>Though reluctant
to leave Grace alone,</i>

1543
01:41:55,068 --> 01:41:58,345
<i>Tom wandered around
quite often now, lost in thought</i>

1544
01:41:58,869 --> 01:42:01,936
<i>as he tried to crack the problem
of possible escape.</i>

1545
01:42:02,435 --> 01:42:06,501
<i>And as Grace's wages no longer
found their way to her purse,</i>

1546
01:42:07,135 --> 01:42:09,133
<i>he had stepped in,</i>

1547
01:42:09,135 --> 01:42:11,353
<i>and together
they had triumphantly picked up</i>

1548
01:42:11,735 --> 01:42:15,481
<i>the last of the seven figurines
from Ma Ginger's window.</i>

1549
01:42:25,635 --> 01:42:28,652
- What's the matter?
<i>- Nothing.</i>

1550
01:42:29,135 --> 01:42:32,762
Are the police
on Canyon Road again?

1551
01:42:33,335 --> 01:42:35,353
<i>No...</i>

1552
01:42:37,569 --> 01:42:40,196
this is just girl talk.

1553
01:42:40,635 --> 01:42:43,822
It's funny you should mention
Canyon Road though,

1554
01:42:44,335 --> 01:42:46,733
right, Martha?
She was just there this morning.

1555
01:42:47,135 --> 01:42:49,133
On the way home from church.

1556
01:42:49,268 --> 01:42:51,266
You see so much more on foot.

1557
01:42:51,602 --> 01:42:53,600
You know, when you're in a car,

1558
01:42:53,602 --> 01:42:57,138
you never notice
the apple orchard for example.

1559
01:42:58,935 --> 01:43:00,933
You can only see it

1560
01:43:01,035 --> 01:43:03,783
<i>from one spot on Canyon Road.</i>

1561
01:43:04,235 --> 01:43:06,543
<i>- That's right...
- You know that spot, Martha?</i>

1562
01:43:06,935 --> 01:43:08,933
<i>Yes I do.</i>

1563
01:43:10,101 --> 01:43:11,901
<i>And...</i>

1564
01:43:11,902 --> 01:43:14,329
did you stop there to enjoy the view
this morning?

1565
01:43:14,735 --> 01:43:17,632
It's harvest time, you know,
in the orchard, after all.

1566
01:43:18,101 --> 01:43:21,408
The old masters always loved
a good harvest theme,

1567
01:43:21,935 --> 01:43:23,933
<i>redolent with fertility,</i>

1568
01:43:24,268 --> 01:43:26,786
not to mention sensibility,

1569
01:43:27,201 --> 01:43:30,628
or even eroticism.

1570
01:43:33,569 --> 01:43:35,567
But how silly of me

1571
01:43:35,802 --> 01:43:38,869
to ask you that, Martha,
because you already said you did.

1572
01:43:43,001 --> 01:43:45,139
She saw you, Grace.

1573
01:43:49,035 --> 01:43:51,693
She saw you...

1574
01:43:54,535 --> 01:43:57,842
behind this pile of broken limbs...

1575
01:43:59,402 --> 01:44:01,650
with Chuck.

1576
01:44:05,001 --> 01:44:08,308
He said it wasn't the first time
you'd made advances towards him.

1577
01:44:10,602 --> 01:44:14,518
<i>He never told me before because he
wanted to spare my feelings.</i>

1578
01:44:16,769 --> 01:44:19,426
He's a withdrawn

1579
01:44:19,868 --> 01:44:22,386
and primitive man.

1580
01:44:23,901 --> 01:44:25,167
Vera...

1581
01:44:25,168 --> 01:44:27,596
But at heart, he's loyal!

1582
01:44:28,001 --> 01:44:29,999
And he's good.

1583
01:44:30,302 --> 01:44:32,849
What do you want with my husband?

1584
01:44:34,368 --> 01:44:38,024
I don't want anything...

1585
01:44:38,602 --> 01:44:40,969
with your husband

1586
01:44:41,368 --> 01:44:43,736
or anybody.

1587
01:44:44,135 --> 01:44:46,713
What about Tom
and the hand-holding at the picnic?

1588
01:44:47,135 --> 01:44:50,472
That's different, I like Tom.

1589
01:44:51,001 --> 01:44:53,169
But you don't like Chuck?

1590
01:44:53,535 --> 01:44:55,902
Liz and Martha are behind me

1591
01:44:56,302 --> 01:44:59,049
<i>when I tell you I'm gonna have
to teach you a lesson.</i>

1592
01:44:59,502 --> 01:45:02,279
I believe in education.

1593
01:45:05,968 --> 01:45:07,367
Vera!

1594
01:45:07,368 --> 01:45:09,366
<i>I believe smashing them</i>

1595
01:45:09,402 --> 01:45:11,740
is less a crime than making them.

1596
01:45:13,669 --> 01:45:15,667
<i>Vera, remember</i>

1597
01:45:15,735 --> 01:45:17,733
how I taught your children...

1598
01:45:17,801 --> 01:45:20,549
<i>- What?
- Remember how happy you were...</i>

1599
01:45:21,001 --> 01:45:23,898
<i>- when I taught your children...
- When you what?</i>

1600
01:45:24,368 --> 01:45:28,114
About the doctrine of stoicism
and they finally understood it?

1601
01:45:29,768 --> 01:45:32,106
<i>All right, for that
I'm gonna be lenient,</i>

1602
01:45:32,502 --> 01:45:35,569
I am going to break
two of your figurines first.

1603
01:45:38,535 --> 01:45:41,991
And if you can demonstrate

1604
01:45:42,535 --> 01:45:45,901
your knowledge
of the doctrine of stoicism

1605
01:45:46,435 --> 01:45:48,513
<i>by holding back your tears,</i>

1606
01:45:48,868 --> 01:45:50,866
<i>I'll stop.</i>

1607
01:45:52,268 --> 01:45:54,266
<i>Have you got that?</i>

1608
01:46:06,535 --> 01:46:09,991
<i>In her lifetime,
Grace had had considerable practice</i>

1609
01:46:10,535 --> 01:46:13,492
<i>at constraining her emotions
and would never have believed</i>

1610
01:46:13,968 --> 01:46:16,216
<i>it would be hard
to control them now.</i>

1611
01:46:17,635 --> 01:46:20,382
<i>But as the porcelain
pulverized on the floor,</i>

1612
01:46:20,834 --> 01:46:24,641
<i>it was as if it were
human tissue disintegrating.</i>

1613
01:46:26,268 --> 01:46:28,546
<i>The figurines were the offspring
of the meeting</i>

1614
01:46:28,935 --> 01:46:31,073
<i>between the township and her.</i>

1615
01:46:31,435 --> 01:46:34,422
<i>They were the proof
that in spite of everything,</i>

1616
01:46:34,901 --> 01:46:38,148
<i>her suffering had created
something of value.</i>

1617
01:46:38,669 --> 01:46:42,095
<i>Grace could no longer cope.</i>

1618
01:46:42,635 --> 01:46:47,350
<i>For the first time
since her childhood, she wept.</i>

1619
01:47:17,335 --> 01:47:19,852
<i>Grace went to see Tom
that very night</i>

1620
01:47:20,268 --> 01:47:22,725
<i>and informed him that
she was ready to follow his advice</i>

1621
01:47:23,135 --> 01:47:25,133
<i>and leave the township.</i>

1622
01:47:25,235 --> 01:47:27,952
<i>And since Tom
had just made up his mind</i>

1623
01:47:28,402 --> 01:47:31,938
<i>that a third party would be needed
to ensure the success of an escape,</i>

1624
01:47:32,502 --> 01:47:35,489
<i>they agreed that Ben
possessed the greatest potential.</i>

1625
01:47:37,035 --> 01:47:40,811
<i>But it was a case where money
was required, Tom concluded.</i>

1626
01:47:41,402 --> 01:47:44,589
<i>And estimated
that considering the times and all,</i>

1627
01:47:45,101 --> 01:47:47,968
<i>$10 would suffice
for Ben and his truck.</i>

1628
01:47:48,435 --> 01:47:50,433
But we don't have $10.

1629
01:47:50,602 --> 01:47:52,969
Then we borrow it.

1630
01:47:53,368 --> 01:47:56,235
- From whom?
- From Dad.

1631
01:47:56,701 --> 01:47:59,069
He has more than that
in the medicine closet.

1632
01:47:59,468 --> 01:48:02,015
I'll talk to him in the morning,
arrange a loan.

1633
01:48:02,435 --> 01:48:04,433
But you have a word with Ben.

1634
01:48:04,768 --> 01:48:07,076
It's the end of the week,
he's bound to be flat broke.

1635
01:48:08,968 --> 01:48:11,596
Tell your father
that I will pay him back.

1636
01:48:12,035 --> 01:48:14,033
Of course!

1637
01:48:17,935 --> 01:48:19,933
Thank you.

1638
01:48:22,768 --> 01:48:26,225
You're always... rescuing me.

1639
01:48:29,968 --> 01:48:32,715
I can't believe you go on
being there for me.

1640
01:48:35,734 --> 01:48:37,732
Good night.

1641
01:48:39,868 --> 01:48:41,866
<i>You should get some sleep.</i>

1642
01:48:50,668 --> 01:48:53,326
<i>Grace went to see Ben next morning.</i>

1643
01:48:54,935 --> 01:48:57,153
Ben?

1644
01:48:57,535 --> 01:48:59,533
<i>When Grace presented the payment</i>

1645
01:48:59,868 --> 01:49:03,525
<i>as compensation between friends,
Ben did not object too heartily,</i>

1646
01:49:04,101 --> 01:49:07,258
<i>considering the trouble he could receive
from the rest of the townspeople</i>

1647
01:49:07,768 --> 01:49:09,906
<i>when they realized
what had happened.</i>

1648
01:49:10,268 --> 01:49:13,544
<i>Perhaps they'd all be relieved
that she was out of their lives,</i>

1649
01:49:14,068 --> 01:49:17,025
<i>but somehow
Grace wasn't too sure of that.</i>

1650
01:49:17,502 --> 01:49:20,718
<i>Ben agreed to drive her,
even though he wasn't out to profit</i>

1651
01:49:21,235 --> 01:49:24,162
<i>from other folks' misfortunes,
as he put it.</i>

1652
01:49:24,634 --> 01:49:27,352
I don't want to profit
from other folks' misfortunes.

1653
01:49:27,801 --> 01:49:28,934
No.

1654
01:49:28,935 --> 01:49:32,831
<i>The fact was Ben would have driven
to the gates of hell and back for $10.</i>

1655
01:49:33,435 --> 01:49:37,351
<i>And the criminal aspect bugged him less
than Grace would ever have guessed.</i>

1656
01:49:37,968 --> 01:49:41,305
<i>He had freighted
all kinds of things in his day.</i>

1657
01:49:41,834 --> 01:49:45,111
<i>The plan was for Grace
to hide among the apples.</i>

1658
01:49:45,634 --> 01:49:47,632
<i>"Knowing the exact time to harvest</i>

1659
01:49:47,901 --> 01:49:50,069
<i>is the greatest art of all,"
Chuck had said.</i>

1660
01:49:50,435 --> 01:49:52,334
<i>And the time had come</i>

1661
01:49:52,335 --> 01:49:55,142
<i>for the apples and for Grace.</i>

1662
01:49:55,601 --> 01:49:57,739
Grace, where you been?
If I'd have displayed

1663
01:49:58,101 --> 01:50:00,179
the same indifference
to the timing of my chores,

1664
01:50:00,534 --> 01:50:03,342
I'd be in for a whipping.
Now get a move on!

1665
01:50:03,801 --> 01:50:07,488
I'm sorry, Olivia,
I had to talk to Ben about something...

1666
01:50:08,068 --> 01:50:09,267
June is near to bursting.

1667
01:50:09,268 --> 01:50:11,575
She can't use the pot on her own,
as you well know.

1668
01:50:11,968 --> 01:50:15,425
It ain't fittin' to toy with her because
she crippled and can't help herself.

1669
01:50:19,901 --> 01:50:23,557
<i>The evening before the escape,
Tom tactically thought it best</i>

1670
01:50:24,135 --> 01:50:27,322
<i>not to press his desires of the flesh
too hard upon Grace.</i>

1671
01:50:28,801 --> 01:50:32,637
<i>And instead, he adopted
a more sensitive approach.</i>

1672
01:50:34,768 --> 01:50:38,335
There's a right and a wrong time
to plant seeds.

1673
01:50:38,901 --> 01:50:40,899
You can't plant seeds in the winter.

1674
01:50:42,701 --> 01:50:44,699
That's true,

1675
01:50:44,768 --> 01:50:46,766
but I love you...

1676
01:50:46,801 --> 01:50:48,909
- I know.
- ...and you love me.

1677
01:50:49,268 --> 01:50:52,454
And we will meet again
in love and in freedom.

1678
01:50:52,968 --> 01:50:55,366
Absolutely.

1679
01:50:55,768 --> 01:50:57,766
I shouldn't be ashamed
wanting you, should I?

1680
01:50:58,068 --> 01:51:00,965
- It's nothing to be ashamed of.
- No.

1681
01:51:01,435 --> 01:51:02,700
I know.

1682
01:51:02,701 --> 01:51:05,628
No, it's lovely.
It's lovely that we want each other.

1683
01:51:07,834 --> 01:51:10,142
- But not this way.
- No.

1684
01:51:10,534 --> 01:51:12,672
It's not right.

1685
01:51:22,601 --> 01:51:24,649
<i>The next morning, when Grace</i>

1686
01:51:25,001 --> 01:51:27,608
<i>wanted to slip down
to Ben's as invisibly as possible,</i>

1687
01:51:28,035 --> 01:51:30,582
<i>it seemed to Grace
that the entire township</i>

1688
01:51:31,001 --> 01:51:33,399
<i>was out and about
at the same time.</i>

1689
01:51:33,801 --> 01:51:36,169
- Grace?
- Yes, Vera?

1690
01:51:36,568 --> 01:51:38,876
If you think that by hitting my child,

1691
01:51:39,268 --> 01:51:41,575
you can get out of working
for me, think again.

1692
01:51:41,968 --> 01:51:45,155
Why don't you just
come by as planned and we'll...

1693
01:51:45,668 --> 01:51:48,006
find something where
you won't be able to harm anyone.

1694
01:51:48,401 --> 01:51:50,399
At... 12:00?

1695
01:51:50,534 --> 01:51:52,167
Yes.

1696
01:51:52,168 --> 01:51:55,235
Why are you taking your copious
belongings around with you?

1697
01:51:55,734 --> 01:51:57,842
<i>Afraid you're gonna lose them?</i>

1698
01:51:58,201 --> 01:52:01,008
Grace, Ben is hauling apples today,
so we won't be loading glasses.

1699
01:52:01,467 --> 01:52:03,465
But that don't mean you're off work.

1700
01:52:03,501 --> 01:52:05,609
Dad wants you to repack
the whole last load.

1701
01:52:05,968 --> 01:52:08,545
Maybe you can do it better
and we'll have an extra crate.

1702
01:52:08,968 --> 01:52:11,575
<i>An old crate like that may not have
much value in your eyes,</i>

1703
01:52:12,001 --> 01:52:13,800
<i>but this is Dogville.</i>

1704
01:52:13,801 --> 01:52:15,799
We're not wealthy here.

1705
01:52:16,035 --> 01:52:17,867
And if your hands get a bit red,

1706
01:52:17,868 --> 01:52:20,206
I've got a tip about something
you can rub on them.

1707
01:52:20,601 --> 01:52:22,334
<i>Grace.</i>

1708
01:52:22,335 --> 01:52:24,472
- Martha.
- Hi.

1709
01:52:25,901 --> 01:52:28,358
We have to wash the flagstones
at the foot of the steps again.

1710
01:52:28,768 --> 01:52:31,395
<i>Dirt's gone and blown under the door.
I can't get the door open...</i>

1711
01:52:31,834 --> 01:52:33,832
Where have you been?

1712
01:52:34,101 --> 01:52:36,319
Harvest is the holiest time of the year.

1713
01:52:36,701 --> 01:52:39,329
Doesn't that sound like something
you could have said?

1714
01:52:39,768 --> 01:52:42,955
I'll be down in a minute, Chuck.

1715
01:52:43,467 --> 01:52:47,124
- I'll bring the crates down.
- Good.

1716
01:52:47,701 --> 01:52:50,309
<i>As Grace hastened
to the garage, she grew</i>

1717
01:52:50,734 --> 01:52:55,090
<i>more and more pleased with the decision
to keep her departure under wraps.</i>

1718
01:52:55,768 --> 01:53:00,244
<i>There was actually quite a bit of work
Dogville didn't need doing,</i>

1719
01:53:00,935 --> 01:53:04,441
<i>that its residents would have
to carry out for themselves in future.</i>

1720
01:53:05,001 --> 01:53:07,488
Grace, I don't like having to say this,

1721
01:53:07,901 --> 01:53:11,178
but I'd like to ask if I could have
the money up front.

1722
01:53:11,701 --> 01:53:15,268
See, it's always the way
in the freight industry...

1723
01:53:15,834 --> 01:53:18,491
once you deliver a load,
you ain't got much to bargain with,

1724
01:53:18,935 --> 01:53:21,772
<i>- if you catch my drift.</i>
- Of course, here's the money.

1725
01:53:22,235 --> 01:53:24,542
Not that this is a professional job,
of course.

1726
01:53:24,935 --> 01:53:28,182
- Don't get out, till I give the say-so.
- All right, Ben.

1727
01:53:49,701 --> 01:53:52,828
<i>Canyon Road
snaked down the valley and away</i>

1728
01:53:53,334 --> 01:53:55,672
<i>and Grace went too.</i>

1729
01:53:56,068 --> 01:53:57,833
<i>And with every bend,</i>

1730
01:53:57,834 --> 01:53:59,733
<i>the township and its noises</i>

1731
01:53:59,734 --> 01:54:02,311
<i>faded ever more mercifully
behind her.</i>

1732
01:54:51,935 --> 01:54:54,832
- Something wrong?
- Yeah.

1733
01:54:55,301 --> 01:54:58,258
There are a hell of a lot
of police up ahead.

1734
01:54:59,868 --> 01:55:02,415
I wasn't expecting that.

1735
01:55:02,834 --> 01:55:05,491
It's more dangerous than I thought.

1736
01:55:05,935 --> 01:55:08,652
We'll have to go back.

1737
01:55:09,101 --> 01:55:10,800
- Back?
- Yeah.

1738
01:55:10,801 --> 01:55:13,728
- No, we can't do that.
- No, but...

1739
01:55:14,200 --> 01:55:16,598
it's just, if this was a...

1740
01:55:17,001 --> 01:55:19,109
- a professional transport job...
- No, Ben.

1741
01:55:19,467 --> 01:55:22,075
Paid proper like,
it would be a lot easier.

1742
01:55:24,768 --> 01:55:26,816
But it's been paid for.

1743
01:55:27,168 --> 01:55:30,065
Yeah, but in the freight industry

1744
01:55:30,534 --> 01:55:32,722
carrying a dangerous load,

1745
01:55:33,101 --> 01:55:35,099
it costs more.

1746
01:55:36,101 --> 01:55:38,908
A surcharge, they call it.

1747
01:55:39,367 --> 01:55:41,975
If this were a professional job,

1748
01:55:42,401 --> 01:55:45,388
I could just charge you.

1749
01:55:48,135 --> 01:55:50,882
But, Ben,
I don't have any more money.

1750
01:55:55,668 --> 01:55:58,735
That's no good then.

1751
01:56:02,401 --> 01:56:04,399
You said once...

1752
01:56:04,701 --> 01:56:06,699
you said once

1753
01:56:06,768 --> 01:56:09,165
that there aren't
many pleasures in my life.

1754
01:56:12,734 --> 01:56:15,361
You know I go to Miss Laura
once a week.

1755
01:56:15,801 --> 01:56:17,567
Yes.

1756
01:56:17,568 --> 01:56:20,555
And you, you got me to see that

1757
01:56:21,035 --> 01:56:23,782
it weren't nothing to be ashamed of.

1758
01:56:25,501 --> 01:56:27,839
And see...

1759
01:56:28,234 --> 01:56:31,481
I was gonna go there tonight.

1760
01:56:34,200 --> 01:56:37,737
And of course, it costs me.

1761
01:56:42,501 --> 01:56:45,338
Not as much as...

1762
01:56:45,801 --> 01:56:50,017
not as much as a surcharge for...

1763
01:56:50,668 --> 01:56:52,666
for dangerous goods,

1764
01:56:52,768 --> 01:56:54,766
but still...

1765
01:56:56,267 --> 01:56:58,665
it does cost me, you know.

1766
01:56:59,068 --> 01:57:01,935
- No, Ben, no, please don't.
- No, no, no, no, no.

1767
01:57:02,401 --> 01:57:05,418
It's not personal, Grace,
it's not personal.

1768
01:57:05,901 --> 01:57:08,298
- I just...
- No.

1769
01:57:08,701 --> 01:57:11,128
I have to take due payment,
that's all.

1770
01:57:12,534 --> 01:57:15,721
- I don't have a choice.
- No, Ben.

1771
01:57:16,234 --> 01:57:18,952
I can't buck the freight industry,
can I?

1772
01:57:19,401 --> 01:57:22,498
No.

1773
01:57:23,001 --> 01:57:25,778
We're parked in the square
in Georgetown.

1774
01:57:27,200 --> 01:57:29,198
Right outside the church.

1775
01:57:29,434 --> 01:57:32,211
You'd better keep your voice down.

1776
01:57:35,901 --> 01:57:37,899
No, Ben.

1777
01:57:37,968 --> 01:57:41,364
This ain't something
I'm proud of, Grace.

1778
01:57:41,901 --> 01:57:44,418
Don't go thinking that.

1779
01:58:16,334 --> 01:58:18,702
<i>Grace fell asleep
on the long highway,</i>

1780
01:58:19,100 --> 01:58:21,208
<i>thanks to her healthy ability</i>

1781
01:58:21,568 --> 01:58:24,465
<i>to push any unpleasantness
around her far away.</i>

1782
01:58:24,935 --> 01:58:27,802
<i>A generous God had blessed her
with the rare talent</i>

1783
01:58:28,267 --> 01:58:30,265
<i>of being able to look ahead</i>

1784
01:58:30,367 --> 01:58:32,365
<i>and only ahead.</i>

1785
01:58:34,067 --> 01:58:36,065
<i>And later
when the truck slowed down</i>

1786
01:58:36,200 --> 01:58:38,198
<i>about to reach its destination</i>

1787
01:58:38,301 --> 01:58:40,759
<i>and she slowly returned
to consciousness,</i>

1788
01:58:41,167 --> 01:58:44,124
<i>she had no way of knowing
how long she had slept.</i>

1789
01:58:44,601 --> 01:58:48,577
<i>All she knew was that she would be happy
to see the light of day again.</i>

1790
01:58:50,568 --> 01:58:54,954
<i>And then she heard the dog.</i>

1791
01:59:00,367 --> 01:59:03,404
All your fondness for apples
seems less and less believable, see?

1792
01:59:03,901 --> 01:59:05,899
You bruised them.

1793
01:59:18,668 --> 01:59:21,535
We had a meeting last night
at the mission house.

1794
01:59:24,134 --> 01:59:27,291
They said you might be
gonna try to run away.

1795
01:59:27,801 --> 01:59:29,819
So when I discovered you'd...

1796
01:59:30,167 --> 01:59:32,355
hidden yourself away on my truck...

1797
01:59:33,801 --> 01:59:36,728
I didn't have no choice
but to bring you back to Dogville.

1798
01:59:39,134 --> 01:59:41,212
In the freight industry
we can't take sides.

1799
02:00:25,601 --> 02:00:27,599
<i>It didn't help Grace</i>

1800
02:00:27,668 --> 02:00:30,005
<i>that the first theft
ever registered in Dogville</i>

1801
02:00:30,401 --> 02:00:32,399
<i>had taken place
the previous evening</i>

1802
02:00:32,501 --> 02:00:35,218
<i>when most people were assembled
for the town meeting.</i>

1803
02:00:35,668 --> 02:00:39,034
<i>Old Tom Edison Sr.
had had a considerable sum of money</i>

1804
02:00:39,568 --> 02:00:42,994
<i>stolen from his medicine closet,
and suspicion soon fell on Grace,</i>

1805
02:00:43,534 --> 02:00:45,722
<i>who had apparently been
planning an escape</i>

1806
02:00:46,100 --> 02:00:48,208
<i>that would surely require funding.</i>

1807
02:00:49,534 --> 02:00:51,532
<i>Grace chose to remain silent</i>

1808
02:00:51,801 --> 02:00:53,938
<i>in the face of these new charges.</i>

1809
02:00:55,267 --> 02:00:58,953
<i>And then Bill, who had lately
improved his engineering skills</i>

1810
02:00:59,534 --> 02:01:02,930
<i>to an astonishing degree,
had by way of his first design</i>

1811
02:01:03,467 --> 02:01:06,833
<i>implemented a kind
of escape prevention mechanism.</i>

1812
02:01:07,367 --> 02:01:09,854
<i>Beautiful, it might not have been,</i>

1813
02:01:10,267 --> 02:01:13,394
<i>but effective, he dared say it was.</i>

1814
02:01:23,934 --> 02:01:25,982
Grace,

1815
02:01:26,334 --> 02:01:28,961
we don't like having to do this.

1816
02:01:29,401 --> 02:01:31,539
<i>We don't have much of a choice,</i>

1817
02:01:31,900 --> 02:01:34,388
<i>if we're to protect our community.</i>

1818
02:01:34,801 --> 02:01:36,938
Could you, would you mind moving?

1819
02:01:37,301 --> 02:01:39,299
Try moving?

1820
02:01:58,967 --> 02:02:00,965
It works.

1821
02:02:01,267 --> 02:02:03,285
We had to make this heavy enough

1822
02:02:03,634 --> 02:02:05,941
<i>so that it could only move...</i>

1823
02:02:06,334 --> 02:02:08,166
<i>where the ground is level,</i>

1824
02:02:08,167 --> 02:02:10,685
<i>and the ground is level in town.</i>

1825
02:02:16,234 --> 02:02:18,692
May I go now?

1826
02:02:23,967 --> 02:02:27,154
I have to figure out
how I'm gonna get into my house.

1827
02:02:29,701 --> 02:02:33,067
Or is that part of the punishment,
having to sleep outdoors?

1828
02:02:33,601 --> 02:02:35,998
No, no, no, no, Grace.

1829
02:02:36,401 --> 02:02:38,828
Don't think of this as punishment,

1830
02:02:39,234 --> 02:02:41,452
not at all.

1831
02:02:41,833 --> 02:02:44,641
See, Bill, he made
the chain long enough

1832
02:02:45,100 --> 02:02:47,348
<i>so that you can sleep in your bed.</i>

1833
02:02:57,900 --> 02:02:59,898
Grace, 6:00.

1834
02:03:02,601 --> 02:03:05,438
Yes, Mrs. Henson.

1835
02:03:12,383 --> 02:03:16,633
CHAPTER EIGHT in which there is
a meeting where the truth is told

1836
02:03:16,800 --> 02:03:20,217
and Tom leaves
(only to return later).

1837
02:03:29,067 --> 02:03:31,145
I'm...

1838
02:03:33,634 --> 02:03:36,001
I couldn't run the risk
of Dad turning me down.

1839
02:03:36,401 --> 02:03:39,208
They think it was me
that took the money.

1840
02:03:39,668 --> 02:03:42,325
Because I told them so.

1841
02:03:45,934 --> 02:03:47,932
You did what?

1842
02:03:48,067 --> 02:03:51,284
First, they suspected me, but then
I convinced them that it was you

1843
02:03:51,800 --> 02:03:54,288
since you were the one
using the medicine closet.

1844
02:03:55,667 --> 02:03:57,266
Why?

1845
02:03:57,267 --> 02:03:59,515
It's good I'm here
to do the thinking for you.

1846
02:03:59,900 --> 02:04:02,857
If we are to have the slightest chance
of getting you out of here...

1847
02:04:04,767 --> 02:04:07,754
they can never know
how close we really are.

1848
02:04:09,301 --> 02:04:12,458
They can't know
I'm trying to help you.

1849
02:04:14,601 --> 02:04:16,648
If they knew it was me
that took the money,

1850
02:04:17,000 --> 02:04:19,368
I wouldn't be here
talking to you now.

1851
02:04:21,634 --> 02:04:24,591
Please, don't disappear, Tom.

1852
02:04:30,568 --> 02:04:33,285
I need you.

1853
02:04:35,667 --> 02:04:37,665
<i>I'll break this one
with some thinking.</i>

1854
02:04:48,833 --> 02:04:50,851
<i>It was not Grace's pride</i>

1855
02:04:51,200 --> 02:04:53,747
<i>that kept her going
during the days when fall came</i>

1856
02:04:54,167 --> 02:04:56,165
<i>and the trees
were losing their leaves,</i>

1857
02:04:56,501 --> 02:04:58,928
<i>but more of the trancelike state
that descends</i>

1858
02:04:59,334 --> 02:05:01,582
<i>on animals
whose lives are threatened,</i>

1859
02:05:01,967 --> 02:05:04,455
<i>a state in which the body
reacts mechanically,</i>

1860
02:05:04,867 --> 02:05:08,963
<i>in a low, tough gear,
without too much painful reflection,</i>

1861
02:05:09,600 --> 02:05:13,786
<i>like a patient passively
letting his disease hold sway.</i>

1862
02:05:14,434 --> 02:05:17,561
<i>And now that Vera
had received proof</i>

1863
02:05:18,067 --> 02:05:20,065
<i>that it was in fact Chuck</i>

1864
02:05:20,234 --> 02:05:24,420
<i>who'd forced his attentions on Grace,
