<i>because they couldn't really
be compared to a sexual act.</i>

1877
02:06:08,234 --> 02:06:10,661
<i>They were embarrassing,
in the way it is</i>

1878
02:06:11,067 --> 02:06:13,065
<i>when a hillbilly has his way
with a cow,</i>

1879
02:06:13,334 --> 02:06:15,332
<i>but no more than that.</i>

1880
02:06:16,567 --> 02:06:19,584
<i>Tom saw everything. It pained him.</i>

1881
02:06:20,067 --> 02:06:23,344
<i>And the sexual visits
were a particularly severe blow.</i>

1882
02:06:23,867 --> 02:06:25,865
Good night.

1883
02:06:30,633 --> 02:06:33,670
<i>But he supported her
as best he could,</i>

1884
02:06:34,167 --> 02:06:36,165
<i>the way a spider supports</i>

1885
02:06:36,367 --> 02:06:39,963
<i>when it has been tangled
in its own web by the wind.</i>

1886
02:06:40,533 --> 02:06:43,051
<i>Tom.</i>

1887
02:06:48,867 --> 02:06:51,385
Everything I tried to do
went wrong.

1888
02:06:52,800 --> 02:06:55,867
I can't come up with the answer
I was looking for.

1889
02:06:56,367 --> 02:06:58,794
You'll come up with it, you'll see.

1890
02:06:59,200 --> 02:07:01,657
You're very clever.

1891
02:07:03,034 --> 02:07:05,032
I provoked them.

1892
02:07:05,367 --> 02:07:07,554
I wouldn't worry about it.

1893
02:07:12,800 --> 02:07:16,197
We provoked them, now it's time
for us to provoke ourselves.

1894
02:07:16,733 --> 02:07:18,731
- What do you mean?
- I mean...

1895
02:07:20,434 --> 02:07:23,910
by showing them some trust.
It all started with a meeting,

1896
02:07:24,466 --> 02:07:27,304
so it would be logical
to end it with one too.

1897
02:07:27,767 --> 02:07:31,244
You'll talk, they'll listen.
They can't refuse to listen.

1898
02:07:33,267 --> 02:07:37,363
- What will I say?
- Everything, you'll say everything.

1899
02:07:38,000 --> 02:07:39,998
<i>- Everything?</i>
- Yeah, the truth, the truth,

1900
02:07:40,334 --> 02:07:43,111
just the truth
about each and every one of them.

1901
02:07:43,567 --> 02:07:45,565
I don't think
they're gonna want to hear that.

1902
02:07:45,767 --> 02:07:48,724
No, I know, I know.
It's like a child...

1903
02:07:49,200 --> 02:07:51,777
who doesn't want
to take his medicine.

1904
02:07:52,200 --> 02:07:55,736
They'll be furious at first,
but in the end, they'll see that it's...

1905
02:07:56,301 --> 02:07:58,299
it's for their own good.

1906
02:07:58,567 --> 02:08:00,565
Just don't be hateful.

1907
02:08:00,667 --> 02:08:03,065
Don't be reproving.

1908
02:08:03,466 --> 02:08:06,743
If anybody can do it,
Grace, you can.

1909
02:08:07,267 --> 02:08:11,652
They'll all realize that this web
of misunderstanding and injustice

1910
02:08:12,334 --> 02:08:14,581
has only one true victim
and that's you.

1911
02:08:14,967 --> 02:08:18,364
And from there it's only
one small step to forgiveness.

1912
02:08:19,867 --> 02:08:24,173
You've done some hard thinking,
Tom Edison.

1913
02:08:25,900 --> 02:08:28,887
I'm sure it's an excellent plan.

1914
02:08:29,367 --> 02:08:31,414
I'm sure.

1915
02:08:49,833 --> 02:08:52,700
<i>If forgiveness
was close at hand in the mission house,</i>

1916
02:08:53,167 --> 02:08:56,064
<i>they were all hiding it well.</i>

1917
02:08:56,533 --> 02:08:59,400
<i>It hadn't been easy for Tom
to get them there.</i>

1918
02:08:59,867 --> 02:09:01,915
<i>Appealing to consciences</i>

1919
02:09:02,267 --> 02:09:05,663
<i>stowed farther and farther away
by their owners every day,</i>

1920
02:09:06,200 --> 02:09:09,676
<i>as if they were as fragile
as Henson's glasses after polishing,</i>

1921
02:09:10,234 --> 02:09:12,232
<i>had proved quite a task.</i>

1922
02:09:13,567 --> 02:09:16,904
<i>But if one was going, the others
might as well come along too...</i>

1923
02:09:17,433 --> 02:09:19,651
<i>so nobody could talk
behind anybody's back.</i>

1924
02:09:22,500 --> 02:09:25,308
<i>Tom had set the scene
for Grace's speech.</i>

1925
02:09:25,767 --> 02:09:28,864
<i>Now, she'd have to sink or swim</i>

1926
02:09:29,366 --> 02:09:32,234
<i>and sincerity be brought to bear.</i>

1927
02:09:32,700 --> 02:09:34,698
<i>While Grace addressed</i>

1928
02:09:34,967 --> 02:09:37,744
<i>the silent congregation
in the mission house on Elm Street,</i>

1929
02:09:38,200 --> 02:09:42,096
<i>the first of the early autumn
snowstorms embraced the town.</i>

1930
02:09:42,700 --> 02:09:45,977
<i>The snowflakes dusted down
over the old buildings</i>

1931
02:09:46,500 --> 02:09:49,158
<i>as if this were just any old town.</i>

1932
02:09:49,600 --> 02:09:51,598
<i>And they played
in the branches and twigs,</i>

1933
02:09:51,934 --> 02:09:53,932
<i>from which the apples had hung.</i>

1934
02:09:54,000 --> 02:09:55,998
<i>But luckily the harvest was home</i>

1935
02:09:56,267 --> 02:09:58,574
<i>and, via the freight industry,
had found a market</i>

1936
02:09:58,967 --> 02:10:01,304
<i>despite the ever-disappointing prices.</i>

1937
02:10:01,700 --> 02:10:04,567
<i>Grace had presented
her story with clarity.</i>

1938
02:10:05,034 --> 02:10:07,721
<i>She had not embellished
or understated.</i>

1939
02:10:08,167 --> 02:10:12,732
<i>And just as she finished, the snowflakes
all at once stopped tumbling down,</i>

1940
02:10:13,433 --> 02:10:16,800
<i>leaving Dogville
clad in the daintiest,</i>

1941
02:10:17,333 --> 02:10:20,231
<i>whitest blanket of snow
imaginable.</i>

1942
02:10:27,466 --> 02:10:29,464
Hmph.

1943
02:10:40,333 --> 02:10:42,381
I don't think it went very well.

1944
02:10:42,733 --> 02:10:45,800
It's fine. You did good.

1945
02:10:53,167 --> 02:10:57,083
<i>The snow had
come early, perhaps too early...</i>

1946
02:10:57,700 --> 02:11:01,067
<i>a misplaced augury
of conciliation?</i>

1947
02:11:02,600 --> 02:11:04,908
<i>Tom looked around, worried.</i>

1948
02:11:05,300 --> 02:11:08,897
<i>Vera's teeth were clenched.
She was the first to speak.</i>

1949
02:11:09,466 --> 02:11:11,804
Copious lies, just lies.

1950
02:11:12,200 --> 02:11:14,807
Yes, Tom, that didn't
accord with the perception

1951
02:11:15,233 --> 02:11:17,231
that I have of this town
and its residents.

1952
02:11:17,567 --> 02:11:20,994
I'm a doctor, damn it. I'm capable
of determining if I'm sick or not.

1953
02:11:21,533 --> 02:11:23,531
What do you have to say
for yourself, Tom?

1954
02:11:23,600 --> 02:11:25,998
Maybe it's time you picked sides.

1955
02:11:26,400 --> 02:11:28,508
Are you for us or against us?

1956
02:11:28,867 --> 02:11:31,674
Liz is right, we've been
far too indulgent with Tom.

1957
02:11:32,134 --> 02:11:35,470
<i>Tom, I got to tell you,
even I have trouble defending that girl.</i>

1958
02:11:36,000 --> 02:11:40,415
With your help, which I prefer
to think was accidental, Tom,

1959
02:11:41,100 --> 02:11:44,876
she's been managed
to spread bitterness

1960
02:11:45,466 --> 02:11:48,943
and trouble throughout
this whole town. She has to go!

1961
02:11:49,500 --> 02:11:51,198
<i>How do we get rid of her, Tom?</i>

1962
02:11:51,199 --> 02:11:53,337
<i>- How do we do it, Tom?
- I agree, Tom.</i>

1963
02:11:53,700 --> 02:11:56,357
You brought her in here, you have
to figure out how to get her out.

1964
02:11:56,800 --> 02:11:58,798
Without her lies
and accusations spreading.

1965
02:12:02,400 --> 02:12:04,398
I asked you here to listen.

1966
02:12:07,533 --> 02:12:09,991
You only came
to defend yourselves.

1967
02:12:10,400 --> 02:12:14,556
I'm sorry. It's quite a blow to me,

1968
02:12:15,199 --> 02:12:19,295
to see all of my friends
act this way...

1969
02:12:22,166 --> 02:12:24,274
so uncivilized.

1970
02:13:18,400 --> 02:13:21,417
Your plan didn't work out
very well, did it?

1971
02:13:23,300 --> 02:13:27,136
- You'll think of another one.
- No.

1972
02:13:27,733 --> 02:13:30,890
No more plans, I promise.

1973
02:13:36,600 --> 02:13:39,587
They asked me to choose
between you and them.

1974
02:13:41,867 --> 02:13:45,673
That's not difficult
on a day like today, I love you.

1975
02:13:46,266 --> 02:13:50,272
You may be stronger,
it's true, with the ideals,

1976
02:13:50,900 --> 02:13:52,898
the ideals we share.

1977
02:13:54,233 --> 02:13:56,661
I'm exhausted.

1978
02:13:58,600 --> 02:14:00,738
Lie down.

1979
02:14:07,199 --> 02:14:09,337
I've chosen, Grace,

1980
02:14:10,967 --> 02:14:13,334
I've chosen you.

1981
02:14:17,300 --> 02:14:19,848
And now it's the time,

1982
02:14:20,266 --> 02:14:23,103
the time we've been waiting for.

1983
02:14:27,166 --> 02:14:30,033
We've freed ourselves of Dogville.

1984
02:14:36,033 --> 02:14:38,661
You're right.

1985
02:14:39,099 --> 02:14:42,846
You're right, Tom, it would be
so easy to make love right now.

1986
02:14:44,967 --> 02:14:47,424
They may kill us any minute,

1987
02:14:47,833 --> 02:14:50,490
it would be the perfect
romantic ending...

1988
02:14:50,934 --> 02:14:52,932
You know I feel it too.

1989
02:14:57,500 --> 02:15:00,367
It would be so beautiful,
but from...

1990
02:15:00,833 --> 02:15:05,048
from the point of view of our love,
so completely wrong.

1991
02:15:10,300 --> 02:15:12,668
We were to meet in freedom.

1992
02:15:25,867 --> 02:15:28,174
You're cold now, Grace.

1993
02:15:38,066 --> 02:15:42,132
I just rejected everybody
I've ever known in your favor.

1994
02:15:44,466 --> 02:15:47,303
Wouldn't it be worth compromising
just one of your ideals

1995
02:15:47,767 --> 02:15:50,344
just a little to ease my pain?

1996
02:15:53,533 --> 02:15:56,370
<i>Everybody in this town
has had your body but me.</i>

1997
02:15:57,900 --> 02:16:00,387
We're the ones
supposed to be in love.

1998
02:16:03,133 --> 02:16:05,131
<i>My darting Tom.</i>

1999
02:16:09,233 --> 02:16:11,721
You can have me if you want me.

2000
02:16:15,433 --> 02:16:17,431
Just do what the others do.

2001
02:16:18,900 --> 02:16:21,147
Threaten me.

2002
02:16:21,533 --> 02:16:24,690
<i>Tell me that you'll turn me in
to the law, to the gangsters,</i>

2003
02:16:25,199 --> 02:16:27,687
and I promise you,

2004
02:16:28,099 --> 02:16:31,526
you can take
whatever it is you want from me.

2005
02:16:33,633 --> 02:16:35,851
I trust you.

2006
02:16:38,033 --> 02:16:40,781
But maybe you don't trust yourself.

2007
02:16:41,233 --> 02:16:44,660
Perhaps you've been tempted.

2008
02:16:45,199 --> 02:16:48,266
You've been tempted
to join the others and force me?

2009
02:16:48,767 --> 02:16:51,864
Perhaps that's why you're so upset.

2010
02:16:52,366 --> 02:16:54,444
All I've ever tried to do is help you.

2011
02:16:54,800 --> 02:16:59,625
I'm just asking if you're afraid
you could be so human.

2012
02:17:00,366 --> 02:17:02,584
No, I'm not afraid of that,
not in the least.

2013
02:17:04,400 --> 02:17:06,398
Good.

2014
02:17:09,800 --> 02:17:13,306
Let tomorrow bring
what it's gonna bring.

2015
02:17:16,166 --> 02:17:18,164
It's not a crime

2016
02:17:18,466 --> 02:17:21,093
to doubt yourself, Tom.

2017
02:17:23,966 --> 02:17:27,063
But it's wonderful that you don't.

2018
02:17:28,600 --> 02:17:30,907
I can't find the rest.

2019
02:17:34,133 --> 02:17:36,621
I think I should go out
for a couple of minutes.

2020
02:17:38,933 --> 02:17:41,771
Take a walk
or something to get it...

2021
02:17:43,933 --> 02:17:46,421
get it all out of my system.

2022
02:17:48,366 --> 02:17:50,444
Trudge the streets,

2023
02:17:50,800 --> 02:17:52,967
listen to the wind as it passes

2024
02:17:53,333 --> 02:17:55,960
through the woods
up through the valley

2025
02:17:56,400 --> 02:17:58,648
and all that.

2026
02:18:02,066 --> 02:18:04,064
You go to sleep though.

2027
02:18:07,500 --> 02:18:09,578
You go to sleep

2028
02:18:09,933 --> 02:18:12,421
and I'll be back

2029
02:18:12,832 --> 02:18:14,940
very soon.

2030
02:18:22,300 --> 02:18:24,817
<i>Of course,
it was all a load of nonsense.</i>

2031
02:18:25,233 --> 02:18:29,589
<i>If anybody was capable of keeping
track of ideals and reality, he was.</i>

2032
02:18:30,266 --> 02:18:33,043
<i>After all, it was his job.</i>

2033
02:18:33,500 --> 02:18:36,307
<i>Moral issues were his home ground.</i>

2034
02:18:36,767 --> 02:18:39,803
<i>To think that he might
doubt his own purity</i>

2035
02:18:40,300 --> 02:18:42,378
<i>was really to think
very little of him.</i>

2036
02:18:42,733 --> 02:18:45,360
<i>Tom was angry.</i>

2037
02:18:48,099 --> 02:18:51,116
<i>And in the midst of it all,
he discovered why.</i>

2038
02:18:52,633 --> 02:18:55,150
<i>It was not because
he'd been wrongly accused,</i>

2039
02:18:55,567 --> 02:18:58,114
<i>but because the charges were true.</i>

2040
02:18:59,899 --> 02:19:03,056
<i>His anger consisted
of a most unpleasant feeling</i>

2041
02:19:03,567 --> 02:19:05,844
<i>of being found out.</i>

2042
02:19:08,533 --> 02:19:11,310
<i>It was all quite a blow
to the young philosopher.</i>

2043
02:19:11,766 --> 02:19:13,844
<i>And realistically enough,</i>

2044
02:19:14,199 --> 02:19:16,367
<i>he thought that if the doubt
was already present,</i>

2045
02:19:16,733 --> 02:19:19,600
<i>it could grow perhaps so great</i>

2046
02:19:20,066 --> 02:19:24,312
<i>that one day it would prove detrimental
to his entire moral mission.</i>

2047
02:19:24,966 --> 02:19:27,214
<i>Tom stopped.</i>

2048
02:19:27,600 --> 02:19:29,817
<i>He almost began to shake
when the threat</i>

2049
02:19:30,199 --> 02:19:32,687
<i>to his career as a writer
dawned upon him.</i>

2050
02:19:33,099 --> 02:19:35,617
<i>It didn't take him long
to agree with himself</i>

2051
02:19:36,033 --> 02:19:38,311
<i>that the risk was
too great to run.</i>

2052
02:19:38,700 --> 02:19:41,067
<i>The danger Grace was to the town,</i>

2053
02:19:41,466 --> 02:19:43,464
<i>she was also to him.</i>

2054
02:19:43,766 --> 02:19:45,764
<i>Tom did not like it</i>

2055
02:19:45,766 --> 02:19:49,633
<i>and he was man enough
to take action to prevent it.</i>

2056
02:19:52,133 --> 02:19:56,549
<i>Fortunately, Tom was as conscientious
as regards his future profession</i>

2057
02:19:57,233 --> 02:19:59,231
<i>as he was practical.</i>

2058
02:19:59,233 --> 02:20:02,889
<i>He allowed sincerity and ideals
plenty of room in his life</i>

2059
02:20:03,466 --> 02:20:07,122
<i>without getting sentimental
about it, as he would put it.</i>

2060
02:20:07,699 --> 02:20:11,176
<i>Throwing away a document
that might be of significance to Tom,</i>

2061
02:20:11,732 --> 02:20:13,840
<i>and with him
future generations of readers,</i>

2062
02:20:14,199 --> 02:20:16,976
<i>as a basis of a novel
or indeed a trilogy</i>

2063
02:20:17,433 --> 02:20:20,180
<i>was not an act
he was so stupid to commit.</i>

2064
02:20:20,633 --> 02:20:23,560
<i>Although he had to admit
that in a moment of weakness</i>

2065
02:20:24,033 --> 02:20:26,051
<i>he might have said he would.</i>

2066
02:20:29,300 --> 02:20:31,667
<i>Before returning
to the meeting that night,</i>

2067
02:20:32,066 --> 02:20:35,782
<i>Tom opened the little drawer he had
opened the night of Grace's arrival</i>

2068
02:20:36,366 --> 02:20:38,703
<i>and found it still there...</i>

2069
02:20:39,099 --> 02:20:41,846
<i>the card from the gangster
in the car.</i>

2070
02:21:02,966 --> 02:21:06,423
<i>The next day, the sun was
shining in the brisk autumn sky</i>

2071
02:21:06,966 --> 02:21:09,154
<i>and the snow was long since gone.</i>

2072
02:21:11,166 --> 02:21:13,164
<i>For the first time for ages</i>

2073
02:21:13,366 --> 02:21:15,673
<i>the pile driver could be heard
in the marshlands</i>

2074
02:21:16,066 --> 02:21:18,064
<i>as it hammered in the piles</i>

2075
02:21:18,166 --> 02:21:21,672
<i>of what might
or might not be a penitentiary.</i>

2076
02:21:22,233 --> 02:21:24,231
<i>Grace opened her eyes,</i>

2077
02:21:24,567 --> 02:21:27,873
<i>after an almost unconscious sleep
and was confused...</i>

2078
02:21:28,400 --> 02:21:31,297
<i>Judging by the light coming
through the cracks in the walls</i>

2079
02:21:31,766 --> 02:21:34,953
<i>it had to be nearly midday,
"the gray hour"</i>

2080
02:21:35,466 --> 02:21:38,802
<i>as Jack McKay, for some reason,
called noon in Dogville...</i>

2081
02:21:39,333 --> 02:21:41,990
<i>being a man of many ideas
and proclivities,</i>

2082
02:21:42,433 --> 02:21:46,149
<i>quite a few of which Grace would have
preferred to remain ignorant of.</i>

2083
02:21:46,732 --> 02:21:49,420
<i>But why had nobody roused her?</i>

2084
02:21:49,866 --> 02:21:52,354
<i>Nobody had hammered
furiously at her door,</i>

2085
02:21:52,766 --> 02:21:55,104
<i>not a child had thrown
mud into her bed</i>

2086
02:21:55,500 --> 02:21:57,957
<i>or broken
her remaining windowpanes.</i>

2087
02:21:58,366 --> 02:22:00,643
<i>Now she remembered.</i>

2088
02:22:01,033 --> 02:22:03,521
<i>She recalled
the meeting the previous day</i>

2089
02:22:03,933 --> 02:22:06,041
<i>and puzzled still more.</i>

2090
02:22:06,400 --> 02:22:09,497
<i>Why had she not been confronted
with the outcome of that meeting</i>

2091
02:22:09,999 --> 02:22:11,997
<i>or even killed?</i>

2092
02:22:12,300 --> 02:22:14,298
<i>It was quite unlike Dogville</i>

2093
02:22:14,500 --> 02:22:17,277
<i>to restrain its indignation
on any point.</i>

2094
02:22:17,732 --> 02:22:20,250
<i>Perhaps things had
turned out well after all.</i>

2095
02:22:20,666 --> 02:22:24,063
- Good morning, Mrs. Henson,
- Morning.

2096
02:22:24,599 --> 02:22:27,207
I would have come earlier, but I...

2097
02:22:27,632 --> 02:22:29,399
<i>I overslept.</i>

2098
02:22:29,400 --> 02:22:32,327
Never mind, Liz put
her back into it this morning.

2099
02:22:34,500 --> 02:22:36,837
We thought some time off
would be good for you.

2100
02:22:40,599 --> 02:22:42,597
That was quite a speech
you made yesterday.

2101
02:22:42,699 --> 02:22:44,867
Gave us all something
to think about.

2102
02:22:49,500 --> 02:22:52,047
- Hello, Liz.
- Hi, Grace.

2103
02:22:53,866 --> 02:22:55,864
Hi.

2104
02:22:59,799 --> 02:23:01,797
I overslept.

2105
02:23:02,599 --> 02:23:04,597
Morning, Miss Grace.

2106
02:23:05,532 --> 02:23:07,530
- Good morning.
- How you this morning?

2107
02:23:09,099 --> 02:23:11,906
- I overslept.
- That's all right.

2108
02:23:19,732 --> 02:23:21,598
It's Grace.

2109
02:23:21,599 --> 02:23:23,677
Hello, Grace.

2110
02:23:24,033 --> 02:23:26,031
Two seconds.

2111
02:23:26,133 --> 02:23:28,131
Good news.

2112
02:23:36,732 --> 02:23:38,730
I went back
to the meeting last night.

2113
02:23:40,699 --> 02:23:43,037
I wasn't gonna let them
get <i>off</i> so easy, but...

2114
02:23:45,799 --> 02:23:47,797
I'll be damned if the mood
hadn't changed.

2115
02:23:49,899 --> 02:23:51,897
I wouldn't say we won exactly,
not exactly,

2116
02:23:52,133 --> 02:23:54,470
but I think something very good
could come out of this...

2117
02:23:54,866 --> 02:23:58,902
- Why didn't you come back and tell me?
- No, I did, I did, but you were asleep.

2118
02:24:00,499 --> 02:24:02,497
And you looked like you needed it.

2119
02:24:03,666 --> 02:24:06,324
That made me suggest that maybe
you should have some time off.

2120
02:24:06,766 --> 02:24:08,814
And you know,

2121
02:24:09,166 --> 02:24:11,164
not one single person objected.

2122
02:24:16,400 --> 02:24:19,207
- That sounds wonderful.
- I know it does, doesn't it?

2123
02:24:20,866 --> 02:24:23,613
The people in this town,
they surprise me again and again.

2124
02:24:25,732 --> 02:24:28,420
I might even have to revise
my theories a little bit.

2125
02:24:28,866 --> 02:24:31,054
You know how much I hate
doing that kind of thing.

2126
02:24:33,899 --> 02:24:37,116
You know, Grace, last night
when I came back

2127
02:24:37,632 --> 02:24:39,650
and I saw you

2128
02:24:39,999 --> 02:24:42,367
lying there asleep so sweetly,

2129
02:24:42,766 --> 02:24:44,764
I was suddenly inspired.

2130
02:24:45,099 --> 02:24:48,136
I wrote the first chapter of a story...

2131
02:24:48,632 --> 02:24:50,880
a story about a small town.

2132
02:24:51,266 --> 02:24:53,374
Guess where I got the inspiration?

2133
02:24:53,732 --> 02:24:56,419
<i>But I haven't come up with a name
for the town yet.</i>

2134
02:24:58,300 --> 02:25:00,298
Why not just call it Dogville?

2135
02:25:00,333 --> 02:25:03,669
It wouldn't work, wouldn't work,
it's got to be universal.

2136
02:25:04,199 --> 02:25:06,337
A lot of writers
make that mistake, you see.

2137
02:25:06,699 --> 02:25:09,596
<i>Hey, you want me to read it to you?-</i>...

2138
02:25:10,066 --> 02:25:12,084
if there's any love in it,
it comes from you.

2139
02:25:12,432 --> 02:25:14,430
Would you be offended
if I said no?

2140
02:25:16,499 --> 02:25:20,156
- No.
- If I really have the day to myself...

2141
02:25:20,732 --> 02:25:23,130
No, no.

2142
02:25:24,632 --> 02:25:26,630
Two people will
only hurt each other

2143
02:25:26,699 --> 02:25:29,067
if they doubt the love
they have in one another.

2144
02:25:31,133 --> 02:25:33,131
You can read it some other time.

2145
02:25:34,699 --> 02:25:36,299
You sit down some place,

2146
02:25:36,300 --> 02:25:38,377
gaze out at the mountains.

2147
02:25:38,732 --> 02:25:40,870
It's what
the girl in my novel does.

2148
02:25:44,099 --> 02:25:45,865
<i>I'll see you later.</i>

2149
02:25:45,866 --> 02:25:47,864
I'll see you. Good news.

2150
02:25:53,699 --> 02:25:56,356
<i>Sensibly,
Grace chose to hope for the best,</i>

2151
02:25:56,799 --> 02:25:58,797
<i>rather than fear the worst,</i>

2152
02:25:58,832 --> 02:26:00,498
<i>and planned to spend the day</i>

2153
02:26:00,499 --> 02:26:02,577
<i>calmly washing her clothes
and herself...</i>

2154
02:26:02,933 --> 02:26:06,030
<i>which for some reason or another
she was sure none of the characters</i>

2155
02:26:06,532 --> 02:26:09,809
<i>from Tom's fictitious township
would dream of doing.</i>

2156
02:26:14,099 --> 02:26:17,935
<i>And then it was
as if Dogville just waited.</i>

2157
02:26:18,532 --> 02:26:20,960
<i>Even the wind dropped,</i>

2158
02:26:21,365 --> 02:26:24,173
<i>leaving the town
in an unfamiliar calm,</i>

2159
02:26:24,632 --> 02:26:29,018
<i>as if somebody had put
a large cheese-dish cover over it</i>

2160
02:26:29,699 --> 02:26:32,506
<i>and created the kind of quietness</i>

2161
02:26:32,966 --> 02:26:36,332
<i>that descends
while you're awaiting visitors.</i>

2162
02:26:36,866 --> 02:26:40,552
<i>After two days off
Grace had been put back to work,</i>

2163
02:26:41,133 --> 02:26:44,439
<i>but the quietness remained.</i>

2164
02:26:44,966 --> 02:26:47,543
<i>Indeed, it intensified.</i>

2165
02:26:47,966 --> 02:26:50,154
<i>Until on the fifth day...</i>

2166
02:26:50,532 --> 02:26:53,549
<i>it swelled into a strange mood</i>

2167
02:26:54,033 --> 02:26:57,779
<i>that all of a sudden brought all
the citizens to the street to listen.</i>

2168
02:27:00,632 --> 02:27:04,259
<i>They asked each other
if the phone was really still down,</i>

2169
02:27:04,832 --> 02:27:07,929
<i>or if they'd heard about Ben
having had to turn his truck around</i>

2170
02:27:08,432 --> 02:27:10,430
<i>on his way to Georgetown
that very morning</i>

2171
02:27:10,599 --> 02:27:13,556
<i>on account of a large tree
blocking the road.</i>

2172
02:27:14,033 --> 02:27:16,430
<i>They were not worried.</i>

2173
02:27:16,832 --> 02:27:18,910
<i>Worried was not the right word.</i>

2174
02:27:20,233 --> 02:27:22,720
<i>And then Tom spotted the cars.</i>

2175
02:27:23,133 --> 02:27:24,798
- How many cars?
- Eight, eight.

2176
02:27:24,799 --> 02:27:27,137
Tom has binoculars
but you can see them with the naked eye.

2177
02:27:27,532 --> 02:27:29,990
- There must be at least eight.
- I thought the road was blocked.

2178
02:27:30,399 --> 02:27:32,477
They must have come through
before the tree came down.

2179
02:27:35,799 --> 02:27:39,016
June's bed! The sheets need changing.
I'll be there in a minute.

2180
02:27:39,532 --> 02:27:42,220
Hello, June.

2181
02:27:44,066 --> 02:27:47,492
<i>Grace had just started on
the bed which June had soiled yet again,</i>

2182
02:27:48,033 --> 02:27:52,278
<i>when an irritating feeling of wasting
her time forced itself upon her.</i>

2183
02:27:54,432 --> 02:27:57,499
<i>And it was without thinking
she then said the words...</i>

2184
02:27:57,999 --> 02:28:00,306
Nobody gonna sleep here.

2185
02:28:05,033 --> 02:28:07,031
<i>She didn't say them out loud</i>

2186
02:28:07,265 --> 02:28:10,302
<i>but even so,
was startled by the utterance</i>

2187
02:28:10,799 --> 02:28:12,907
<i>that had urged itself upon her.</i>

2188
02:28:14,866 --> 02:28:17,583
<i>Where had these
ominous words come from?</i>

2189
02:28:27,299 --> 02:28:31,545
<i>Darkness was falling as Grace made
her way home from work that evening.</i>

2190
02:28:32,198 --> 02:28:34,826
<i>The people on the square
overlooking the valley</i>

2191
02:28:35,265 --> 02:28:39,391
<i>had finally given up hope of seeing
anything else now the light had faded.</i>

2192
02:28:40,033 --> 02:28:43,050
<i>They trudged up Elm Street
in disappointment.</i>

2193
02:28:48,198 --> 02:28:50,032
- Tom.
- Hi, Grace.

2194
02:28:50,033 --> 02:28:52,051
There were some cars, but...

2195
02:28:52,399 --> 02:28:54,397
too dark, we can't see anymore.

2196
02:28:54,732 --> 02:28:57,799
We haven't seen
much of each other.

2197
02:28:58,299 --> 02:29:00,787
Yeah, I know. I've been busy
with my book, you know.

2198
02:29:01,198 --> 02:29:03,336
<i>Can I ask you something?</i>

2199
02:29:03,699 --> 02:29:05,717
<i>Yeah, anything.</i>

2200
02:29:09,033 --> 02:29:11,430
You couldn't bring yourself
to throw it away, could you?

2201
02:29:13,899 --> 02:29:16,476
<i>The number he gave you that night,
you couldn't throw it away.</i>

2202
02:29:16,899 --> 02:29:20,325
I told you how dangerous
that man was.

2203
02:29:20,866 --> 02:29:22,864
That was stupid.

2204
02:29:28,632 --> 02:29:30,740
<i>Stupid or not, Tom was soon</i>

2205
02:29:31,099 --> 02:29:34,195
<i>a passionate spokesman for
locking Grace in her shed that night.</i>

2206
02:29:36,699 --> 02:29:39,186
<i>If the vehicles were indeed
a sign that the call</i>

2207
02:29:39,599 --> 02:29:42,526
<i>Tom had placed five days earlier
on behalf of the community</i>

2208
02:29:42,999 --> 02:29:45,746
<i>to the number indicated
on the card from his bureau drawer</i>

2209
02:29:46,198 --> 02:29:48,196
<i>had at last led to action</i>

2210
02:29:48,432 --> 02:29:51,119
<i>and Grace was now
to be eliminated from their lives,</i>

2211
02:29:51,566 --> 02:29:55,132
<i>it would surely look good
if the town had also locked her up.</i>

2212
02:29:57,766 --> 02:30:01,192
<i>Grace was lying on the bed
when Jason was sent up with the key.</i>

2213
02:30:01,732 --> 02:30:03,980
<i>Grace heard it turn in the lock,</i>

2214
02:30:04,365 --> 02:30:07,522
<i>but she was deeply absorbed
by arguments and thoughts</i>

2215
02:30:08,033 --> 02:30:12,218
<i>on matters she had otherwise avoided
for the best part of a year now.</i>

2216
02:30:20,633 --> 02:30:27,967
CHAPTER NINE in which Dogville receives
the long-awaited visit and the film ends.

2217
02:30:31,632 --> 02:30:34,349
<i>From the moment when they'd finally
heard the sound of vehicles</i>

2218
02:30:34,799 --> 02:30:37,756
<i>starting one after the other from
the direction of the edge of the woods,</i>

2219
02:30:38,232 --> 02:30:40,340
<i>things had moved rapidly.</i>

2220
02:30:40,699 --> 02:30:44,645
<i>Tom had arranged a delegation
to provide a proper reception.</i>

2221
02:30:45,265 --> 02:30:50,360
<i>Dogville might be off the beaten track,
but it was hospitable, nonetheless.</i>

2222
02:31:04,132 --> 02:31:06,097
Welcome, gentlemen, welcome.

2223
02:31:06,098 --> 02:31:08,316
The town places itself
at your disposal.

2224
02:31:08,699 --> 02:31:11,716
I should have a large key to give you,
but I only have this small one.

2225
02:31:12,198 --> 02:31:14,196
- Where is she?
- Secured by this very key.

2226
02:31:14,365 --> 02:31:15,932
Where is she?

2227
02:31:15,933 --> 02:31:19,269
Okay... if you're wondering
about that sound,

2228
02:31:19,799 --> 02:31:22,516
they're driving piles
for the new penitentiary.

2229
02:31:22,966 --> 02:31:25,713
Tell me, has the crime rate
really gone up in this country

2230
02:31:26,165 --> 02:31:28,163
as we're led to believe?

2231
02:31:28,198 --> 02:31:31,265
Maybe people just regard
things as criminal because,

2232
02:31:31,766 --> 02:31:34,223
because they envy their success.

2233
02:31:34,632 --> 02:31:37,319
What's your opinion
on the subject?

2234
02:31:38,766 --> 02:31:41,423
Maybe you have none.
I'll get the door.

2235
02:31:41,866 --> 02:31:43,974
<i>-</i> Sorry.

2236
02:31:46,165 --> 02:31:48,243
Voila, as the French might say.

2237
02:31:48,599 --> 02:31:51,026
What the hell is this?

2238
02:31:51,432 --> 02:31:52,531
Who did that?

2239
02:31:52,532 --> 02:31:55,399
Billy, put your hand up!
Put your hand up!

2240
02:31:55,866 --> 02:31:57,798
Who's Billy? Come on,
just get your tools.

2241
02:31:57,799 --> 02:31:59,907
- It's okay.
- It's gonna be all right.

2242
02:32:04,499 --> 02:32:06,497
We felt safer
when she had the chain on.

2243
02:32:06,699 --> 02:32:09,686
You're probably more adept
at handling her kind.

2244
02:32:11,399 --> 02:32:13,976
None of us feel able

2245
02:32:14,399 --> 02:32:16,397
to accept money
for just helping people.

2246
02:32:16,699 --> 02:32:21,054
I mean, unless it would make you feel
better to divest yourself...

2247
02:32:21,732 --> 02:32:23,730
- Shut the hell up!
- Absolutely.

2248
02:32:28,699 --> 02:32:31,916
<i>Grace was no expert
in exclusive automobiles,</i>

2249
02:32:32,432 --> 02:32:34,890
<i>yet she recognized
with no difficulty</i>

2250
02:32:35,299 --> 02:32:37,697
<i>the sound of the vehicle
that was rounding the corner</i>

2251
02:32:38,098 --> 02:32:40,376
<i>from Canyon Road
at that very moment.</i>

2252
02:32:41,766 --> 02:32:43,764
<i>Alas, in Grace's memory</i>

2253
02:32:43,998 --> 02:32:47,655
<i>the legendary purr
of the Cadillac series 355 C</i>

2254
02:32:48,232 --> 02:32:52,828
<i>was inextricably linked with another
rather less sophisticated sound...</i>

2255
02:32:53,532 --> 02:32:56,719
<i>that of gunfire
directed against her person.</i>

2256
02:33:21,232 --> 02:33:23,230
Don't!

2257
02:33:46,965 --> 02:33:50,442
You need to justify your actions
before you shoot us?

2258
02:33:52,499 --> 02:33:54,497
That's new.

2259
02:33:58,465 --> 02:34:00,463
That could be interpreted
as weakness, Daddy.

2260
02:34:00,732 --> 02:34:03,099
<i>I'm disappointed in you.</i>

2261
02:34:03,499 --> 02:34:06,806
- I didn't come to shoot anybody.
<i>- You shot at me before.</i>

2262
02:34:07,332 --> 02:34:09,330
<i>Yes.</i>

2263
02:34:10,865 --> 02:34:13,173
<i>And so I regret that...</i>

2264
02:34:13,566 --> 02:34:15,564
<i>you ran away.</i>

2265
02:34:15,799 --> 02:34:19,695
But shooting at you
certainly didn't help matters.

2266
02:34:20,299 --> 02:34:22,547
Of course not,
you're far, far too stubborn.

2267
02:34:26,332 --> 02:34:28,500
If you don't want to kill me
then why did you come?

2268
02:34:28,865 --> 02:34:31,643
Our last conversation,
the one in which you told me what it was

2269
02:34:32,098 --> 02:34:36,074
you didn't like about me,
never really concluded, as you ran away.

2270
02:34:36,699 --> 02:34:39,885
I should be allowed to tell you
what I don't like about you.

2271
02:34:40,399 --> 02:34:45,194
That, I believe, would be a rule
of polite conversation, no?

2272
02:34:45,932 --> 02:34:47,930
That's why you showed up?

2273
02:34:51,332 --> 02:34:53,700
And you call <i>me</i> stubborn?

2274
02:34:54,098 --> 02:34:58,014
You're sure you're not here to force me
to go back and become like you?

2275
02:34:58,632 --> 02:35:00,849
If I thought there was
a chance of forcing you...

2276
02:35:01,232 --> 02:35:04,419
but of course,
that would never happen.

2277
02:35:04,932 --> 02:35:08,179
You're more... more than welcome

2278
02:35:08,699 --> 02:35:12,824
to return home,
become my daughter again anytime,

2279
02:35:13,465 --> 02:35:16,971
and I would even begin

2280
02:35:17,532 --> 02:35:22,747
<i>to share my power and responsibility
with you if you did.</i>

2281
02:35:23,532 --> 02:35:27,887
- Not that you care...
- So what is it?

2282
02:35:28,566 --> 02:35:31,373
What is it, the thing, the thing
that you don't like about me?

2283
02:35:31,831 --> 02:35:34,079
It was a word you used
that provoked me.

2284
02:35:34,465 --> 02:35:36,513
You called me arrogant.

2285
02:35:36,865 --> 02:35:40,052
To plunder, as it were, a God-given
right. I'd call that arrogant, Daddy.

2286
02:35:40,566 --> 02:35:43,752
But that is exactly
what I don't like about you.

2287
02:35:44,265 --> 02:35:47,422
- It's <i>you</i> that is arrogant.
- That's what you came here to say?

2288
02:35:51,632 --> 02:35:55,168
I'm not the one passing judgment, Daddy,
<i>you</i> are.

2289
02:35:55,732 --> 02:35:58,449
No, <i>you</i> do not pass judgment

2290
02:35:58,898 --> 02:36:02,525
because you sympathize with them.
A deprived childhood,

2291
02:36:03,098 --> 02:36:07,284
and a homicide really isn't
necessarily a homicide, right?

2292
02:36:07,932 --> 02:36:10,739
The only thing you can blame
is circumstances...

2293
02:36:11,198 --> 02:36:13,626
rapists and murderers

2294
02:36:14,032 --> 02:36:15,964
may be the victims,
according to you,

2295
02:36:15,965 --> 02:36:18,573
but I, I call them dogs.

2296
02:36:18,998 --> 02:36:20,996
And if they're lapping up
their own vomit,

2297
02:36:21,265 --> 02:36:23,263
the only way to stop them
is with the lash.

2298
02:36:23,465 --> 02:36:25,463
But dogs only obey
their own nature,

2299
02:36:25,731 --> 02:36:27,779
so why shouldn't we forgive them?

2300
02:36:28,132 --> 02:36:31,409
Dogs can be taught
many useful things,

2301
02:36:31,932 --> 02:36:35,848
but not if we forgive them
every time they obey their own nature.

2302
02:36:48,465 --> 02:36:50,463
So I'm arrogant?

2303
02:36:50,666 --> 02:36:53,033
I'm arrogant
because I forgive people.

2304
02:36:53,432 --> 02:36:55,430
My God,

2305
02:36:55,465 --> 02:36:58,422
can't you see how condescending
you are when you say that?

2306
02:36:59,865 --> 02:37:03,322
I mean you have...
you have this preconceived notion

2307
02:37:03,865 --> 02:37:07,781
that nobody, listen... that nobody
can possibly attain

2308
02:37:08,399 --> 02:37:12,205
the same high ethical standards as you,
so you exonerate them.

2309
02:37:12,798 --> 02:37:14,431
I cannot...

2310
02:37:14,432 --> 02:37:17,449
I cannot think of anything
more arrogant than that.

2311
02:37:17,932 --> 02:37:20,969
You, my child, my dear child,

2312
02:37:21,465 --> 02:37:23,603
you forgive others with excuses

2313
02:37:23,965 --> 02:37:26,333
that you would never in the world
permit for yourself.

2314
02:37:26,731 --> 02:37:29,309
Why shouldn't I be merciful? Why?

2315
02:37:29,731 --> 02:37:32,449
<i>No, no, no, you should,
you should be merciful</i>

2316
02:37:32,898 --> 02:37:35,086
<i>when there's time to be merciful.</i>

2317
02:37:35,465 --> 02:37:37,463
But, you must maintain
your own standards.

2318
02:37:37,765 --> 02:37:40,633
You owe them that,
you owe them that.

2319
02:37:41,098 --> 02:37:44,664
The penalty you deserve
for your transgression,

2320
02:37:45,232 --> 02:37:47,230
they deserve
for their transgressions.

2321
02:37:47,532 --> 02:37:49,809
- They're human beings, Dad.
- No, no, no, of course...

2322
02:37:50,198 --> 02:37:53,155
<i>but does every human being need to be
accountable for their actions?</i>

2323
02:37:53,631 --> 02:37:56,119
Of course they do, but you
don't even give them that chance.

2324
02:37:56,532 --> 02:37:58,869
And that is extremely arrogant.

2325
02:37:59,265 --> 02:38:02,332
I love you, I love you,
I love you to death,

2326
02:38:02,831 --> 02:38:06,228
but you are the most arrogant
person I have ever met.

2327
02:38:06,765 --> 02:38:09,223
And you call me arrogant.

2328
02:38:13,198 --> 02:38:15,196
I...

2329
02:38:15,399 --> 02:38:17,676
I have no more to say.

2330
02:38:19,731 --> 02:38:22,888
You're arrogant, I'm arrogant,
you've said it, now you can leave.

2331
02:38:23,399 --> 02:38:25,946
And without my daughter I suppose.

2332
02:38:32,731 --> 02:38:34,919
- I said without my daughter.
- Yes.

2333
02:38:36,665 --> 02:38:39,033
<i>- Well?</i>
- Yes!

2334
02:38:39,432 --> 02:38:41,480
You decide, you decide.

2335
02:38:44,798 --> 02:38:46,697
Grace, they...

2336
02:38:46,698 --> 02:38:48,776
they say you're having
some trouble here.

2337
02:38:50,332 --> 02:38:52,330
No.

2338
02:38:52,565 --> 02:38:54,673
No more trouble than back home.

2339
02:38:55,032 --> 02:38:57,340
I'm gonna give you a little time
to think about this,

2340
02:38:57,731 --> 02:39:00,598
<i>- perhaps you'll change your mind.</i>
- I won't.

2341
02:39:01,065 --> 02:39:03,063
<i>Listen, my love,</i>

2342
02:39:03,365 --> 02:39:05,582
<i>power is not so bad.</i>

2343
02:39:05,965 --> 02:39:08,982
I am sure that you can

2344
02:39:09,465 --> 02:39:12,092
find a way to make use of it
in your own fashion.

2345
02:39:15,265 --> 02:39:17,842
Take a walk and think about it.

2346
02:39:18,265 --> 02:39:20,263
The people who live here...

2347
02:39:22,132 --> 02:39:24,130
are doing their best

2348
02:39:24,332 --> 02:39:28,338
under very hard circumstances.

2349
02:39:28,965 --> 02:39:30,963
If you say so, Grace.

2350
02:39:33,332 --> 02:39:35,989
<i>But is their best...</i>

2351
02:39:38,365 --> 02:39:40,363
<i>really good enough?</i>

2352
02:39:41,798 --> 02:39:43,796
I do love you.

2353
02:39:53,831 --> 02:39:56,758
<i>Grace had already
thought for a long time.</i>

2354
02:39:57,232 --> 02:40:00,688
<i>She had known that if she were not shot
when the gangsters arrived,</i>

2355
02:40:01,232 --> 02:40:04,069
<i>she would be faced with her father's
suggestion that she return</i>

2356
02:40:04,531 --> 02:40:07,518
<i>to be become a conspirator with him
and his gang of thugs and felons.</i>

2357
02:40:07,998 --> 02:40:11,455
<i>And she did not need any walk
to reconsider her response to that...</i>

2358
02:40:13,299 --> 02:40:15,986
<i>even though the difference
between the people she knew back home</i>

2359
02:40:16,432 --> 02:40:18,430
<i>and the people she'd met in Dogville</i>

2360
02:40:18,731 --> 02:40:21,538
<i>had proven somewhat slighter
than she'd expected.</i>

2361
02:40:23,965 --> 02:40:27,422
<i>Grace looked at the gooseberry bushes,
so fragile in the smooth darkness.</i>

2362
02:40:28,965 --> 02:40:32,002
<i>It was good to know that
if you did not treat them ill,</i>

2363
02:40:32,498 --> 02:40:35,016
<i>they would be there come spring
as always,</i>

2364
02:40:35,432 --> 02:40:37,619
<i>and come summer
they'd again be bursting</i>

2365
02:40:37,998 --> 02:40:40,655
<i>with the quite incomprehensible
quantity of berries</i>

2366
02:40:41,098 --> 02:40:43,346
<i>that were so good in pies,</i>

2367
02:40:43,731 --> 02:40:45,729
<i>especially with cinnamon.</i>

2368
02:40:45,932 --> 02:40:48,709
<i>Grace looked around
at the frightened faces</i>

2369
02:40:49,165 --> 02:40:52,382
<i>behind the windowpanes
that were following her every step</i>

2370
02:40:52,898 --> 02:40:56,055
<i>and felt ashamed
of being part of inflicting that fear.</i>

2371
02:40:58,365 --> 02:41:00,363
<i>How could she ever hate them</i>

2372
02:41:00,432 --> 02:41:03,269
<i>for what was at bottom
merely their weakness?</i>

2373
02:41:03,731 --> 02:41:07,008
<i>She would probably have done
things like those that have befallen her</i>

2374
02:41:07,531 --> 02:41:09,609
<i>if she had lived
in one of these houses.</i>

2375
02:41:09,965 --> 02:41:13,501
<i>To measure them by her own yardstick,
as her father put it,</i>

2376
02:41:14,065 --> 02:41:16,063
<i>would she not, in all honesty,</i>

2377
02:41:16,399 --> 02:41:18,397
<i>have done the same as Chuck?</i>

2378
02:41:18,598 --> 02:41:21,555
<i>And Vera and Ben? And Mrs. Henson?</i>

2379
02:41:23,032 --> 02:41:26,129
<i>And Tom?
And all these people in their houses?</i>

2380
02:41:30,731 --> 02:41:32,729
<i>Grace paused.</i>

2381
02:41:32,865 --> 02:41:34,973
<i>And while she did,</i>

2382
02:41:35,332 --> 02:41:38,109
<i>the clouds scattered
and let the moonlight through.</i>

2383
02:41:45,965 --> 02:41:49,152
<i>And Dogville underwent another
of those little changes of light.</i>

2384
02:42:03,565 --> 02:42:06,632
<i>It was as if the light previously
so merciful and faint,</i>

2385
02:42:07,132 --> 02:42:10,528
<i>finally refused to cover up
for the town any longer.</i>

2386
02:42:12,032 --> 02:42:14,579
<i>Suddenly you could
no longer imagine a berry</i>

2387
02:42:14,998 --> 02:42:17,186
<i>that would appear one day
on a gooseberry bush,</i>

2388
02:42:17,565 --> 02:42:20,223
<i>but only see the thorn
that was there right now.</i>

2389
02:42:21,798 --> 02:42:25,664
<i>The light now penetrated every
unevenness and flaw in the buildings,</i>

2390
02:42:26,265 --> 02:42:28,782
<i>and in the people.</i>

2391
02:42:32,265 --> 02:42:35,921
<i>And all of a sudden, she knew
the answer to her question all too well.</i>

2392
02:42:38,531 --> 02:42:40,529
<i>If she had acted like them</i>

2393
02:42:40,865 --> 02:42:44,142
<i>she could not have defended
a single one of her actions</i>

2394
02:42:44,665 --> 02:42:47,562
<i>and could not have condemned
them harshly enough.</i>

2395
02:42:48,032 --> 02:42:53,127
<i>It was as if her sorrow and pain
finally assumed their rightful place.</i>

2396
02:42:54,865 --> 02:42:58,262
<i>No, what they had done
was not good enough.</i>

2397
02:43:00,132 --> 02:43:04,228
<i>And if one had the power to put it
to rights, it was one's duty to do so,</i>

2398
02:43:04,865 --> 02:43:06,863
<i>for the sake of other towns,</i>

2399
02:43:07,132 --> 02:43:09,499
<i>for the sake of humanity</i>

2400
02:43:09,898 --> 02:43:13,055
<i>and not least,
for the sake of the human being</i>

2401
02:43:13,565 --> 02:43:16,143
<i>that was Grace herself.</i>

2402
02:43:24,464 --> 02:43:26,462
If I went back and...

2403
02:43:28,132 --> 02:43:30,130
became your daughter again,

2404
02:43:30,364 --> 02:43:33,401
when would I be given
the power you're talking about?

2405
02:43:37,398 --> 02:43:39,264
Now.

2406
02:43:39,265 --> 02:43:41,372
At once?

2407
02:43:41,731 --> 02:43:43,729
<i>Why not?</i>

2408
02:43:48,531 --> 02:43:50,669
So that would mean
that I would also take on

2409
02:43:51,032 --> 02:43:53,809
the immediate responsibility,
at once.

2410
02:43:55,232 --> 02:43:57,230
And I'd be a part
of the problem solving...

2411
02:43:58,898 --> 02:44:00,896
like the problem

2412
02:44:01,065 --> 02:44:03,063
<i>of Dogville.</i>

2413
02:44:08,731 --> 02:44:11,189
We could start by shooting the dog

2414
02:44:11,598 --> 02:44:14,405
and nailing it to a wall over there,

2415
02:44:14,865 --> 02:44:17,203
beneath that lamp for example.

2416
02:44:18,798 --> 02:44:20,876
It might help,
it sometimes does, no?

2417
02:44:21,232 --> 02:44:23,689
It would only make the town
more frightened,

2418
02:44:24,098 --> 02:44:26,675
it would hardly make it
a better place.

2419
02:44:28,865 --> 02:44:30,863
And it could happen again.

2420
02:44:32,098 --> 02:44:34,096
Somebody...

2421
02:44:34,165 --> 02:44:36,352
somebody happening by,
revealing...

2422
02:44:41,798 --> 02:44:43,796
their frailty.

2423
02:44:48,065 --> 02:44:50,722
<i>That's what I want to use
the power for, if you don't mind.</i>

2424
02:44:55,132 --> 02:44:57,999
I want to make this world
a little better.

2425
02:45:01,364 --> 02:45:03,502
Yeah?

2426
02:45:03,865 --> 02:45:07,261
The damn kid won't shut up.
Says he wants to talk to you, miss.

2427
02:45:07,798 --> 02:45:09,876
<i>Can we just shoot him now?</i>

2428
02:45:10,231 --> 02:45:12,399
No, let me talk to him.

2429
02:45:17,231 --> 02:45:19,279
What? What is it?

2430
02:45:21,865 --> 02:45:24,053
A man can't really be blamed

2431
02:45:24,431 --> 02:45:26,397
for being scared, can he?

2432
02:45:26,398 --> 02:45:28,826
- No...
<i>- No.</i>

2433
02:45:29,231 --> 02:45:31,229
I'm scared, Grace.

2434
02:45:31,298 --> 02:45:34,016
<i>I used you and I am sorry.</i>

2435
02:45:34,464 --> 02:45:36,064
I am stupid. I am.

2436
02:45:36,065 --> 02:45:38,342
I'm maybe even arrogant sometimes.

2437
02:45:41,098 --> 02:45:43,146
You are, Tom.

2438
02:45:44,531 --> 02:45:47,928
Although using people
is not very charming,

2439
02:45:48,464 --> 02:45:51,591
I think you have to agree
that this specific illustration

2440
02:45:52,098 --> 02:45:54,205
<i>has surpassed all expectations.</i>

2441
02:45:54,565 --> 02:45:56,563
It says so much about being human.

2442
02:45:56,898 --> 02:45:59,585
It's been painful, but I think
you'll also have to agree

2443
02:46:00,032 --> 02:46:02,959
- it's been edifying, wouldn't you say?
- Not now, Tom.

2444
02:46:03,431 --> 02:46:05,429
Not now.

2445
02:46:09,798 --> 02:46:12,865
If there's any town this world
would be better without, this is it.

2446
02:46:19,298 --> 02:46:21,636
- <i>Yes?</i>
- Shoot them, burn down the town.

2447
02:46:26,965 --> 02:46:29,542
What? Something else, honey?

2448
02:46:30,965 --> 02:46:32,963
There's a family with kids.

2449
02:46:36,197 --> 02:46:38,715
Do the kids first
and make the mother watch.

2450
02:46:39,131 --> 02:46:42,558
Tell her you'll stop
if she can hold back her tears.

2451
02:46:47,364 --> 02:46:49,362
I owe her that.

2452
02:46:56,131 --> 02:46:58,849
I'm afraid she cries
a little too easily.

2453
02:47:01,731 --> 02:47:03,729
We'd better get you out of here.

2454
02:47:05,197 --> 02:47:07,505
I'm afraid you've learned
far too much already.

2455
02:47:11,464 --> 02:47:13,462
Come on, come on.

2456
02:47:15,364 --> 02:47:18,081
<i>Feeling cold, sweetie?
Would you like a wrap?</i>

2457
02:47:19,531 --> 02:47:21,197
<i>I'm fine.</i>

2458
02:47:24,032 --> 02:47:26,519
You want the curtains opened?
You don't need them anymore.

2459
02:47:28,197 --> 02:47:30,195
You think?

2460
02:47:35,464 --> 02:47:37,462
I think we should open them.

2461
02:47:39,531 --> 02:47:41,529
I think it's appropriate.

2462
02:47:58,998 --> 02:48:00,996
No!

2463
02:48:01,865 --> 02:48:03,863
- <i>No! No!</i>
- No, no.

2464
02:48:04,197 --> 02:48:06,195
No, No.

2465
02:48:10,965 --> 02:48:12,963
No!

2466
02:48:13,765 --> 02:48:15,763
- No, Dad, no.
- No.

2467
02:48:15,932 --> 02:48:17,930
<i>Dad!</i>

2468
02:48:22,264 --> 02:48:24,262
Chuck!

2469
02:48:28,031 --> 02:48:30,029
Mom!

2470
02:48:30,364 --> 02:48:32,552
<i>Mom, help, help!</i>

2471
02:48:33,965 --> 02:48:35,963
Mom!

2472
02:48:50,831 --> 02:48:52,564
Stay, Achilles.

2473
02:48:52,565 --> 02:48:55,342
Dear God.

2474
02:48:58,798 --> 02:49:01,755
<i>No! Oh god!</i>

2475
02:49:38,398 --> 02:49:40,416
Bingo, Grace.

2476
02:49:42,865 --> 02:49:44,863
Bingo.

2477
02:49:46,364 --> 02:49:49,461
I have to tell you, your illustration,
it beat the hell out of mine.

2478
02:49:52,565 --> 02:49:54,753
It's frightening, yes,

2479
02:49:55,131 --> 02:49:57,129
but so clear.

2480
02:49:58,464 --> 02:50:00,462
<i>Do you think I can
allow myself to use it</i>

2481
02:50:00,731 --> 02:50:03,448
as an inspiration in my writing?

2482
02:50:13,665 --> 02:50:15,663
Goodbye, Tom.

2483
02:50:41,565 --> 02:50:43,753
Some things
you have to do yourself.

2484
02:50:45,097 --> 02:50:47,095
Really?

2485
02:50:50,097 --> 02:50:52,405
That one you're gonna have
to explain to me on the way home.

2486
02:50:53,765 --> 02:50:56,542
<i>Suddenly there was a noise...</i>

2487
02:50:56,997 --> 02:51:00,744
<i>not so persuasive and powerful as it
had been on one rainy night in spring,</i>

2488
02:51:01,331 --> 02:51:04,518
<i>but loud enough to work its way
through the final sighs of the timber</i>

2489
02:51:05,031 --> 02:51:08,398
<i>that was rapidly burning out.</i>

2490
02:51:08,931 --> 02:51:11,948
<i>It came again, everyone heard it.</i>

2491
02:51:12,431 --> 02:51:15,498
<i>- Grace was the first to recognize it.</i>
- That's Moses.

2492
02:51:15,997 --> 02:51:18,685
<i>"That's Moses," she said
and jumped out of the car.</i>

2493
02:51:20,131 --> 02:51:22,908
<i>She quickly covered the distance
to the dog pen through what,</i>

2494
02:51:23,364 --> 02:51:26,521
<i>now the buildings were gone,
could scarcely be called a street,</i>

2495
02:51:27,031 --> 02:51:29,868
<i>and certainly not Elm Street,
as there wasn't a tree left</i>

2496
02:51:30,331 --> 02:51:33,318
<i>on Dogville's little mountain ledge,
let alone an elm.</i>

2497
02:51:33,798 --> 02:51:35,905
<i>It was Moses.</i>

2498
02:51:36,264 --> 02:51:38,632
<i>His survival was astonishing,
a miracle.</i>

2499
02:51:40,031 --> 02:51:41,963
No, no.

2500
02:51:41,964 --> 02:51:44,042
No, just let him be.

2501
02:51:44,398 --> 02:51:47,705
<i>They will have spotted the flames
in Georgetown by now.</i>

2502
02:51:48,231 --> 02:51:50,599
Someone will come and find him.

2503
02:51:56,131 --> 02:51:58,559
He's just angry
because I once took his bone.

2504
02:52:10,231 --> 02:52:12,196
<i>Whether Grace left Dogville,</i>

2505
02:52:12,197 --> 02:52:14,745
<i>or on the contrary
Dogville had left her...</i>

2506
02:52:15,164 --> 02:52:16,763
<i>and the world in general...</i>

2507
02:52:16,764 --> 02:52:18,812
<i>is a question
of a more artful nature</i>

2508
02:52:19,164 --> 02:52:21,791
<i>that few would
benefit from by asking,</i>

2509
02:52:22,231 --> 02:52:24,399
<i>and even fewer
by providing an answer.</i>

2510
02:52:24,764 --> 02:52:27,482
<i>And nor indeed
will it be answered here.</i>

